<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LILCOTrial     12-05 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LILCO Trial,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Says LILCO Lied To PSC To Get Rate Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury Monday awarded Suffolk County
$22.8 million in damages from Long Island Lighting Co., finding that
LILCO and a former executive repeatedly lied to get rate hikes to
help pay for its Shoreham nuclear power plant.
   The verdict, following a two-month trial of the county's civil
racketeering lawsuit against the utility, could make LILCO liable
for $1.8 billion if the trial judge certifies the lawsuit a class
action on behalf of all ratepayers.
   The utility, through its attorney Michael Lesch, issued a
one-sentence statement that said the verdict was ``insupportable''
and that LILCO would seek to set it aside or reverse it on appeal.
   The seven-member jury found that LILCO and a former president,
Wilfred O. Uhl, on three occassions lied to the Public Service
Commission about the completion schedule of Shoreham in order to
obtain rate hikes.
   The jury awarded $7.6 million in damages to the county for what
it overpaid on utility costs because of fraudulently obtained rate
increases in 1978 and 1984, tripled to $22.8 million under the
racketeering statue.
   The county had sought up to $72 million in damages.
   The jury rejected the county's charges that LILCO deceived the
PSC in obtaining other rate increases in 1975, 1976, 1979 and 1981.
   It also found no violations by three other former LILCO officials
who were defendants.
   ``I think the jury spoke loud and clearly that LILCO had been
engaging in a pattern of fraud for a decade,'' said Kenneth
McCallion, who was the county's lead attorney during the two-month
trial.
   Last week in Albany, the state Legislature let pass by a deadline
for approving a plan that would keep Shoreham closed and give LILCO
5 percent annual rate hikes over the next decade.
   LILCO has said that while the plan could be revived, it would
proceed toward licensing the plant.
   Suffolk County Executive Patrick Halpin called the verdict ``a
great victory for the county and Suffolk's ratepayers.''
   According to testimony at the trial, the Shoreham plant, which is
located 55 miles east of Manhattan, had originally been scheduled to
be in operation in 1978 at a cost of $77 million. Construction was
completed in 1985, but the plant was never opened because of public
opposition.
   The county alleged that LILCO spent $8 billion in the
construction of Shoreham, but LILCO says the plant cost $5.3 billion.
   Originally, the county had wanted to make the suit a class action
on behalf of all LILCO customers, but U.S. District Judge Jack B.
Weinstein limited the scope of the suit before the trial started.
   After the verdict, Weinstein said he would now accept a motion
asking him to certify the class and indicated that if he granted the
request, LILCO could be liable for up to $1.8 billion.
   ``This will have a significant impact on the financial health of
LILCO,'' Weinstein said.
   Lesch, the LILCO attorney, answered, ``It certainly will.''
   One of the jurors, Norma Spagna of Queens, said the jurors had
not believed Uhl, who was one of 21 witnesses who testified for
LILCO.
   ``I think he lied on the stand,'' said Spagna.
   Uhl, who was president of LILCO from 1978 to 1984, had denied
that he lied to state officials about when the construction of
Shoreham would be completed.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
