<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PlaneSit-in     12-05 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Sit-in,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disgruntled Passengers Occupy Plane for Eight Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers angered by two days of flight delays
staged an eight-hour sit-in inside a jetliner of China's
trouble-plagued national airlines, an official newspaper reported
today.
   The China Daily said 120 Chinese passengers refused to get off a
plane scheduled to fly from Beijing's Capital Airport to the
southwestern city of Chungking after being told just before takeoff
of another delay due to fog in Chungking.
   The ``chaotic scenes'' at the airport on Sunday came several days
after Hu Yizhou, director-general of the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC), the state-run airlines, told an
emergency meeting ``effective measures'' were being taken to improve
the airlines' poor service record.
   The meeting was held because of rising complaints from Chinese
and foreign passengers about CAAC service, notably frequent flight
delays, overbooking, refusal to provide information about flights
and indifferent in-flight service.
   The daily said the flight to Chungking originally scheduled for
Saturday was canceled because of fog in the Sichuan province city
and ticket holders had been put in an airport hostel with no heat or
electricity.
   The flight was rescheduled for Sunday, and the plane had taxied
to the runway for takeoff when it was decided that Chungking was
still too foggy for a landing. A few Chinese and foreign passengers
left the plane when it returned to the terminal, but 120 Chinese
passengers refused.
   Airport officials denied a report in the Beijing Evening News on
Monday that they were rude to the passengers and cut off the plane's
electricity and heating systems when the passengers refused to
disembark.
   Officials said they decided to use the same Boeing 737 for a
flight Sunday to the Sichuan provincial capital of Chengdu, but that
flight too was canceled because of the sit-in.
   Airport official Zhang Zuochang said today that the Chungking
airport remained closed by heavy fog. He said some of the protesters
had given up and returned their tickets, while others took a Monday
flight to Chengdu, 170 from Chungking.
</TEXT>
