<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sicily-Strike     12-05 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sicily-Strike,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Strike-Bound Palermo, `It's Forbidden to Be Born or to Die'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-week-old strike by city employees of
Palermo has left the morgue full, newborns unable to leave the
hospital and traffic more hopeless than ever.
   ``Agony of Palermo: Here it's forbidden to be born or to die,''
read the headline on the front-page Sunday of La Repubblica, a
nationwide daily.
   Among the striking city employees were gravediggers, traffic
police, school janitors and clerks in the office that gives out
birth certificates.
   Italian news accounts said bodies in coffins were being stacked
in the morgue during the strike.
   The Palermo correspondent of Il Giornale, a Milan newspaper,
reported that one day last week police had to be called to break up
an angry crowd of fathers who wanted to register the births of their
new sons and daughters but who found the office barred because the
clerks were striking.
   The birth certificate problem is more than one for the records
because Italian law forbids the discharge of a newborn from a
hospital without one, La Repubblica noted.
   With garbage piling up and bathrooms uncleaned, schools have been
forced to close.
   The strike centered over how to distribute back pay tied to
seniority, which must be awarded according to a recently made
contract. A court ruled the payments should come in installments
over a 24-month period, but employees want it paid over a 12-month
period.
   To protest the stalemate, six union officials chained themselves
to each other and were refusing to budge from two sofas in the
waiting room just outside Mayor Leoluca Orlando's office in city
hall.
   The unionists on Friday began a liquid-only fast and vowed to
stick it out until the workers get their way.
   The mayor has pointed out that it might take some time for a
settlement. The city council on Saturday night approved the
12-installment plan, but Orlando was quoted as saying the scheme
needs the approval of a provincial control commission that is not
scheduled to meet for several weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
