<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrownConcert     12-05 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown Concert,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 400 Turn Out For James Brown Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Brown sang to about 400 people Sunday
during a ``Wrestle-Rock '88'' concert and wrestling show staged in
part to fufill terms of his probation from South Carolina.
   Brown's spokesmen had said prior to the concert that it was
costing the singer, known as ``The Godfather of Soul,'' about
$40,000 to stage the event.
   Appearing at a charity event was a condition of the probation
Brown received in May. He had pleaded guilty to charges of carrying
a pistol and resisting arrest and pleading no contest to a charge of
possession of the hallucinogen PCP near his home in Beech Island,
S.C.
   Tickets were $10. On Thursday, officials at the Augusta-Richmond
Civic Center said just 41 tickets had been sold; it could not be
immediately determined Sunday night how many of the estimated 400 in
the audience had bought tickets and how many were guests.
   The civic center can seat up to 7,500 people for such a concert.
   ``The thought was the message,'' Brown said Sunday. ``The turnout
didn't bother me.''
   But he added that if he ever did another benefit show, he would
concentrate more on being ``advertised, not criticized.''
   Proceeds from the benefit were to go to the Aiken, S.C.,
Fraternal Order of Police, a society that helps abused children, and
leukemia research.
</TEXT>
