<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Martin, McGee, Maher obits; AMs separate on Paychek moved
on sports wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Johnny Paychek</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former boxer Johnny Paychek, who once fought Joe
Louis for the world heavyweight championship, died Saturday in a
suburban hospital at age 74.
   Paychek, who also fought under the names Paycheck and Pacek,
began his boxing career on Chicago's South Side and won the Golden
Gloves heavyweight title in 1933.
   Paychek quit the ring in 1936 and moved to Des Moines, Iowa, but
he resumed his boxing career there the same year.
   By 1940, he earned a title bout against Louis, who knocked him
out in the second round on March 29 at New York's Madison Square
Garden. After another defeat nine months later, Paychek quit the
ring for good.
   In recent years, he held several coaching jobs in Lyons Township.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Terrell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLAREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Upton Terrell, author of more than
40 books and a historian of the Old West, died of a heart attack
Thursday. He was 87.
   A Chicago native, Terrell spent time as a youth on his uncle's
ranch in Montana. He ran away from home in his teens to become a
cowboy and got work as a ranch hand. He later wrote for the San
Francisco Chronicle and United Press and covered World War II for
Newsweek.
   His books about the West included ``Life Among the Apaches,'
``The Arrow and the Cross: A History of the American Indian and the
Missionaries,'' ``Furs by Astor'' and ``Faint the Trumpet Sounds''
with coauthor George Walton.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Donald Tavel</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald L. Tavel, a pioneer in computerized
music and art, died Saturday from injuries suffered in a Nov. 28
automobile accident.
   Tavel, 36, received the first-ever master of music degree from
the Indiana University Center for Electronic and Computer Music in
1976.
   He also founded a computer graphics and animation department at
IU and taught computer music courses at Indiana Unviersity-Purdue
University at Indianapolis. He held several patents on computer
hardware and programs.
   He owned Donte Inc., which created animations for radio and
television stations, MTV and advertising, and was vice president in
charge of marketing for Premium Optical Co., owned by his brother,
Dr. David Tavel.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Maher</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Maher, a child heroin addict who went
on to found the Delancey Street drug recovery program, died
Saturday. He was 48.
   Maher had a history of heart trouble and suffered several heart
attacks in recent years, but no cause of death was immediately
established.
   Maher often said he became a social leader because he ``failed as
a bum.'' His Delancey Street Foundation, founded in San Francisco in
1971, has branches from California to New York.
   For 14 years, he led the program but a drunken driving arrest
forced him to resign from Delancey Street in 1985. He moved back to
New York, working as a construction worker and moving frequently.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>J. Vernon McGee</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEMPLETON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. J. Vernon McGee, whose ``Thru
the Bible'' series was heard on 600 radio stations in the United
States and overseas, died Thursday. He was 84.
   McGee, ordained a Presbyterian minister in 1933, served churches
in Nashville, Tenn., Cleburne, Texas, and Pasadena before moving in
1949 to the nondenominational Church of the Open Door, famous for
its ``Jesus Saves'' neon sign.
   He broke with the Presbyterian Church in 1955, saying its
``liberal leadership has taken over the machinery of the presbytery
with a boldness and ruthlessness that is appalling.'' He launched
the radio program in 1967.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Nino Martin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nino J. Martin, an award-winning television
producer-director and host of Hawaii Public Television's ``The
International Kitchen,'' died Sunday after a long illness. He was 51.
   Martin joined KHET in 1970 and eventually became the executive
producer of the station's Culture and Arts Division.
   Martin came to Honolulu in 1969 to work as a producer-director at
KGMB-TV. Prior to that, he worked as a producer at KBHK-TV in San
Francisco.
   Martin earned a Peabody Award for producing and directing the
teleplay ``Damien.'' He also received a Houston International Film
Award, two ``Best of the West'' prizes and a New York International
Film Festival Award.
</TEXT>
