<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activist Andrei Sakharov plans to stop
in Paris for a few days to attend a celebration of the 40th
anniversary of the Declaration of Human Rights, a relative says.
   French President Francois Mitterrand invited Sakharov to make the
stop on the Nobel laureate's way back to the Soviet Union, said
Efrem Yankelevich, a son-in-law of Sakharov's wife, Yelena Bonner.
   The visit to France would change Sakharov's schedule, but
Yankelevich said Sunday he and family members were unsure when the
Soviet physicist would leave the United States or when he would
arrive in Moscow.
   Sakharov has been in the United States since Nov. 4.
   The universal Declaration of Human Rights was passed by the
United Nations on Dec. 10, 1948, and spells out fundamental human
rights. The date is observed each year as International Human Rights
Day.
</TEXT>
