<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0106EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Carlucci     12-05 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Carlucci,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Chief Visits U.S. Warship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
visited the aircraft carrier USS Nimitz and praised its crew for
keeping last week's fire on the flight deck from turning into a
major disaster, officials said.
   Carlucci, on the second of a four-day swing through the Persian
Gulf region, flew by helicopter Sunday from Oman to the
nuclear-powered carrier off the coast in the Arabian Sea.
   Earlier in the day, he visited two Omani military installations.
   During several hours aboard the 90,944-ton carrier, Carlucci was
shown the location of Wednesday's pre-dawn fire that killed two
sailors and damaged seven aircraft, U.S. officials said.
   In a videotaped message broadcast on the ship's closed-circuit
system, he ``praised the entire ship's efforts'' in dealing with an
emergency that could have been much worse, one official said.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, quoted
Carlucci as saying safety drills and intensive training for
emergencies enabled firefighters to contain the blaze within 20
minutes on a flight deck where many other aircraft were parked.
   Investigators are still trying to determine why a 20mm gun on an
A-7E Corsair fighter-bomber accidentally fired a burst during an
overhaul, igniting a parked A-6D tanker plane.
   One sailor was killed in the fire and a second died of burns on
Friday in a U.S. military hospital in West Germany.
   Carlucci's gulf itinerary also includes stops in Bahrain, Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait before he returns to Washington.
   U.S. officials say his tour is probably the last by a top Reagan
administration official to the gulf, where the United States has
over the past 18 months conducted its biggest naval operation since
Vietnam.
   President Reagan ordered the buildup of U.S forces to protect
U.S.-flagged shipping and help protect gulf sea lanes after the
Iraq-Iran war escalated in the waterway in mid-1987.
   The Pentagon says the U.S. force, still 25 ships, will be scaled
back gradually if the Iraq-Iran cease-fire, in effect since Aug. 20,
continues to hold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
