<DOCNO> AP881205-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HealthSecretary     12-05 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Health Secretary,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head of Black Medical College Candidate for HHS Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the only predominantly black
medical school founded in the United States this century has emerged
as a candidate to head the Department of Health and Human Services
in President-elect George Bush's administration.
   Although there is no indication Bush is prepared to move quickly
on the HHS post, the selection of Dr. Louis W. Sullivan of the
Morehouse School of Medicine would be in line with Bush's stated
desire to find qualified blacks for his Cabinet.
   Bush's wife, Barbara, serves on the Morehouse board of trustees
and the vice president himself stood beside Sullivan in 1982 when
the new medical school moved into its first permanent home.
   Mrs. Bush delivered congratulations from President Reagan at
ceremonies in 1985 when the Atlanta school graduated its first
full-fledged class of medical students.
   Another HHS secretary candidate also said to be under active
consideration is Dr. Monroe Trout, a doctor and lawyer who serves on
the Morehouse board with Mrs. Bush and was active in Republican
politics in Connecticut before moving to California to head a chain
of non-profit hospitals.
   Trout, who is white, has declined to talk to reporters but has
acknowledged to friends that he is interested in the job and was in
Washington recently to discuss the possibility with individuals and
groups with a keen interest in the HHS post, although not
necessarily directly with Bush operatives.
   For his part, Sullivan said last week that he has had no contact
with Bush or his transition staff about any job, but added that he
was aware a number of Republicans have recommended to Bush that he
be named to the top job at HHS.
   The same sources who said Sullivan and Trout are under active
consideration said Rep. Willis Gradison of Ohio, ranking Republican
on the Ways and Means health subcommittee that oversees Medicare and
many other HHS programs, remains on the ``short list.''
   Gradison has declined to discuss his prospects with reporters,
but sources familiar with the congressman's thinking said he is not
pushing for the job even though he was frequently mentioned for it
long before Bush's election.
   Gradison was in Bush's graduating class at Yale, but the two were
not particularly close at the time. Gradison entered the school when
he was 16 years old, the same year Bush enrolled after returning
from service in World War II.
   While Gradison has more detailed knowledge of the workings of
HHS, a huge agency with more than 100,000 employees and a budget
larger than the Pentagon, there is widespread speculation that Bush
might want to follow the precedent set by Reagan with the
appointment of Dr. Otis R. Bowen and name another physician to
succeed him.
   Bowen, a former two-time Republican governor of Indiana with
close ties to Bush, has made clear he wants to return home to tend
his garden in retirement.
   However, Bush is known to value the country doctor's counsel and
sent his personnel chief to confer privately with Bowen last week,
about the same time sources learned that Sullivan's name had been
put in play.
   Another new name that surfaced last week was that of retired Navy
Adm. James Watkins, who enhanced his national reputation as chairman
of the White House AIDS commission.
   Watkins was the major force in pushing the commission to
recommend adoption of federal legislation to ban discrimination
against people infected with the AIDS virus _ a position Bush made a
point of embracing during his campaign even though Reagan had
stopped short of that stance in referring the anti-discrimination
question to the Justice Department for study.
   Social Security Commissioner Dorcas Hardy has made no secret of
her desire for a promotion in a Bush administration and has long
been considered a serious candidate because of her gender and
familiarity with the department, of which the Social Security
Administration is a part.
   However, she is more closely identified with Reagan's
conservative policies than other often-mentioned candidates and may
have been damaged further by recent news stories regarding Social
Security activities.
   One concerned a low-level draft proposal to change the appeals
process for people denied Social Security benefits. The proposal
became public before reaching either Hardy or her chief deputies for
review and Hardy subsequently disavowed it.
</TEXT>
