<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KeyRingKing     12-05 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Key Ring King,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Ring The Thing For Collector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL LAKE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brian Braje might be called the Lord of
the Rings.
   He has key rings that light up, do multiplication, and others
that read, ``I love Bingo'' and ``I love Jesus.''
   He has a Michael Jackson and Boy George key ring and one that
looks like a pickle. And enough glow-in-the-dark key rings are in
his room to give it an eerie, greenish cast when the lights are out.
   The 16-year-old mentally and physically disabled boy from this
community 40 miles northwest of Chicago enjoys his collection, said
his stepmother, Judy Braje.
   ``Everyone looks for a niche in life,'' said Mrs. Braje. ``If a
special child can find his and really grasp it, he can blossom.''
   Brian has the physical appearance of a 7-year-old, his speech is
difficult to understand and he has trouble grasping many elementary
concepts.
   But his limitations do not extend to collecting key rings.
   Brian started the collection four years ago, and it has grown to
1,256.
   ``He gets very excited when he gets a new one or when he finds
one in the store. He seems to have almost a radar for them,'' said
Mrs. Braje.
</TEXT>
