<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-05 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before the plane chartered by Virgil and Debbie
Thomas could deliver its two passengers to their destination, the
couple delivered a passenger 8,000 feet in the air _ a 6-pound,
5-ounce baby girl.
   Mrs. Thomas had gone into labor Thursday at her home in the town
of John Day, but had wanted to give birth at St. Charles Medical
Center in Bend, about 80 miles east.
   She and her husband quickly chartered a plane, but their daughter
was quicker, arriving about 30 miles short of the Bend airport.
   Upon landing at Bend, paramedics who had been contacted by radio
took over. Jan Grey, a nurse at St. Charles, said no complications
developed and mother and daughter were in great shape.
   The baby, whose name was not given, is the couple's second child.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angelo and Nina Pittner never owned a car,
always preferring to take the bus, trolley or train.
   So the McKeesport couple celebrated not only their 60th
anniversary Sunday but toasted their love affair with public
transportation by drinking champagne aboard a trolley car.
   Five bottles were uncorked as the couple and 45 family members
had a party on the chartered light-rail car.
   ``People think we might be rich because of all the money we've
saved by not owning a car,'' said Mrs. Pittner, 78.
   Pittner, 83, was a railroad engineer for USX Corp.'s National
Works in suburban McKeesport for 25 years.
   ``I just never had any desire to own a car,'' he said.
   The Pittners have taken bus trips to Florida and train trips to
Yellowstone National Park and across Canada.
</TEXT>
