<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Stock Prices Decline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing Nikkei, dollar</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down to close lower against the
Japanese yen Monday, while share prices also declined on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 121.53 yen, down 0.11 yen from Friday's
close of 121.64 yen. Opening at 121.48 yen, the currency was traded
in a range between 121.30 yen and 121.65 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 13.25-point
winner during its half-day session Saturday, lost 50.82 points or
0.17 percent to finish trading at 29,614.68.
   ``The market is in a cautious and directionless mood following
news about the emperor's condition,'' said an analyst with Daiwa
Securities. Speaking on condition of anonymity, he said most of the
investors had taken to the sidelines.
   Emperor Hirohito, bedridden since Sept. 19 from internal
hemorrhaging, received emergency blood transfusions Monday after he
discharged a large amount of blood. He has been under constant
surveillance at the Fukiage Palace.
