<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Argentina-Mood     12-05 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Mood,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worried Argentines Filled Plazas To Repudiate Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Argentina, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braving a scorching sun that sent
temperatures to 98 degrees, worried Argentines filled plazas to
repudiate an army revolt they viewed as a threat to their 5-year-old
democracy.
   Hundreds of others journeyed to the outskirts of the capital to
shout insults and throw rocks at rebel soldiers, who sprayed them
with tear gas and fired rubber bullets and live ammunition.
   News reports said four people were killed.
   In downtown Buenos Aires, teen-agers, many shirtless and wearing
shorts, young couples with children in tow and the elderly in their
Sunday best sought shade or strolled around the giant plaza facing
the green-domed National Congress building.
   Still littered with debris left by 150,000 demonstrators Saturday
night, the plaza throbbed with the beat of bass drums pounded by
perspiring youngsters.
   ``We've been here since yesterday morning,'' said Maria Cabrera
Garandan, 30, of suburban Lanus Este. ``I think there's going to be
a fight between the military, but I believe it will turn out all
right.''
   ``We represent a lot of different political groups,'' she said,
pointing to the banners representing most of Argentina's center and
leftist parties. ``But we're united now by a common cause against
the rebels.''
   Esteban Fernandez, 48, trying to eat an ice-cream cone before it
melted, described himself as ``just another Argentine, an apolitical
one, who is sick and tired of military coups.''
   Argentina has experienced six coups that toppled elected
governments since 1930.
   ``I'm here to support democracy,'' said Fernandez, who came to
the plaza Saturday night and again Sunday, his only day off, along
with his two children ``so they can learn something.''
   ``There's a little bit of everything here, socialists,
communists, you name it, but we all have to learn to live
together,'' said his son Manuel, 21, a university student. His
daughter, Alicia, 19, nodded in agreement.
   Maria del Carmen Martinez, 25, handed out leftist Workers' Party
pamphlets urging that the rebels be ``squashed'' _ which, she said,
could only occur ``if the workers mobilize and march on the barracks
to put down this rightist uprising.''
</TEXT>
