<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Kirk     12-05 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kirk,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Party Chairman Reportedly to Step Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: News conference scheduled for 2 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul G. Kirk Jr. has decided to resign as chairman
of the Democratic National Committee, The Boston Globe reported
today.
   Kirk believes he has accomplished the goals he set for himself
and feels ``that one term is enough,'' according to a source that
the newspaper did not identify.
   The Globe said Kirk would announce his decision at a news
conference today in Washington.
   Other sources close to Kirk told the newspaper he based his
decision solely on personal concerns. The newspaper said it was
widely known that his wife, Gail, preferred that he step down.
   Kirk, who took over head of the party after the 1984 presidential
election, turned down several requests from leading Democrats that
he remain on the job, the newspaper said.
   Leading candidates to replace Kirk are believed to include Rick
Wiener, chairman of the Michigan Democratic Party, and Ronald H.
Brown, who worked briefly in the presidential campaigns of the Rev.
Jesse Jackson and Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   Also expected to seek the post are former congressmen Michael
Barnes of Maryland, James Jones of Oklahoma and Jim Stanton of Ohio.
</TEXT>
