<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0321EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Venezuela-Glance     12-05 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Venezuela-Glance,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Venezuela-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Venezuela, where voters went
to the polls Sunday to elect their seventh president since an
authoritarian ruler, Gen. Marcos Perez Jimenez, was toppled in 1958:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Venezuela covers 352,143 square miles, an area larger
than Texas and Utah combined. It lies on the north coast of South
America, on the Caribbean and the Atlantic Ocean. It shares borders
with Brazil on the south, Colombia on the west and Guyana on the
east. It has unsettled border disputes with Guyana and Colombia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ Venezuela has 18.43 million people, and its
population is growing at a rate of 2.9 percent, one of the highest
rates in Latin America. The literacy rate is 90 percent, one of the
region's highest. More than 9.1 million people over 18, the voting
age, are registered to vote by the Electoral Council, which
supervises elections.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ Oil accounts for more than 90 percent of the
nation's export revenue. Oil income this year will be $7.1 billion,
down from $9.1 billion in 1987. The plunge in oil prices since the
early 1980s, coupled with a foreign debt of $33 billion, thwarted
plans to expand and modernize the economy. The oil crunch is also
responsible for a sharp decline in the nation's per capita income _
$2,782 in 1986, down from $3,408 in 1980.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Christopher Columbus discovered Venezuela _ named for
Little Venice _ in 1498. Venezuela declared independence in 1811 and
Spain recognized the nation in 1821. Since its separation in 1830
from a federation made up of Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela, the
country has had 34 presidents, mostly a succesion of ``caudillos,''
strongmen backed up by local militias, until 1959, when Romulo
Betancourt became the first president of the modern era of democracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
