<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     12-05 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Stable After Massive Transfusions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's condition stabilized today and
his vital signs were near normal after massive blood transfusions to
make up for blood lost during internal hemorrhaging, palace
officials said.
   The 87-year-old monarch's condition is ``picking up ... as can be
seen by his blood pressure,'' said Kenji Maeda, spokesman for the
Imperial Household Agency. He said Hirohito's blood pressure
recovered to 107 over 49 after it fell to 65 over 35 in the morning.
   A healthy person has a reading of about 120 over 80.
   The monarch's temperature was 98.78, Maeda said.
   Hirohito was given 2.13 pints of blood, including a 1.7-pint
emergency transfusion, the spokesman said.
   It was the second time the emperor's blood pressure plummeted to
a dangerously low level since he fell ill Sept. 19 after coughing up
blood. On Nov. 8, his blood pressure dropped to 68 over 30.
   Doctors believe that Hirohito, the world's longest-reigning
monarch, is bleeding mostly in the upper intestinal area where he
underwent a bypass operation in September 1987. In recent days, he
has spent most of his time sleeping and responds very little to
questions from aides, doctors say.
   They have refused to comment on reports the monarch has
pancreatic cancer.
</TEXT>
