<DOCNO> AP881205-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhiteCollarBoxers     12-05 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-White Collar Boxers,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Professionals Pound Each Other in the Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The podiatrist connects with a right to the
physical therapist's nose. A little stream of blood appears. And the
aggressor stops.
   It's not a brawl, but a sport attracting an increasing number of
young professionals: boxing.
   Foot-doctor Bob Gerber and Greg Znajda, the physical therapist,
are among those finding pleasure in a sport more often practiced in
the ghetto.
   ``We aren't out to hurt each other,'' said Gerber, 33, explaining
why he stopped after drawing blood on his friend. ``We're here to
learn.''
   At the Degerberg Academy on Chicago's North Side, lawyers,
psychiatrists, computer scientists, teachers and others mix it up
under the tutelage of gym owner and boxing instructor Fred Degerberg.
   ``For business guys, it can give them a competitive edge,''
Degerberg said. ``It makes them more aggressive. Business people
need any edge they can get and they're going to go for it.''
   Whether they're drawn to the gym by an interest in self defense,
a desire to get into shape, or a simple sense of aggression,
Degerberg says many professionals are taking up boxing.
   ``It improves reflexes, strength, timing, flexibility, hand-eye
coordination and it's a great aerobic workout,'' he said.
``Well-to-do people like the sense of being in top shape. They like
to feel they're able to take care of themselves.''
   But they aren't able to hop right into the ring as soon as they
get to the school. At Degerberg's, most take classes on the
principles of self-defense before taking up boxing.
   Gerber began at the gym after he discovered he felt heavy and his
joints felt weak during a ski trip last winter.
   He began by pounding the heavy bag, then graduated to jumping
rope to gain rhythm. He moved on to the speed bag to improve his
hand-eye coordination, and then worked with partners wearing
oversized mitts that he chased with his punches.
   Only then did he learn to jab, cross and hook and to block
punches, and finally climb into the ring.
   ``There has been a definite shift in how I view myself in
relation to other people,'' Gerber said. ``Having done boxing, I'm
less intimidated by people. I have more confidence.'
   ``It's almost mystical to be in there,'' said Znajda, 30, dabbing
blood from his nose after his bout with Gerber. ``When you go into
the ring, the rest of the world goes away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
