<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan-Airlift     12-05 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Airlift,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Starts Airlift for Starving Southerners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planes loaded with food for hundreds of
thousands of starving Sudanese began shuttling to rebel- and
government-controlled towns as part of a Red Cross effort to feed
the hungry.
   The first two flights Sunday from Khartoum to Wau, 625 miles
southwest of the capital, carried four to five tons of food, said
Pierre Pont, the Red Cross official in charge of the airlift.
   The food was carried in two U.S.-made Hercules C-130 transport
planes.
   Another two C-130s carried food from Lokichokio, Kenya, to the
border town of Nimule and some other rebel-held towns in south Sudan.
   The $2 million project, financed by the Swiss-based International
Committee of the Red Cross, is scheduled to last two weeks. It will
involve 28 trips from Khartoum to Wau.
   Pont said the airlift is very costly but that most roads are
mined, so planes are the safest way to transport the food.
   He said it's possible the project will be extended beyond the
two-week schedule, ``according to the need of the people and the
situation there,'' adding that a cease-fire agreement made him
optimistic the operation would be a success.
   C-130s will be used to airlift food to Wau, but light Cessna
aircraft will be used in areas where there are no airstrips, Pont
said.
   Pont said he had assurances from the government and the rebels
that the operation would go smoothly.
   Rebels of the predominately Christian and animist Sudan People's
Liberation Army have been fighting the Moslem government for nearly
six years. Last month, the governing coalition agreed to a
cease-fire with the rebels.
   Pont said this agreement had helped in the airlift.
   ``I have the feeling that both sides have now understood relief
should go to the people whatever be the differences between them. We
have the best conditions ever for a successful operation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
