<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Venezuela-Perez     12-05 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Venezuela-Perez,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New President Associated With Prosperity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Venezuela-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Andres Perez, the son of a
coffee grower who grew up to be president, is closely identified
with his country's best economic times.
   But the Venezuela he will preside over now is facing far more
serious economic problems than the nation he headed in 1974-1979,
when the Arab oil embargo propelled this oil-producing nation to
growth and prosperity.
   The charismatic Perez triumphed over a conservative rival on
Sunday by mixing populist rhetoric with tireless campaigning,
scheduling eight daily campaign stops during the last seven months.
   Whether he's a ``full-time politician'', as he calls himself, or
a political animal, as others have, the balding, 6-foot-1 statesman
seems to lose half of his 66 years whenever he's in a crowd.
   Perez is the son of a coffee grower and the 11th of 12 children.
At age 15, he joined the clandestine National Democratic Party,
which later became Democratic Action party of Romulo Betancourt.
   Perez studied law while working as Betancourt's personal
secretary when the Democratic Action and other democratic parties
overthrew a military government in 1945. Betancourt headed the
revolutionary junta.
   But before he finished law school, Perez was jailed and then
exiled with many militants when the new democracy was crushed by a
1948 military coup led by Col. Marcos Perez Jimenez.
   From exile in Colombia, Cuba and Costa Rica _ where he worked at
the newspaper La Republica in San Jose _ Perez and other party
leaders plotted to remove Perez Jimenez. They succeeded in 1958.
   When Betancourt was elected president a year later, Perez was
elected congressman. He returned to Betancourt's side when the
president selected his protege as interior minister in 1962, at a
time of increasing domestic guerrilla insurgency.
   Perez earned a reputation as a tough law-and-order man in
crushing the movement with force, although it was not fully
eliminated until President Rafael Caldera, who served from 1968 to
1973, sponsored a successful amnesty program.
   By that time, Perez had become the Democratic Action party's
secretary-general, its candidate for president, and, in the 1973
election, its fourth democratically elected president.
   During the next five years, Venezuela's income nearly tripled as
oil prices went through the roof following the Arab oil embargo of
1973-74.
   In 1976, Perez made history when he nationalized the foreign oil
companies operating in Venezuela.
   Perez is credited with having invested many of the incoming
billions of dollars in developing basic industries such as aluminum,
steel and hydroelectricity.
   But he was nearly impeached for his alleged involvement in
receiving kickbacks of tens of thousands of dollars in the public
purchase of a refrigerator ship, the Sierra Nevada, and left office
in disgrace despite his acquittal.
   The Sierra Nevada case is still remembered by voters, and Perez'
main challenger, Eduardo Fernandez, used it as an early campaign
weapon.
   But during these times of economic difficulty, many voters, in
particular the poor and working classes, remember more the
prosperity, full employment and rising living standards of Perez's
first government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
