<DOCNO> AP881205-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0503EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steinberg     12-05 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Limits Jury's Use Of Nussbaum's Testimony</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain; cross-examination expected by
afternoon EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The star prosecution witness' testimony about
being beaten by her former live-in lover may lead jurors to conclude
that he also beat the 6-year-old illegally adopted girl he is
accused of killing, his lawyer said.
   But Judge Harold Rothwax told the jurors in the murder trial of
disbarred attorney Joel Steinberg that they were hearing testimony
from Hedda Nussbaum solely to gain insight into her state of mind
when Lisa Steinberg was fatally injured Nov. 2, 1987.
   Prosecutors said jurors need to know Ms. Nussbaum's state of mind
at the time so they will understand why she could not have hurt Lisa
herself and why she took no action to help the child.
   Ms. Nussbaum was scheduled to resume her testimony today in state
criminal court, where Steinberg, 47, stands accused of beating Lisa
to death.
   Defense attorney Ira London said he believed the judge was right
to tell the jurors they could not use Ms. Nussbaum's testimony to
decide Steinberg's guilt.
   But London said he thought the instruction was futile.
   ``If Hedda Nussbaum is permitted to testify as to instances of
physical abuse by Joel,'' London said, ``the jury may just conclude
that if he beat Hedda, he beat Lisa.''
   She testified last week that Steinberg beat, starved and
humiliated her.
   In slow cadences punctuated by sighs, gulps and sobs, Ms.
Nussbaum said Steinberg fed her cocaine, cut her off from her
family, brainwashed her into believing she was a cultist who
hypnotized people and got her fired from her job as a children's
book editor at Random House.
   She also testified that she ``worshipped'' Steinberg, believed he
had ``godlike'' powers and was a healer. This, she said, was in part
why she did nothing to help Lisa as the child lay unconscious on the
bathroom floor for hours.
   Ms. Nussbaum initially was charged in Lisa's death, but the
charges were dropped after prosecutors said they found she was
incapable physically and emotionally of hurting or protecting the
child.
   A copy of a letter purportedly written by Ms. Nussbaum about 10
years ago and obtained by Newsweek magazine sheds light on her
childhood and trouble she had asserting herself.
   The letter said that her mother, when pregnant with her, had
wanted an abortion, the magazine reported this week.
   ``(My mother) insisted on doing everything for me _ putting on my
socks at age 6 for example, she said. ``My father, on the other
hand, was always saying, `Listen to me. I'm older. I know better.'
The combination made me feel like I couldn't do anything for myself
and didn't know anything.''
   Lisa, illegally obtained by Steinberg the day after she was born
to an unwed teen-ager, was removed bruised and unconscious from
Steinberg's apartment. She died of head injuries Nov. 5, 1987.
   Ms. Nussbaum has testified that Steinberg admitted to her he
``knocked Lisa down and she didn't want to get up'' about the time
the prosecution says the fatal blow was struck.
</TEXT>
