<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Capsize     12-05 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Capsize,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Drowned, Two Missing After Dredger Capsizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dredger capsized and sank in stormy seas
off the Belgian coast early today, and two of the 10 crew members
were killed and another two were missing, the coast guard said.
   Six crew members were rescued and taken to hospitals in Belgium,
a Dover coast guard spokesman said. It was not immediately known if
any of them was injured.
   The Cardiff, Wales-registered Bowsprite turned back in rough
weather from a trip to the Belgian port of Nieuwpoort and was
heading for the English coast when it capsized about 25 miles west
of Zeebrugge, Belgium, the spokesman said.
   Dredgers often gather aggregate for construction materials from
sand banks in river channels or harbors.
   The spokesman, speaking on condition he not be identified, said a
Mayday call was received shortly after midnight saying the vessel
was breaking in half and that its crew was taking to life rafts.
   The British minesweeper Upton, carrying out routine duties off
the Belgian coast, took charge of a rescue operation involving a
British military Sea King helicopter, two Belgian helicopters and a
North Sea ferry, Pride of Bruges.
   Rescuers picked up six survivors and the bodies of two men, the
coast guard said.
</TEXT>
