<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistAdoption     12-05 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Adoption,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Custody Case Focuses On Polygamists' Fitness For Adoption</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Hearing scheduled to begin at 11 a.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women are seeking to block the
adoption of their dead sister's six children by a polygamist couple
despite a state social worker's finding that the polygamists are
``highly qualified'' to be parents.
   Attorneys were to begin presenting arguments today in the custody
case hinging on whether people who practice polygamy in violation of
Utah law can be considered proper candidates for adoption.
   The state Department of Social Services has an informal policy
that polygamy is a matter of religion rather than morals and is not
to be considered when social workers make recommendations in
adoption cases, officials say.
   ``We are dealing with children raised in a fundamentalist home
being adopted into a fundamentalist home,'' said Terry Twitchell, a
spokeswoman for the department. ``It's no different than a Jewish
child going to a Jewish home or a Mormon child going to a Mormon
home.''
   But the attorney for the women trying to block the adoption
contends the state policy endorses illegal behavior rather than
tolerating it.
   ``We're not talking about enforcement of bigamy statutes,'' said
the lawyer, Tim Anderson. ``We're not talking about the state
sitting on the fence. In this case, the state is an accomplice in
creating an illegal polygamist family relationship.''
   Vaughn and Sharane Fischer, of the polygamous southwestern Utah
community of Hildale, want to adopt the six children of Brenda
Thornton, a member of the community who died of cancer in August
1987.
   Thornton's children, who range from ages 5 to 19, have lived with
the Fischers the past 1{ years and are said to want to be adopted by
them. Thornton had left a previous polygamous marriage and became
Fischer's third wife two months before her death.
   Thornton signed a document surrendering her children to the
Fischers, and the children's biological father, Joseph Phil
Thornton, consented.
   But two of Brenda Thornton's sisters, Pat and Janet Johanson,
contend the state cannot award custody to parents who openly
practice polygamy and intend to teach those beliefs to their
children.
   Polygamy was sanctioned by the early Mormon church but was banned
before Utah was admitted to statehood. However, some fundamentalist
offshoots of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints still
believe in the practice.
   A home study by a state social worker recommends approval of the
adoptions, calling the Fischers ``highly qualified to take care of
these children'' and ``a good family for adoption.''
   The report mentions that Vaughn Fischer has another wife, Katrina
Stubbs, in addition to Sharane Fischer. But it does not evaluate the
relationship and makes no finding of their ``moral fitness'' to
adopt, as required by law.
   Anderson criticized that approach: ``When you or I go to adopt,
it (moral fitness) is dealt with in depth. The larger issue here is
why does the state have a policy that treats the claims of religious
fundamentalists differently than you or I or anyone else?''
   Jean Nielsen, director of the Division of Family Services, said
the overriding factor is the best interests of the children.
   ``That is why an alternative lifestyle does not rule out someone
from being an adoptive parent,'' she said.
   But if that lifestyle is illegal? ``Then it's probably not in the
best interests of the child,'' she said.
   ``Polygamy is a crime,'' said Steven Snow, an attorney
representing the Fischers. ``But so is adultery and fornication, and
those laws are not enforced either. There are matters far more
important in this case than religious lifestyle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
