<HEAD>Youths Donating Christmas Money To Help Pay Santa's Hospital Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN LAKE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa will be getting gifts this
Christmas instead of giving them.
   Rather than spending money to exchange presents among themselves,
pupils at Mountain Lake Elementary School are making donations to
help pay Elmer Buller's medical expenses.
   Buller, who has played Santa in the community 100 miles southwest
of Minneapolis for at least 20 years, was burned over 25 percent of
his body on Nov. 21 when he slipped into a pit of burning coals at
Balzer Manufacturing, a farm implement plant where he is a custodian.
   Buller, 60, is in intensive care in the burn unit at St.
Paul-Ramsey Medical Center in St. Paul and is expected to be
hospitalized for a month. The burns are mostly on his legs and hands.
   Every year, Buller donned his red Santa suit for an annual visit
to the city park, arriving in a sleigh or behind a team of horses.
But he didn't stop there. He would pop up all over town in costume,
greeting travelers and distributing candy.
   ``He was such a natural,'' said Ardelle Neufeld, office secretary
for the Chamber of Commerce. ``Everybody in Mountain Lake knew it
had to be Elmer (to play the community's Santa).''
   Elmer's wife, Rubie, said the outpouring of care from the
community since the accident has been tremendous. And she said Elmer
will miss playing Santa this year.
   ``He'll miss the kids,'' she said.
</TEXT>
