<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fog in Pacific Northwest; Snow In East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fog blanketed the Pacific Northwest and snow fell in parts of New
England, but skies were clear in much of the nation early today as a
quiet weather pattern that has dominated the nation the last six
days continued.
   The main storm track ran northward along western Canada before
dipping south across the upper Mississippi Valley and the
mid-Atlantic region.
   Northwest winds crossing the eastern Great Lakes produced widely
scattered snow showers in parts of New York state and central New
England late Sunday evening. Two inches of snow fell at Syracuse,
N.Y. Snowfall ranged from a trace to 4 inches across Vermont. One to
three inches of snow was measured in parts of southern New Hampshire.
   Once again dense fog was covering much of the Pacific Northwest
and the central California valleys. The Boise, Idaho, Aiport was
closed Sunday afternoon because of dense fog.
   The nation's high Sunday afternoon was 86 degrees at Palm
Springs, Calif.
   Today's forecast called for snow showers in the Great Lakes
region. An upper air disturbance moving into the Pacific Northwest
was expected to produce rain in western Washington state.
   Much of the nation was to have fair skies because of a large area
of high pressure over the south-central portion of the nation.
   Foggy conditions were expected in valley areas of the northern
and central Pacific Coast.
   Predicted highs: below 20 in northern Maine; 20s in the rest of
northern New England and northeast New York state; 30s and 40s in
eastern parts of the northern Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley,
the Great Lakes states, the central Appalachians and southern New
England, and the northern Rockies; 70s in south Texas, the southern
Florida peninsula, Southern California and the desert Southwest.
   The rest of the nation was expected to have highs in the 50s and
60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 66 at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 40 fair; Boston 26 snow; Buffalo 33 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 40 fair; Cincinnati 25 fair; Cleveland 32 cloudy;
Detroit 34 cloudy; Miami 61 air; New York 35 windy; Philadelphia 34
fair; Pittsburgh 28 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 19 fair;
Washington 38 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 29 fair; Chicago 33 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 39
fair; Denver 27 fair; Des Moines 37 fair; Indianapolis 32 cloudy;
Kansas City, Mo. 32 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 29 fair; Nashville 31
fair; New Orleans 49 fair; St. Louis 34 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 34 fair; Anchorage 20 fair; Las Vegas 40 fair;
Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 64 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City 30
foggy; San Diego 54 fair; San Francisco 53 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 12 fair; Toronto 32 cloudy.
</TEXT>
