<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0609EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RockyFlats     12-05 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rocky Flats,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romer Calls Nuclear Weapons Plant Safe But Renews Threat To Close
It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Roy Romer said storage sites for radioactive
wastes at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant are secure, but he
renewed his threat to close the plant if the federal government
fails to find other storage sites.
   ``I'm saying to the federal government, `Get off your duff _
let's go, let's get a solution,''' the Colorado governor said Sunday
after touring the plant.
   Waste has been collecting in boxcars and in enclosed facilities
at the plant since October when Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus barred them
from entering his state for disposal.
   Romer said he did not want to have to carry out his threat to
force the closure of the plant, which uses plutonium to make
triggers for nuclear bombs, when it reaches storage capacity in
March or April. The plant, about 16 miles northwest of Denver,
employs about 6,000 people.
   A permanent federal disposal site is under construction near
Carlsbad, N.M., but is not expected to be ready until June at the
earliest.
   Romer and other Western governors are to meet with Department of
Energy officials Dec. 16 to discuss the waste storage problem.
   Romer said one temporary solution he will suggest then is that
the storage boxcars be placed in non-populated areas, such as
military bases, under guard. He said he might suggest that
``everybody take three cars and keep them three months'' to give the
federal government a little more leeway.
   Romer said the workers he spoke with at the plant feel
comfortable with their safety measures, but he said the storage
sites could threaten groundwater supplies for neighboring
municipalities.
   The 385-acre plant is surrounded by a 6,500-acre, federally owned
buffer zone, but studies showing higher cancer rates and plutonium
contamination have led to promises of an expensive cleanup.
   Romer said Rocky Flats officials assured him that $20 million
would be spent cleaning up the most contaminated storage sites at
the plant in the next fiscal year.
   Waste disposal is one of many problems that have beset the Energy
Department's nuclear weapons facilities across the country. Four
have been partly closed, virtually halting atomic arms production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
