<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CucciReturn     12-05 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cucci Return,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jersey City Mayor Returns With Wife's Body; Says He'll Go Back To
Peru</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jersey City Mayor Anthony Cucci says he's
ready to get on with his work despite grief over his wife's death in
a Peruvian train accident blamed on sabotage.
   ``I suffered a loss, a great, great loss. I loved her very
much,'' Cucci said of his wife, whom he married in 1985, 11 days
after his election.
   The mayor, who was also injured, arrived with Anna Cucci's body
at Newark International Airport Sunday evening. Mrs. Cucci, 62, will
be buried Wednesday.
   Cucci, 66, said he would be back at City Hall today.
   ``I still have my job to complete,'' he said.
   He also said he thought his wife would have liked him to run for
re-election, but he would decide that later.
   ``If I know Annie, she would have said, `Get out there and do it
again,''' he said.
   Cucci, who was wheeled off the plane in a wheelchair, moved
slowly and stiffly and said he felt ``kind of sore.''
   ``I'm feeling very lucky,'' he said. ``I don't have any internal
injuries.''
   Mrs. Cucci died Thursday when the train she was riding with her
husband and Cuzco city officials derailed on its way to the Inca
ruins of Machupicchu and plunged into a ravine.
   Doris Chacon, the 58-year-old wife of Cuzco Mayor Carlos Chacon,
also was killed. Mayor Chacon suffered multiple fractures and
underwent major surgery.
   Peruvian authorities said the accident was caused by sabotage.
They said it may have been connected to either guerrillas of the
left-wing Maoist Shining Path group or a nationwide labor strike.
   Cucci said he received a warm reception from the Peruvian people
and ``I have no cause to believe there was foul play,'' in the
accident. ``I don't condemn Peru. ... Those few (bad people) will be
weeded out.''
   The New Jersey delegation traveled to Cuzco to sign a
sister-cities agreement to promote cultural, scientific and artistic
exchanges.
   The agreement was signed despite the accident.
   ``It didn't dampen my spirit for a sister city,'' Cucci said.
``I'm going back.''
</TEXT>
