<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     12-05 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower in early European trading
today and currency dealers said they expect little movement during a
week in which no economic indicators are scheduled to be released.
Gold prices rose as much as $6.45 an ounce.
   Traders said volume has already fallen to its traditional slim
year-end levels.
   ``The general market view is bearish, but if you talk to people
in the dealing rooms, you can hear many different opinions,'' said
one dealer at a West German bank in Frankfurt.
   ``The situation is fairly confused, and since we don't expect any
figures this week, we'll probably stay in a (narrow trading) range.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar slipped 0.11 yen to close at 121.53 yen on reports that
Emperor Hirohito's condition had worsened, dealers said. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 121.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.7224 West German marks, down from 1.7315
   _1.4425 Swiss francs, down from 1.4598
   _5.8835 French francs, down from 5.9200
   _1.9452 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9490
   _1,273.75 Italian lire, down from 1,279.50
   _1.1845 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1869
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8713, more than 1 cent more
expensive for buyers than late Friday's $1.8597.
   Gold prices were sharply higher in Europe. Gold surged in New
York on Friday in the wake of another surge in platinum prices.
   The metal opened in London at a bid price of $429.80 a troy
ounce, up from $425.50 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $430.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $430.75, up from $424.30 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 86 cents to close at a bid
$429.94.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.20 a troy ounce,
up from Friday's $6.13.
</TEXT>
