<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0707EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0763 12-05 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0763,0895</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Revival of Thornton Wilder's `Our Town' on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs at end with additional reviews; no pickup. No PMs
planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty years after it first arrived on Broadway,
Thornton Wilder's ``Our Town'' remains an unexpectedly vibrant,
often surprising, piece of theater.
   That's pretty amazing considering how well-known the play is.
There probably isn't a drama club, high school, college playhouse or
community theater where the story of life in Grover's Corners, N.H.,
hasn't been told.
   That sense of vibrancy permeates a sterling new production of
``Our Town.'' It's the work of the Lincoln Center Theater company
which opened the play Sunday at Broadway's Lyceum Theater. The
darkly burnished revival, directed by the company's artistic guru
Gregory Mosher, is straightforward and unsentimental, but it doesn't
sacrifice honest emotion.
   ``Our Town'' is a meditation on life, quite serious and even
somber, particularly in its third act when it deals with life after
death. But that's not what most people remember about the play.
Usually it's bathed in nostalgia for the past, an uncomplicated
turn-of-the century America where people didn't lock their doors at
night, where the milkman still delivered milk to your doorstep and
where young lovers could get engaged over a strawberry phosphate at
the local drug store.
   Those details are in this production but that's just what they
are _ only details in the larger story of life. ``In our town, we
like to know the facts about everybody,'' says the stage manager,
the nameless narrator who tells the story of Grover's Corners and
the people who live there. It's these facts _ pleasant and
unpleasant _ that make the picture whole.
   Wilder divides his play into three acts. The first, called
``Daily Life,'' introduces the characters of ``Our Town,''
particularly the Gibbs and Webb families. It's their children _
George Gibbs and Emily Webb _ who marry and whose story becomes the
second act, ``Love and Marriage.''
   There's no title for Act III. ``I reckon you can guess what
that's about,'' says the stage manager. It deals with death,
specifically Emily's death in childbirth. The scenes are played
simply yet the sparseness of the emotion makes it all the more
affecting.
   Mosher has been fastidious in his casting of the large company,
nearly 30 actors in all. The narrator is playe here by Spalding
Gray. Gray, best known as the author and star of his own monologues
including ``Swimming to Cambodia,'' is a sardonic storyteller.
There's an edge to his performance that slices the sweetness of some
of the events happening on stage.
   Penelope Ann Miller and Eric Stoltz turn the sometimes cloying
young lovers into believable human beings. Miss Miller, in
particular, handles the transition from innocence to experience with
a touching directness.
   Frances Conroy, James Rebhorn, Roberta Maxwell and Peter Maloney
are fine as the quartet of parents, offering individual portraits in
roles that are often considered no more than supporting. Miss Conroy
is eerily effective as the other worldly Mrs. Gibbs who loses all
interest in what was her life after she has ``passed on.''
   Mosher also gets strong support from an excellent production
team. Jane Greenwood's costumes are stylish yet subdued,
monochromatic outfits that don't call attention to themselves yet
seem exactly right. Equally commendable is Kevin Rigdon's sensitive
lighting and Douglas Stein's few chairs and tables strewn across a
bare playing area.
   There's a magical, almost mystical, quality to this production of
``Our Town.'' Maybe that's because it's performed on the large empty
stage of a Broadway theater. Intricate patterns of pipes cover the
back brick wall of the Lyceum and an enormous system of lights seems
to climb to the sky.
   It's a haunting environment for a haunting production, told with
a style and simplicity that reconfirms ``Our Town's'' reputation as
an American classic.
   In other reviews, The New York Times' Frank Rich pointed to ``one
major casting miscalculation, Spalding Gray's flip Stage Manager,
that constantly disrupts the fragile text, the firm staging and the
otherwise well-chosen cast. ... The attempt, through Mr. Gray, to
turn the playwright into something he's not derails Mr. Mosher's
`Our Town.'
   ``While it would no doubt be sickening to see a Stage Manager
resembling the lovable old codgers in wine-cooler commercials, Mr.
Gray swings too far the other way, presenting the narrator as if he
were a narcissistic new-wave raconteur exactly matching the
storyteller in his own autobiographical performance pieces.''
   Clive Barnes of the New York Post wrote: ``Gray is altogether too
contemporary and too removed from the Middle America of the first
decades of the century. ... What makes the version glow _ and what
will forever be remembered about it _ are the two young people ...
These two lit up the stage with truth, honesty and unexpected
tragedy as a village Romeo and Juliet.''
   And Howard Kissel wrote in the Daily News: ``The tone of Gregory
Mosher's production, though full of lively ideas, often seems too
casual. It misses the gravity of turn-of-the-century life, when
grownups felt compelled to act as such. ... But the play is
actor-proof, even non-actor-proof, since Spalding Gray as the Stage
Manager confirms my feeling that avante-garde performers are not
really actors.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
