<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmergencyLandings     12-05 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Emergency Landings,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2 Planes Make Emergency Landings; None Aboard Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE JIRIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two commuter aircraft made emergency landings
within minutes of each other at Stapleton International Airport
after landing gear problems forced them to turn back shortly after
takeoff, airport officials said.
   Both landings went smoothly Sunday and there were no injuries
among the more than 90 people on the flights.
   Rocky Mountain Airways Flight 2178 took off for Steamboat Springs
at 4 p.m. with 43 people on board, but turned back after a warning
light concerning the landing gear came on, said airline spokeswoman
Rita Cuddihy.
   The DeHavilland-7, four-engine turboprop circled Denver to use up
fuel while airport emergency crews moved into place, said Stapleton
spokesman Norm Avery.
   The plane landed safely about 5:45 p.m., Cuddihy said.
   ``They were able to get the gear down and locked, but the (nose)
wheel was cocked to the left. When they landed, the wheel
immediately straightened out,'' she said. The passengers were
transferred to another plane, she said.
   Within a half-hour of the landing, United Express Flight 3939
returned to Stapleton with about 50 people on board, Avery said,
calling the landing ``precautionary.''
   The crew radioed the control tower with ``unknown gear problems''
after taking off for Grand Junction, Avery said.
   Because of the previous landing, ``the emergency equipment was
already in place,'' he said.
   Avery didn't know what kind of plane the United Airlines commuter
service was using, and United Express personnel reached at home had
no information on the flight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
