<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Yugoslav-MoneyLaundering     12-05 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslav-Money Laundering,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavian Consul General Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case of the Yugoslavian consul general
who faces money laundering charges may hinge on a judge's ruling
about diplomatic immunity.
   Defense attorneys said they plan to raise the issue at a pretrial
hearing, but prosecutors maintained Sunday that Bahrudin Bijedic
lacks the broad immunity protecting diplomats.
   Bijedic has no diplomatic immunity from these charges because he
is a consul, Assistant U.S. Attorney Paul Sarmousakis said. He said
diplomats are covered by a treaty that gives them broader immunity,
but consuls, who are named by a country to foster the interests of
its citizens and businesses in a foreign city, can be prosecuted for
offenses that occur outside their official duties.
   Bijedic, the consul general to Chicago, was indicted Thursday
with four other men. He pleaded innocent Sunday before a federal
magistrate and was released to the Yugoslavian acting ambassador on
$150,000 bail. LBS Bank of New York Inc., the U.S. branch of a
Yugoslavian bank, was also indicted.
   ``I expect an apology from the U.S. mass media,'' Bijedic said to
reporters shortly after his arraignment. ``I never violated any
American law.''
   Bijedic was arrested as the result of a U.S. Customs Service
sting operation that tracked at least eight alleged transactions
totaling nearly $1.5 million.
   The defendants are accused of taking cash given to them by
undercover agents out of the country, depositing it in foreign
accounts and wiring the money back to U.S. banks under the names of
phony corporations to hide the money's origin.
   In one instance, Bijedic provided the others with diplomatic
stickers that barred U.S. officials from opening the packages of
money, according to the 21-count indictment.
   Vladimir Matic, Yugoslavian charge d'affaires at the embassy in
Washington, accepted responsibility for Bijedic and assured the
court he will appear for future proceedings. Matic was acting as
ambassador because the chief Yugoslavian representative was not in
the country, U.S. officials said.
   U.S. Magistrate Tullio Leomporra said if Bijedic fled
prosecution, Matic would be imprisoned and forced to pay the bail.
Matic accepted the terms.
   Michael Goode, Bijedic's attorney from Chicago, said it is too
soon to predict what kind of defense will be used. But he said he
would raise the issue of diplomatic immunity.
   Bijedic was released by a federal judge to customs agents and
brought to Philadelphia for the hearing Friday.
   During the proceedings, Goode said he and Bijedic returned to his
hotel room from breakfast early Sunday to find customs agents
rifling the man's belongings looking for documents.
   Several of the documents were placed in a sealed envelope, but
Goode argued the search was a violation of Bijedic's Fourth
Amendment rights.
   The documents will remain in the sealed envelope in the
possession of prosecutors until the challenge can be made at future
hearing before the trial judge assigned to the case, Leomporra said.
   All five men named in the indictment were charged with violating
currency reporting laws, the arms export and control act, and
conspiracy, customs officials said.
   Indicted along with Bijedic, 52, were Vjekoslov Spanjol, 31, a
naturalized U.S. citizen from Texas; Vinko Mir, 54, chairman of LBS
Bank; Hubert Francis Cole, 44, of Carrollton, Texas; and Larry Card,
50, of Chattanooga, Tenn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881205-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0730EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cameroon-Panic     12-05 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cameroon-Panic,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Die In Panic At School In Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAOUNDE, Cameroon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panic provoked by a false alarm that a
Yaounde school was about to collapse left 34 people dead today and
at least 50 injured, an official at the U.S. Embassy said.
   Cameroon authorities were trying to determine what started the
panic at the Institut Jean Monthe, a private secondary school
located in a marshy area in the heart of the West African capital,
said Gemuh Akuchu, a spokesman for the embassy.
   About 10,000 students between the ages of 12 and 16 attend the
school.
   According to first reports from the scene, a confrontation about
9:30 a.m. between a student and teacher on the ground floor provoked
a wave of shouting by students that was interpreted by others
upstairs as a warning that the old building was about to collapse.
   In the panic, students rushed down an open staircase in the
five-story structure toward the only entrance. Akuchu said some of
those killed apparently fell off the staircase, others jumped out
windows on the upper floors and some were crushed underfoot in the
stampede to the door.
   The French news agency Agence-France Presse, quoting unnamed
hospital sources, reported that at least 50 young people had been
taken to the local hospital.
   Parents rushed to the scene, complicating the work of emergency
teams and ambulances caring for the injured.
   A spokesman for President Paul Biya said he also was expected at
the scene.
</TEXT>
