<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Bombs,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Bombs Explode In Athens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four bombs exploded early today in the
capital, damaging two political party offices and a car belonging to
a conservative politician, police said.
   The blasts, which occurred at 20-minute intervals, caused some
property damage but no injuries, said a police spokesman speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The left-wing terrorist group Social Resistance claimed
responsibility for the explosions in a telephone call to the
left-wing daily Eleftherotypia.
   The police spokesman said the first bomb went off outside the
office of Nikos Anagnostopoulos, a parliamentarian with the main
conservative opposition party New Democracy.
   The second bomb went off outside Anagnostopoulos' apartment,
located in the same building as his office, the police spokesman
said.
   The next shattered windows in a nearby office of the governing
Panhellenic Socialist Movement, he said.
   The fourth bomb damaged the car of New Democracy parliamentarian
Athanassios Kanellopoulos, parked outside his home.
   Social Resistance emerged for the first time Nov. 16 when it
claimed responsibility for blasts outside the office of New
Democracy deputy Stephanos Manos and outside an apartment owned by
Yannis Latsis, a Greek industrialist.
