<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Postal     12-05 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Postal,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office Adds Planes For Christmas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service has added extra cargo planes
connecting 10 major cities to speed the flow of mail during the
Christmas season, Postmaster General Anthony Frank reported today.
   The special package service will operate through Dec. 24, using
Terre Haute, Ind., as a hub, according to agency officials.
   The Postal Service regularly operates a fleet of 23 aircraft
through its Terre Haute hub in the early hours of each morning; the
special Christmas service will add daytime flights to help cope with
the pre-holiday crush.
   Frank said in an interview on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America''
that the Postal Service is expecting a deluge of mail Dec. 19 and
urged Americans to send their cards and packages before that.
   ``Everybody's going to try to mail on the 19th, he said. But, all
in all, even in the last week, we'll be able to handle it.''
   The supplemental air transport system will begin Dec. 10 and
connect New York, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Dallas, Boston,
Atlanta, Detroit, Denver, Seattle and Pittsburgh.
   Frank was said he does not expect an increase in postage rates
for at least two years.
   He has said several times in the past that the agency is likely
to begin the complex process of raising rates in 1990, with an
increase expected in 1991.
</TEXT>
