<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Hamadi     12-05 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Hamadi,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Confessed Hijacker Shouted `We Kill Marines'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi pointed a gun
at the head of a U.S. serviceman during the 1985 TWA hijacking and
said ``We kill Marines,'' according to testimony at the confessed
hijacker's trial today.
   Kenneth Bowen, 26, a civil engineering student who was a hostage
on the TWA jet, testified that Hamadi dragged him to the first-class
section of the hijacked airliner to question him.
   ``Hamadi grabbed me by my hair and pulled me to the first-class
section,'' Bowen testified. ``He had a gun in his hand and asked me
if I was a Marine.
   ``I said I was a sailor,'' Bowen said. ``He said `We kill
Marines.'''
   He said Hamadi spoke to him in broken English.
   During the exchange, Bowen said, he and Hamadi ``were face to
face and he had the pistol pointed at my face saying `you Marine, we
kill Marine.'''
   ``He (Hamadi) indicated that if I didn't cooperate, he would
shoot me,'' Bowen said.
   Bowen told the court he was a member of a team of U.S. Navy
divers traveling aboard the Athens-to-Rome flight when it was
hijacked in June 1985. He said he had been a close friend of Robert
Stethem, the Navy diver who was shot and killed by one of the
hijackers.
   Previous witnesses have testified that the hijackers apparently
mistook the divers for U.S. Marines.
   Stethem was the only fatality during the ordeal, during which 39
Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   Hamadi has admitted taking part in the hijacking, but has denied
shooting Stethem. He is being tried on murder and air piracy charges
in a heavily guarded Frankfurt courtroom.
   Choking back tears, Bowen described the events surrounding
Stethem's murder.
   ``I heard some commotion in the front of the plane. I thought I
heard a door open. There was a muffled shot and sounds of a person
moaning,'' Bowen said. He said he did not see who shot Stethem.
   Bowen, who was discharged from active Navy service in 1985, also
told the court he believed Hamadi was the leader of the hijackers.
   ``Hamadi had the gun most of the time and he made most of the
decisions,'' Bowen said.
   Under court guidelines to protect witnesses, Bowen was not asked
to give his current residence. Court records indicate that at the
time of the hijacking, his address was listed as St. Petersburg, Fla.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt Airport in January 1987 after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
   His older brother, Abbas Ali Hamadi, is serving a 13-year prison
sentence in West Germany after being convicted of helping to kidnap
two West Germans in Beirut in an effort to win release of his
brother.
   The West German hostages have since been released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
