<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NIreland-PeaceMarch     12-05 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Peace March,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholics And Protestants Join North Ireland Peace March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Protestants and
Roman Catholics joined a peace march by torchlight to appeal for an
end to nearly 20 years of sectarian violence.
   Police said an estimated 8,000 people took part in the Sunday
night rally. Northern Ireland's four main churches organized the
procession through Belfast, which ended with Christmas carol singing
in the rain.
   Organizers said it was the first peace demonstration jointly
organized by the Catholic, Protestant, Methodist and Presbyterian
churches since violence began in the British province in 1969.
   ``For so many people to get up out of their armchairs on a night
such as this shows they want peace,'' said the Rev. Cahal Daly, the
Catholic bishop of Down and Conor.
   The bishop of the Protestant Church of Ireland, the Rev. Samuel
Poyntz, said: ``Better times for our city will come through prayer
and praise, not through protest and provocation.''
   Guerrillas of the Irish Republican Army have been waging a
violent campaign to end British rule in the province and unite it
with the Irish Republic.
   Almost 2,000 people have been killed in sectarian violence since
1969.
</TEXT>
