<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HighwayKillings     12-05 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Killings,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Of One Of Five Victims Found Along Highways Identified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have identified one of the
five young women killed and dumped along highways in southeastern
Massachusetts in what police believe was the work of a serial killer
or killers.
   The body of Dawn Mendes, 25, of New Bedford was identified
Saturday by pathologists, said Bristol County District Attorney
Ronald A. Pina. She had been reported missing Sept. 10 from this
port town, near where the remains of five women have been found
since July in the brush just off Interstate 195 and Route 140.
   Pina said Mendes had a 5-year-old son and a record of arrests,
but he would not say what the arrests were for.
   Authorities said the investigation will try to trace backward
from the time Mendes was reported missing. Her body was the fourth
to be found.
   State police using trained dogs were to resume a search for more
victims and other evidence today.
   Mendes' remains were found Tuesday along the Reed Road exit ramp
on I-195. The third body was discovered Nov. 8 off the same ramp on
the other side of the the highway, not far from where the second
body was found in July.
   An autopsy was performed Friday on the fifth body, which was
found Thursday in nearby Freetown along Route 140, three miles south
of where the first body was found July 3.
   On Friday, Pina linked the victims to several women reported
missing in recent months from Weld Square, known by police as a
center of drug dealing and prostitution in this fishing port of
98,000 people about 50 miles south of Boston. There have been
reports of abductions from the red-light district in recent months.
   Pina said Friday that one of the victims was strangled. The cause
of death of some of the others had been determined but he would not
disclose the results.
   The remains of all five women will be examined by the FBI to more
accurately determine the cause of death and other details,
authorities said.
</TEXT>
