<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Cyclone     12-05 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Cyclone,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Bodies Recovered From Cyclone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers recovered hundreds of bodies
from the Bay of Bengal and coastal mangrove swamps, but thousands of
people remained missing nearly a week after a cyclone hit India and
Bangladesh.
   Indian officials said 500 people died there, while the count in
Bangladesh varied widely.
   The government news agency of Bangladesh said 1,389 people were
killed by the storm, but the state-owned Bangladesh Times newspaper
said 1,500 died. The independent newspaper Inqilab maintained the
5,500 people died.
   The Red Crescent Society said its count stood at 1,150 but it had
not been updated since Sunday.
   The Bangladesh Times said 353 bodies were recovered Sunday from
the Bay of Bengal and mangrove swamps at the Sunderbans forest in
southwestern Bangladesh.
   Between 3,000 and 5,000 people have been missing since the
cyclone hit Tuesday night, according to officials and newspapers.
   Retired army Maj. Ziauddin, president of the fisherman's
association for a strip of coastal river delta land called Dublar
Char, said 5,000 fishermen and 1,400 boats were unaccounted for.
   Ziauddin, who uses only one name, told a news conference in
Khulna that bodies of 200 other Dublar Char fishermen had been
found. It was not known if these were among the 353 bodies reported
recovered by The Bangladesh Times. Khulna is 85 miles southwest of
Dhaka.
   A Khulna official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
salvage vessels are removing about 70 sunken barges blocking the
major port of Mongla on the Pasur River 25 miles south of Khulna.
   The cyclone struck three months after a flood inundated
three-quarters of Bangladesh and killed 1,500 people.
   A cyclone in 1985 killed at least 10,000 people, and one in 1970
claimed at least 500,000 lives.
</TEXT>
