<DOCNO> AP881205-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0906EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugBattle     12-05 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Battle,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Block Party Honors Anti-Drug Crusader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 70-year-old retired librarian who has
worked against drug dealing received a car as a gift of appreciation
at a block party thrown on her behalf by neighbors, police,
politicians and community leaders.
   Police believe Dorothy Erb's own car was firebombed by drug
dealers last month. There have been no arrests.
   The used car, a gift from a Sunnyvale man who admired Erb's
courage, was presented to her during the party Saturday that drew
about 300 people.
   ``A show of support is what will help the fight against drug
dealers,'' said George Bollog, the car's donor, who lives in a
relatively crime-free area.
   ``It could happen in my neighborhood someday. There's no place
that's immune to it. It's our collective reaction that will fight
it.''
   Erb said she was ``flabbergasted'' by the outpouring of support
for her. ``With this car, I am in my glory.''
   Erb has lived in her East Oakland neighborhood of small, older
homes and rundown apartment buildings for eight years. She became
active in the area's Home Alert program after a sharp increase in
burglaries in the last 18 months.
   She routinely reports to police the license plate numbers of
motorists involved in suspicious activities, and is a block captain
for Home Alert.
   Police Lt. Fred Peoples said there has been heavy drug dealing in
the neighborhood.
   Erb was home alone on the night of Nov. 9 when she heard a
popping sound outside and discovered her car in flames.
   ``It is like being in the middle of a war,'' she said.
``Sometimes I feel frightened, but when you are in the middle of it
you're too busy to worry.''
   The mood of Saturday's block party was primarily festive, with
free hot dogs, balloons, a puppet show, punch and gospel music. But
there was an underlying element of fear nonetheless.
   ``At first I was scared to come,'' said Jean Lea. ``But now I
feel good.''
   Betita Coty said Erb is a good example for others: ``Dorothy is
my kind of woman, a woman who can stand up for righteousness.''
   Luiza Gonzalez, who lives in the apartment building where dealers
are known to frequent hallways, says she showed up because she wants
the illegal activity stopped.
   ``People have their rights and they don't have to live this
way,'' she said.
</TEXT>
