<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Teen-ager Killed in Clash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with today's developments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed a 15-year-old
Palestinian girl today in a clash with stone-throwing schoolgirls in
a Gaza Strip refugee camp, witnesses and hospital officials said.
   Witnesses told Arab reporters that soldiers opened fire after
dozens of pupils at the Shati refugee camp threw stones at the
troops.One girl, identified as Asma Abu Obadah, died of a bullet
wound to the head, said officials at Shifa Hospital in nearby Gaza
City.
   A military spokesman said the army was checking the report.
   The girl is the 319th Palestinian killed in the Arab uprising
that began last Dec. 8. Most were killed by army gunfire. Eleven
Israelis also have been killed.
   At least eight Palestinians, most of them teen-agers, were shot
and wounded Sunday in scattered clashes in the West Bank and Gaza,
hospital officials said. The army said it also was checking the
reports.
   A top-ranking army official said Sunday that violence in the
Israeli-occupied territories was decreasing.
   ``In the struggle between civilian violence and security forces,
we see a gradual advantage ... of the Israeli security forces,''
Maj. Gen. Ehud Barak, Israel's deputy chief of staff, said on Israel
radio.
   Barak said that plastic bullets restored army deterrence, so that
a soldier ``has a clear feeling that when he raises his weapon, the
activity he faces disperses immediately.''
   Israel's use of plastic bullets, which penetrate the body and may
even kill if fired from a short distance, has provoked international
criticism. Israel defends the bullets as an efficient means of riot
control.
   Barak spoke several hours before a hand grenade was hurled at an
Israeli bus in the West Bank town of Hebron. It exploded on the
road, causing no injuries or damage.
   In another development, an Israeli woman told the daily Jerusalem
Post that she witnessed a rampage by troops in the village of Beita
near Nablus on Nov. 19.
   The woman, Judith Green, was quoted as saying she was told later
by villagers that a soldier had killed a 12-year-old boy by shooting
him in the head at point-blank range, the Post said.
   The army reported Nov. 23 that a boy died of a bullet wound to
the head after being shot in a clash with soldiers in Beita on the
day Ms. Green claims to have witnessed the rampage.
   An army spokeswoman said today the death was under investigation.
   Ms. Green, described as an Israel-American architect, was quoted
as saying she was in the village to discuss aid to Palestinians when
she saw soldiers ``trotting and along the way smashing every window
they passed with their rifle butts.
   ``Several of them paused alongside a terrace wall and took stones
from it, throwing them at the houses, cars, windows and shutters,''
she told the Post.
   On Sunday, a U.S.-born immigrant was sentenced to three years in
prison for the shooting death of an Arab shepherd who brought his
sheep to graze near the West Bank Jewish settlement of Shilo, 18
miles north of Jerusalem.
   Israel Zeev, 38, originally from Chicago, was convicted of
manslaughter last week for the killing of Jude Abdallah Awad, 28.
Zeev shot the shepherd while on guard duty in May.
   It was the first time a Jewish civilian was convicted in the
death of an Arab since the start of the uprising. Zeev also was
convicted for shooting and seriously injuring a second Arab.
   Zeev also was given a two-year suspended sentence and ordered to
pay the dead Arab's family $17,500 in compensation.
</TEXT>
