<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Saudi-Afghan     12-05 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saudi-Afghan,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrilla Leaders Said Dropping Resistance To Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas and Soviet
officials today ended their first face-to-face peace talks, and
sources said the guerrillas had softened their objections to an
international peace conference on Afghanistan.
   Sources close to the Afghan delegation, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the guerrillas agreed to study the proposal for a
conference but were demanding that Islamic nations, such as Pakistan
and Saudi Arabia, be allowed to participate.
   Pakistan is one of the main supporters of the guerrillas in their
nine-year war with the Soviet-backed government in Afghanistan. The
guerrillas have their headquarters in Pakistan.
   The guerrilla delegation was led by Burhanuddin Rabbani. The
Soviet delegation in the Saudi Arabian mountain resort of Taif was
led by deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov.
   Saudi Arabia supports the Afghan guerrillas and has linked
diplomatic relations with Moscow to an end to the Soviet
intervention in Afghanistan.
   Officially, Saudi Arabia maintained a distance from the talks it
organized in the town 600 miles southwest of the capital, Riyadh.
Prince Turki, the chief of intelligence, set up the talks.
   The sources expressed satisfaction at the ``marked progress''
achieved at the three informal sessions.
   The Soviets gave what was described as preliminary agreement to
hand over maps of the minefields laid in areas their troops were
leaving.
   ``The two sides have agreed on a number of points that can form a
good foundation for solving the Afghan problem and bringing peace to
Afghanistan,'' said one source.
   In a statement from Peshawar as the Taif talks started, the
guerrillas demanded immediate withdrawal of Soviet troops, payment
of war reparations, the removal of mines and maps of mined areas now
under Soviet control.
   The sources said there was agreement on side issues such as
prisoners of war, but they gave no details.
   Moscow and Afghan President Najib seek to convene an
international conference to demilitarize the country and set up a
coalition government with the guerrillas. The resistance had
rejected such a conference.
   The guerrillas were not party to an accord signed in Geneva in
April under which the Soviets agreed to withdraw their estimated
100,000 troops from Afghanistan by Feb. 15. They have continued
military operations against the Soviets, who suspended the
withdrawal until a cease-fire is reached. Half the Red Army force
remains in Afghanistan.
   The two sides agreed that the Taif meeting and its outcome does
not annul the articles of the Geneva accord, said the sources.
   Rabbani heads a loose alliance of the seven Afghan resistance
groups based in Peshawar, Pakistan. Other resistance leaders joined
Rabbani at the Taif talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
