<1ST_LINE>d i PM-Netherlands-RhinePollution     12-05 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Netherlands-Rhine Pollution,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Stop Drinking Water From Pesticide-Polluted Rhine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Amsterdam water authority has
stopped taking water from the Rhine because it is polluted by
pesticides from a spill at a West German chemical plant, a
spokeswoman said today.
   The intake point at Nieuwegein, 22 miles south of Amsterdam, was
closed Sunday after unacceptably high levels of the pesticide
Mecoprop were found in the Rhine, according to authority spokeswoman
Anthonia Schierman.
   ``It was accidentally dumped into the river on Nov. 28 by BASF,''
a chemical company in Ludwigshafen, West Germany, Mrs. Schierman
said. About 440 pounds of the toxic agent were spilled, she said.
   The Mecoprop content at the border was 7.2 micrograms a gallon,
nearly 10 times the acceptable level of .76 micrograms a gallon,
Mrs. Schierman said.
   She said the 1 million households in the Dutch capital and the
surrounding area are using water reserves that could last two months.
   Mrs. Schierman said the authority will resume taking in Rhine
water later this week. The water is pumped to reservoirs along the
Dutch coast and then filtered.
</TEXT>
