<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-TrainCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0474 12-05 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Train Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2 Killed In Commuter Train Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with higher injury toll, exact
cause of accident not known. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The impact...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter train whose driver apparently missed a
stop signal slammed into the back of another train in Tokyo today,
killing two people and injuring 97, police and railway authorities
said.
   Shuichiro Yamanouchi, vice president of East Japan Railways,
apologized for the crash at a news conference after the accident.
   Yamanouchi said 28-year-old Teruki Hirano, who was driving the
commuter train, might have missed a signal before plowing into the
back of a train stopped at the Higashi-Nakano Station, said a Japan
Railways official.
   Hirano and Yoji Abo, 31, a resident of Tokyo, were killed in the
9:40 a.m. collision, police said. They said two of the injured were
in critical condition.
   Police said the exact cause of the collision was not known.
   The impact crushed parts of two cars and derailed several cars.
About 10 fire department rescue teams worked to free people from the
cars. News reports said at least 600 people were on the two trains.
   Passengers said there was a huge crash and they were thrown to
the floor.
   ``The train was lifted up quite a bit and seats were broken and
thrown all over in the train,'' said an unidentified man in a
television interview.
   The railway official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
traffic signals on the rail line are controlled automatically to
signal approaching trains to stop.
   He said all East Japan Railways trains are connected to the
system, which also sounds a buzzer to warn drivers that a train is
blocking the line ahead.
   The buzzer, however, can be switched off by the driver and in
metropolitan Tokyo, drivers usually turn off the system for smoother
service during rush hours, the official said.
   It was possible that Hirano either missed the red light or had
his buzzer system off, the official said.
   News reports said westbound trains were running about 10 minutes
behind schedule when the commuter train rammed into the rear of the
other train.
   Keiko Uehara, who runs a bookstore near Higashi-Nakano station,
said the crash made such a noise that ``I thought a building had
fallen down.''
   Tokyo police are investigating the accident and questioning the
driver of the second train as well as the conductors on both trains,
police said.
   The accident was the first involving injuries on Tokyo commuter
trains since March 1986, when about 60 people were hurt in a
two-train collision.
   The last train accident in Japan involving fatalities was in
December 1984, when a train driver was killed and at least 120
people were injured in a head-on collision between two trains.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
