<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels     12-05 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Kills 15 Rebels, Captures Food Supply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopter-borne troops assaulted
communist rebels on two remote islands today, killing at least 15
insurgents and capturing three rebel supply boats loaded with rice,
military officials said.
   Brig. Gen. Alejandro Galido, military commander for southern
Luzon, said the dead included the chief of a village on Kalotkot
island whom he identified as a rebel and operator of the three
30-ton, wooden-hulled boats.
   ``The actual body count is 15 rebels dead,'' Galido said in a
telephone interview from his headquarters in Lucena City, 60 miles
southeast of Manila.
   He said the government suffered no casualties in fighting that
lasted eight hours after six helicopters transported army Scout
Rangers to Kalotkot and nearby Patnanungan island. The islands, in
the Polillo group off Quezon province, are 80 miles east of Manila.
   ``Practically the entire islands are controlled by the NPA,''
Galido said referring to the communist New People's Army.
   He said the rice was shipped to the islands to feed rebels
fleeing increased military operations around Quezon's Mount Banahaw
and the Bondoc Peninsula.
   Col. Hernani Figueroa, southern Luzon command spokesman, said in
a radio interview the troops also captured a truck and a car used by
rebels to transport guerrillas fleeing the Mount Banahaw area.
   Figueroa said some passengers were captured and being
interrogated.
</TEXT>
