<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LeadersSummit     12-05 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Leaders Summit,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Delegates To Conference Enjoy American-Style Recreation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After spending three days comparing countries
and getting to know each other, Soviet and American delegates at a
superpower conference said they have broken through the
``getting-to-know-you'' stage.
   ``We can speak open now,'' said Vladimir Plise, a cantor at a
Moscow synagogue.
   On Sunday, the 170 Soviet delegates and 169 American delegates to
the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Emerging Leaders Summit took advantage of the
chance to play tennis, racquetball, golf, billiards, chess and
volleyball at Cigna Corp.'s corporate center, Eagle Lodge, in
suburban Montgomery County.
   Plise called the facility ``clever, very organized.'' Although
the Soviet Union has similar centers _ he called them ``rest
houses'' _ they are not as big as Eagle Lodge, he said.
   Lilia Vlasova, a Soviet lawyer, said through an interpreter that
she enjoyed seeing American recreation.
   In her hometown of Minsk in the republic of Byelorussia, she said
she is helping plan a youth center and Eagle Lodge has given her
some ideas.
   Bruce Shaeffer, a spokesman for Eagle Lodge, said that although
Cigna has no delegates at the conference, the Philadelphia-based
insurer offered the use of the 280-acre center ``in the spirit of
cooperation.''
   On Saturday, the group got a different look at American sports by
attending the Army-Navy football game, in which Army defeated Navy
20-15.
   On Sunday morning, the delegates had brunch with congressional
representatives and other government officials.
   Delegates to the first-ever gathering of rising stars from the
two nations were chosen to be part of 16 commissions that are
discussing topics such as creative arts, international business,
mass media, the military, religion, education, science and medicine.
   During breaks Sunday, some of the delegates discussed the
progress of the seven-day conference.
   Vlasova said the domestic and international law commission will
discuss education of attorneys and the use of computers in teaching
law.
   Nikolai Devyatkin, a pastor at a church in northern Russia, said
the religion commission is discussing problems that churches face in
the two countries.
   He said he visited a black church in Philadelphia on Sunday and
was impressed by the emotion displayed.
   ``I have never seen that before today,'' he said.
   Plise, the cantor, said he too feels there are differences
between churches in the countries, but has not exactly figured them
out.
   ``We need time to understand this process,'' he said.
   While the Soviet delegates were far from their homeland, the
ethnic strife and nationalism boiling in some of the Soviet
republics was on the minds of some of them.
   Rein Kaarepere, assistant to the prime minister of Estonia, was
wearing the traditional blue, black and white colors of the Estonian
flag and speaks Estonian. He is among those who hope the once
sovereign country can establish an economy not beholden to Moscow.
   Only for the past year have Estonians been able to wear the
colors of their state, which was free between the first and second
world wars. The republic's leaders have led the charge in a recent
quest by Soviet minorities for greater autonomy.
   The Soviet Union, under Mikhail Gorbachev's perestroika, or
restructuring, is aiming for drastic change in its economic
structure. ``But it's another thing when this is warped to an
absurdity,'' said Viktor Mironenko, a member of the Supreme Soviet's
Presidium, the country's highest executive body, and also a delegate
to the conference.
   Elsewhere in the Soviet Union, nationalism has turned violent. At
least 60 people have died since February in ethnic rioting between
Armenians and Azebaijanis in the Soviet Caucasus region, near the
Middle East.
   Delegates from those republics canceled their trips to the
conference as violence flared again in recent weeks.
</TEXT>
