<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Dali,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Painter Leaves Intensive Care Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surrealist artist Salvador Dali left the
intensive care unit today, a week after being rushed to Quiron
Clinic because of heart trouble and blood clots in his lungs.
   A statement from his five doctors said the 84-year-old painter's
condition ``continues to improve favorably'' and that he was no
longer receiving medication intravenously.
   Dr. Juan Garcia San Miguel told reporters complications still
could arise, but ``the possibility he could suffer a setback is
greatly reduced.''
   Dali was taken to the clinic Nov. 28 from a hospital in his
hometown of Figueras, 60 miles north of Barcelona. He had entered
Figueras hospital the previous day suffering from pneumonia.
   The artist has been in poor health since August 1984, when a fire
broke out in the bedroom of his Pubol Castle residence in La Pera,
40 miles south of Figueras.
   After leaving the hospital three months later, Dali moved to his
Galatea Tower mansion attached to his Theater-Museum in Figueras.
   In July 1986 he underwent surgery in Barcelona to receive a
pacemaker.
   Dali, a founder of the Surrealist movement, is the last living
member of an outstanding generation of Spanish painters that
included Pablo Picasso, who died in 1973, and Joan Miro, who died a
decade later.
</TEXT>
