<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Seabrook     12-05 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Seabrook,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Hampshire Town Barred from Removing Nucelar Accident Warning
Sirens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today barred a New Hampshire
community from removing poles bearing sirens that could alert
townspeople about an accident at the controversial Seabrook nuclear
power plant.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that limits the
power of cities to revoke licenses for the poles.
   Public Service of New Hampshire, major owner of Seabrook, is
required by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to develop an
emergency evacuation plan in case of an accident at the plant.
   The utility company installed sirens placed on poles in several
seacoast communities, including Rye, N.H.
   The poles are about 60 feet high, with sirens weighing about 500
pounds attached to them.
   The Rye Board of Selectmen in 1984 licensed three poles in the
town. The New Hampshire Department of Transportation also authorized
poles on state highways, including state roads that pass through Rye.
   The board of selectmen then changed its mind and sought to revoke
the licenses. A state judge ordered the poles removed. But the New
Hampshire Supreme Court overruled the judge last March.
   Towns may not veto nuclear evacuation plans without good reason,
such as public safety, the state Supreme Court said.
   The state court said Rye selectmen ``lack the authority to revoke
the licenses they granted ... for any reason other than a reason
relating to the safe, free and convenient use for public travel of
the highway.'' The state court said the selectmen offered no
justification based on safety for removing the poles.
   The $5.6 billion Seabrook plant has been a target of protests
since before construction began in 1976.
   It was completed in 1986, but has been unable to get a federal
operating license. Federal regulators have yet to approve evacuation
plans for communities surrounding Seabrook, including some in
Massachusetts.
   There are also serious financial problems, with Public Service of
New Hampshire having filed for bankruptcy protection in January.
   The case is Rye vs. Public Service of New Hampshire, 88-621.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881205-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1044EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-InsuranceTaxes     12-05 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Insurance Taxes,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Resolve Decisions in Tax Dispute Over Louisiana Insurance
Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to resolve
conflicting decisions by federal appeals courts in a tax dispute
between the Internal Revenue Service and the life insurance industry.
   The court said it will decide whether the ``ceding commissions''
a life insurance company pays when reinsuring another firm's
policies may be claimed as tax deductions for the year they are paid.
   The IRS refused to let Colonial American Life Insurance Co., a
Lousiana-based corporation, claim some $1.5 million in such
deductions for 1975 and 1976.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the tax agency's
refusal last April but other appeals courts have allowed such
deductions.
   Colonial American's appeal to the nation's highest court was
supported by the American Council of Life Insurance and the National
Association of Life Companies.
   The Reagan administration, arguing that the 5th Circuit court
ruled correctly, nevertheless urged the justices to take the
Colonial American case to resolve the conflicting lower court
rulings.
   Colonial American in 1975 and 1976 agreed to partially indemnify
Transport Life Insurance Co. policies. In return, Colonial American
became entitled to the same percentage of future premiums received
on the policies.
   The agreements provided that Transport was to pay, as reinsurance
premiums, amounts equal to the reserves required to cover Colonial
American's liability on the policies.
   The reinsurance premiums were $675,762 for 1975 and $851,398 for
1976.
   The agreements also required Colonial American to pay Transport
Life ceding commissions in consideration for the business acquired.
The commissions totaled $680,000 in 1975 and $852,000 in 1976.
   Colonial American then sought to deduct as business losses the
full amount of the commissions in the years they were paid.
   The IRS disallowed the deductions, ruling that those amounts
represented the acquisition costs of future benefits. The tax agency
said that the ceding commissions should be capitalized and amortized
over the period of the policies' indemnification _ seven years.
   The U.S. Tax Court ruled for Colonial American but the 5th
Circuit court reversed that ruling.
   The case is Colonial American vs. Commissioner of Internal
Revenue, 88-396.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
