<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Indians     12-05 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Indians,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Ask for Comment in Arizona Reservation-Crime Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today asked the Justice
Department for its views on whether states may prosecute non-Indians
accused of crimes against Indians on tribal reservations.
   The court invited government lawyers to comment on an appeal by
Arizona officials seeking to prosecute a non-Indian school teacher
accused of sexual relations with Indian boys on a Navajo reservation.
   The justices are not expected to say whether they will grant full
review to the case until hearing from the government. That could
take months.
   A lower court ruled that the federal government has exclusive
authority to prosecute the man.
   The teacher, Conrad Marion Flint, was indicted twice by state
grand juries on charges of oral sexual contact with minors and
commercial sexual exploitation of minors.
   Flint, who is not an Indian, taught fifth grade students at the
Kayenta School District on the Navajo reservation.
   He allegedly lured Indian boys to his apartment, leased from the
Navajos, paid them to pose nude and engaged in sexual acts with them.
   The state said it seized more than 2,000 photographs and
videotapes from Flint's apartment.
   A state judge threw out the indictments on grounds only the
federal government may prosecute non-Indians for crimes against
Indians that take place on tribal reservations.
   The Arizona Court of Appeals upheld the judge's ruling last
January.
   The appeals court, citing a 1946 Supreme Court ruling, said Flint
``is charged with serious sexual crimes against several young Indian
males, thus creating a strong tribal interest.'' In such cases,
state officials lack authority to act, the state court said.
   The case is Arizona vs. Flint, 88-603.
</TEXT>
