<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-RICO     12-05 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-RICO,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Revive Lawsuit over Miami Gun Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive a
lawsuit seeking money for six injured FBI agents and for the
families of two agents killed in a Miami gun battle with two men who
also died.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that the agents
and their families should be allowed to use a federal
anti-racketeering law to recover damages from the estates of the two
alleged criminals.
   The shootout occurred on April 11, 1986, as the result of an FBI
investigation into a series of robberies, extortions and attempted
murders in the Miami area.
   After a car chase, the agents caught up with Michael Lee Platt
and William Russell Matix after the two men allegedly robbed the
Barnett Bank in Miami.
   In the ensuing gun battle, agents Benjamin Grogan and Jerry Dove
were killed along with Platt and Matix. The injured agents were John
Hanlon, Gordon McNeill, Edmundo Mireles, Richard Manauzzi, Gilbert
Orrantia and Ronald Risner.
   The agents and their families sought compensation under the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO).
   The federal law is used for criminal prosecutions and also
authorizes civil lawsuits for recovery of triple damages for ``any
person injured in his business or property'' by racketeering
activities.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last January upheld a
federal judge's ruling throwing out the suit.
   ``In our view, the ordinary meaning of the phrase `injured in his
business or property' excludes personal injuries, including the
pecuniary losses therefrom,'' the appeals court said. ``We do not
understand Congress to have authorized recovery for these injuries.''
   The 11th Circuit court noted that the Supreme Court in 1985
permitted wide latitude for civil suits invoking RICO and that the
law was being used in increasingly imaginative ways.
   But, the appeals court said, ``some limits on civil RICO still
exist.''
   The case is Grogan vs. Platt, 88-650.
</TEXT>
