<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BannedPlay     12-05 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banned Play,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School's Decision to Ban Holiday Play Upsets Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents and children say a school
district's ban on a non-biblical play based on the birth of Jesus
violates their First Amendemnt rights, but administrators say they
are upholding the Constitution.
   A fifth-grade class in central Michigan selected ``No Room at the
Inn'' from a book of plays in the school library. The play tells the
story of a coldhearted innkeeper who refuses a room to a pregnant
woman, then is transformed after the baby is born.
   Superintendent John Reynolds of the Waverly School District said
the play ``could be viewed as promotion of Christianity.''
   ``School officials are just trying to be sensitive to their
duties to abide by the law,'' schools attorney Scott Szpara said.
``The content appears to violate the (First) Amendment's
establishment clause, which forbids public schools from favoring or
encouraging any religion.''
   But parents say they are not buying the argument. They met
Saturday to press their demand for a special Board of Education
meeting Tuesday on the ban.
   ``The ban violates the children's constitutional right to free
speech and another First Amendment clause that prevents the state
from inhibiting the free exercise of religion,'' said David Kallman,
an attorney representing the parents.
   Several students expressed the same view.
   ``It's just not fair,'' said Peggy Huizen, 10, a fifth-grader.
``I can understand they don't like religious plays performed, but we
found this in our own school library in a book of traditional
holiday plays, `100 Plays for Children.' It's not a religious play.''
   Kallman said the play doesn't promote a specific religion because
it is a fictional account.
   ``Jesus' name isn't even in it,'' Kallman said.
</TEXT>
