<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SweatLodges 1stLd-Writethru a0046 12-05 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweat Lodges, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0046, </2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Inmates Sue Utah Prison Over Structure Used In Ancient Rites</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 2nd graf to state the suit was filed by six inmates.
The tribes are lending moral support, but are not the plaintiffs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simple dome-like structure used by Plains
Indians for ancient worship rites is the focus of a long-running
battle over religion and rehabilitation between tribal leaders and
Utah State Prison officials.
   Six Indian inmates are suing for the right to build sweat lodges
at the state's only maximum security prison, 25 miles south of Salt
Lake City.
   ``It's a form of worship and I think prison officials really
ought to be more cognizant of it as a rehabilitative tool,'' said
Travis Parashonts, a Paiute Indian who is director of the Utah
Office of Indian Affairs. ``It's a very uplifting and spiritual
experience.''
   But prison officials say the lodges represent a security risk,
and call the Indians' demand unreasonable.
   Permitting a sweat lodge would be akin to allowing ``a mosque and
minaret for the Moslems, a shrine for the Buddhists, a temple for
the Latter-day Saints, and a cathedral for the Catholics,'' said
Corrections Executive Director Gary DeLand, a defendant in the
20-month-old federal lawsuit that is scheduled for trial next month.
   The sweat lodge is a small structure made of willow poles covered
with blankets or dirt. They are often circular resembling tepees but
can be square, hutlike structures.
   Inside, usually about eight to 10 people sing and pray around a
pit of heated stones in a quest for purification, forgiveness and
spiritual renewal. Some Indians pray to a Great Spirit, who is the
father of all things and a life force; others pray to spirits
associated with various aspects of nature like rocks or animals.
   Tribal leaders have been frustrated by the prison ban on lodges,
particularly because nine other western states allow them in their
prisons. The other states include Arizona and Nevada, which like
Utah is where the 25,000-square-mile Navajo Reservation is located.
   The 180,000-member Navajo tribe has repeatedly offered to
construct a sweat lodge at its own cost _ estimated at only about
$50 _ and provide medicine men to conduct ceremonies.
   ``It wouldn't cost the state anything,'' said Larry Foster, the
tribe's director of intergovernmental relations. ``Given the fact
that we've been able to work with all the other states, I guess in a
sense it's perplexing.''
   Tribal officials say comparisons with structures for other
religions are unfair because sweat lodges can be built so quickly
and cheaply. They also dismiss fears of security risks.
   ``There is nothing there (at a sweat lodge ceremony) that could
be used in a negative manner,'' said Clifford Duncan, director of
the Ute Indian Museum at Fort Duchesne. There are about 2,200 Utes
living on the 2 million-acre Uintah and Ouray Reservation in eastern
Utah.
   The lawsuit was filed in March 1987 and is scheduled for trial
Jan. 9 in U.S. District Court.
   Plaintiffs' attorney Danny Quintana said he hoped newly elected
Attorney General Paul Van Dam, a Democrat, would be more flexible
than his predecessor, Republican David Wilkinson, and seek to settle
the issue out of court.
   ``He seems to have a little more common sense than his
predecessor but I don't know. I hope so,'' Quintana said.
   Van Dam said he plans to review the case but he would not discuss
the likelihood of a settlement. ``It's simply a matter that will
take me a few weeks to get to ... (but) that is an important case,''
he said.
   Foster said the Navajo will watch Van Dam's arrival with interest
but will ``continue, irregardless, to assist those inmates in the
practice of their religion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881205-0098 </DOCNO>
