<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CitiesConference 1stLd-Writethru a0447 12-05 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cities Conference, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0447,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Urban Agenda To Get Push From Local Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to update with Dukakis speech, picking up
at the 5th graf pvs, `Boston mayor ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis today urged leaders of the
nation's cities to keep the municipal issues that were raised during
the 1988 presidential campaign before the incoming Bush
administration.
   Homelessness and potential cuts in Medicare and Medicaid funding
were among the issues Dukakis cited in a speech to 5,000 delegates
to the 65th Congress of the National League of Cities, which
formally opened today.
   ``The issues we raised in the campaign haven't dissappeared
because the election is over,'' the former Democratic presidential
candidate said. ``We can not retreat. We can not go backwards.''
   Dukakis blamed a lack of affordable housing on cuts in federal
housing subsidies during the Reagan administration, but indicated he
and President-elect George Bush found some common ground on the
issue during their meeting last Friday.
   ``He called it a national disgrace, and it is,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis said forging partnerships among state and local
governments, the banking industry and building trade unions is
necessary to ease the housing crunch.
   More than 8,000 delegates from 1,300 local governments were
expected to attend the convention. The leagus is the nation's
largest municipal organization.
   Earlier, league officials said they will urge the Bush
administration to strengthen ties between local and federal
government.
   ``In the past there has not been a positive relationship between
the state and federal levels,'' the league's vice president, Mayor
Terry Goddard of Phoenix, said Saturday.
   Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn called the convention ``an
excellent opportunity to set an urban agenda for the nation's
cities.''
   League President Pamela P. Plumb, a Portland, Maine, city council
member and former mayor, said the nation's cities and towns ``will
bear the brunt of deficit reduction programs unless President-elect
Bush deals with revenue collection in a serious way.''
   She said critical issues cited by delegates for discussion at the
convention include affordable housing, economic development, job
training, fighting inner-city drug use and improving education.
   Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich said that during the past two
years, the federal government has cut state programs by 60 percent.
   ``A message needs to be sent to Washington saying no more
mandates, regulations or intrusion in state and local fiscal
affairs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
