<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Punitive 1stLd-Writethru a0543 12-05 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Punitive, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0543,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stage Set for Ruling on Punitive-Damage Awards in Texas-Vermont
Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 00-00, In other action, with other cases</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today set the stage for an
important ruling on the constitutionality of enormous
punitive-damage awards that have become increasingly common in a
range of lawsuits.
   The justices agreed to study the issue in an appeal by
Browning-Ferris Industries Inc., a waste collection business with
headquarters in Houston. The company was ordered to pay $6 million
to a Burlington, Vt., competitor that accused the Texas company of
undercutting its prices in an effort to drive it out of business.
   The high court last May declined to decide the constitutionality
of such enormous punitive-damage awards in personal-injury and
breach-of-contract cases.
   In its May ruling, the court cited narrow, procedural reasons for
upholding a $1.8 million judgment won by an injured Mississippi man
against an insurance company that wrongfully rejected his $20,000
claim.
   Left unresolved was the legitimacy of skyrocketing
punitive-damage awards, a development that has touched off a wave of
legislative activity, often called ``tort reform.''
   Some states, reacting to soaring insurance rates, have imposed
ceilings on how much punitive-damage money can be recovered.
   The court's decision last May, and its dismissal shortly
thereafter of several cases that mounted similar challenges to
punitive damages, indicated the justices were willing to give state
legislatures and state courts more time to study the issue.
   But the justices announced today they now will tackle the issue,
with a decision expected by July.
   The court will review a decision by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals last April that upheld the damage award against
Browning-Ferris.
   The company, with revenues in excess of $1.3 billion in 1986,
decided in 1973 to enter the waste disposal business in Burlington,
Vt.
   The company appointed Joseph Kelley to be district manager for
its new regional office.
   Kelley left Browning-Ferris in 1980 to form his own company,
Kelco Disposal Inc., which soon became a direct competitor.
   Kelco captured more than 40 percent of the market in the
Burlington region by 1982.
   There was testimony in the case that Browning-Ferris then
instructed its new Burlington manager to ``put Kelly out of
business. Do whatever it takes. Squish him like a bug.''
   Browning-Ferris then cut its prices almost in half. The
price-cutting maneuver prompted a suit by Kelly accusing
Browning-Ferris of attempting to monopolize the waste collection
market in the region in violation of antitrust laws.
   A jury awarded Kelco about $100,000 in compensatory damages and
on the antitrust claim and $6 million in punitive damages.
   The 2nd Circuit court said, ``We do not think the damages here
were so disproportionate as to be cruel, unusual or constitutionally
excessive.''
   In other action the court:
   _ Agreed to hear a Reagan administration appeal aimed at limiting
recovery of lawyers' fees for people who win disputes with the
government over Social Security benefits.
   The court said it will review a ruling that the government
reimburse attorneys' fees for an Alabama woman who won disability
benefits.
   _ Refused to revive a $70,000 award to a Tennessee woman who said
her rights were violated in a dispute with public school officials
over ``godless'' textbooks.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Vicki Frost, a
Christian fundamentalist briefly arrested for refusing to leave
school grounds during an attempt to remove her daughter from a
reading class.
   _ Agreed to decide whether a federal law allowing public scrutiny
of governmental advisory groups applies to the American Bar
Association's role in picking federal judges.
   The court said it will review a ruling that shields the ABA's
judicial selection committee from the law.
   _ Refused to bar police from conducting roadside sobriety tests
by setting up checkpoints at unannounced locations.
   The court, by a 7-2 vote, let stand a ruling from California that
such tests for drunken driving do not violate the rights of
motorists.
   _ Refused to revive a lawsuit seeking money for six injured FBI
agents and for the families of two agents killed in a Miami gun
battle with two men who also died.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that the agents
and their families should be allowed to use a federal
anti-racketerring law to recover damages from the estates of the two
alleged criminals.
   The punitive damages case is Browning-Ferris vs. Kelco Disposal,
88-556.
</TEXT>
