<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     12-05 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Novelist Testifies In Support of 11 Black Activists In Treason
Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's foremost
novelist, Nadine Gordimer, today testified in support of 11 black
activists at the start of a hearing to determine their sentences for
treason and terrorism.
   Four of the defendants, including three leaders of the country's
largest anti-apartheid group, were convicted of treason and seven of
terrorism last month after a trial that lasted more than three years.
   Two visiting U.S. Democratic senators, Sam Nunn of Georgia and
David Boren of Oklahoma, were among those crowding in a Pretoria
courtroom for today's hearing.
   Ms. Gordimer, one of several leading foes of apartheid called to
give mitigatory evidence, said she supported the goals of the ANC
and felt that its guerrilla campaign was justified.
   She said her fellow whites were to blame for stifling blacks'
non-violent protests.
   ``The time had to come that there had to be some military wing
(of the ANC),'' said Ms. Gordimer, a writer whose novels include
``July's People'' and ``Burger's Daughter.''
   The maximum penalty for treason and terrorism is death, but most
observers expect Pretoria Supreme Court Justice Kees van Dijkhorst
to impose prison sentences on the 11 black activists when the
hearing ends, possibly this week.
   In his verdict, van Dijkhorst ruled that the United Democratic
Front, a multiracial coalition formed in 1983 to seek black
political rights, was a revolutionary organization. He said the
front, which was banned in February, conspired with the outlawed
African National Congress to incite violence in 1984 aimed at making
South Africa ungovernable.
   Also testifying in support of the defendants were Professor Jakes
Gerwel, chief administrator of the predominantly mixed-race
University of the Western Cape, and Enos Mabuza, president of the
homeland of Kangwane.
   The three best-known defendants, all convicted of treason, are
Popo Molefe, 36, who was the United Democratic Front's national
secretary; Terror Lekota, 40, its publicity secretary, and Moses
Chikane, 40, secretary of its Transvaal Province branch.
   Murphy Morobe, who succeeded Lekota as the front's chief
spokesman, reportedly discussed the treason trial Sunday with the
U.S. senators, who are on a fact-finding trip.
   According to the independent South African Press Association,
Morobe told Nunn and Boren that the government was repressing young
anti-apartheid leaders while it was moving to release long-serving
political prisoners, possibly including ANC leader Nelson Mandela.
   ``We do not see the moves to release older activists as an act of
benevolence on the part of the government, but rather one which
takes the attention of the world away from what is being done to the
younger people who are expected to take over the reins,'' Morobe was
quoted as saying.
   Morobe and two colleagues spent five weeks holed up in the U.S.
Consulate in Johannesburg after escaping from detention on Sept. 13.
   In another trial today, a white conscientious objecter, Charles
Bester, was convicted of refusing to serve in the armed forces and
sentenced to six years in prison. Bester, 18, told a Johannesburg
magistrate his Christian beliefs would not allow him to serve in a
force which he felt was used to maintain apartheid.
   Under apartheid, blacks have no vote in ntional affairs. The
white minority controls the government and has separate districts,
schools and health services.
</TEXT>
