<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SavannahRiver     12-05 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savannah River,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Outlines Conditions For Savannah River Reactor Restart</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 5th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent safety committee will meet
next week to discuss the prerequisites for restarting one of the
three closed Savannah River Plant nuclear reactors, and one member
says it will be difficult to meet a target of spring or summer for
the restart.
   A Department of Energy report on the restart calls for an
unprecedented, top-to-bottom inspection of the reactor, as well as
comprehensive changes in written procedures, training and staffing
throughout the government-owned nuclear weapons fuel plant at Aiken.
   The reactors have been closed for safety reasons.
   Officials from the Energy Department and the Department of
Defense are anxious for Savannah River to resume operation because
it is the nation's only producer of tritium, a radioactive gas that
is critical for nuclear warheads.
   Pentagon experts have said that if Savannah River does not have
all three reactors operating by next summer, extraordinary steps
might be needed, including deactivating warheads and transferring
their tritium to higher-priority weapons.
   On Tuesday, Energy Secretary John S. Herrington said one of the
reactors at the troubled plant would open by spring or summer.
   Elmer Schwartz, a member of an independent safety committee
established this year by Herrington, said it is possible to follow
the report's guidelines and meet the deadline, but ``it will take a
hell of an effort.''
   But some Energy Department officials and independent safety
experts believe it will take far longer, possibly extending into
early 1990, The New York Times and The State newspapers reported.
   Robert M. Keller, a senior nuclear engineer at the Energy
Department who wrote the restart plan, told the Times it may take
until December 1989 to start up the first of the reactors. The
newspaper said engineers estimated that it would take until the end
of 1990 to restart the others.
   The full safety committee is scheduled to review the start-up
criteria Dec. 13 and 14 in Washington. The plan reviewed by the
committee will be final and contain a specific target date for the
restart.
   Savannah River's three operable reactors were limited to 50
percent power in March 1987 because of concerns about the ability of
their emergency cooling systems to prevent melting of the
radioactive core during an accident.
   Once the reactors are returned to service, power levels may be
further reduced because of safety questions, The State reported.
   No matter how long the overhaul of the first reactor takes,
Schwartz and others believe the new procedures will enhance overall
safety at Savannah River and at 16 other Energy Department weapons
production facilities. Over the past eight months, each has come
under increasing public and congressional scrutiny spawned by
decades of lax safety practices.
   Energy Department officials have proposed replacing the three
aging Savannah River reactors with a $4 billion, heavy-water reactor.
   Rep. Lindsay Thomas, D-Ga., whose congressional district lies
across the state line from the Savannah River Plant, said he would
oppose funding for the new reactor because of the facility's poor
safety record. Thomas, a member of the House Appropriations
Committee, was to testify today at an Energy Department
environmental hearing in Savannah on the proposed reactor.
</TEXT>
