<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeensKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0489 12-05 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teens Killed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Teens Killed in Oregon Traffic Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after the 3rd to update with community
reaction, and Inserts 2 grafs after the 6th graf previous, ``I
couldn't,'' with school reaction.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARRENTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six teen-agers en route to a party were
killed when their compact car swerved in front of a pickup truck and
was crushed, police said.
   ``This is the worst wreck I've ever seen,'' John Meiners, a
safety officer with an area volunteer fire department, said after
the Friday night accident. ``I haven't seen anything like this since
I was an 18-year-old Marine in Vietnam putting bodies in
helicopters.''
   Sheriff John Raichl said there was no evidence that any of the
teen-agers had been drinking before the accident on U.S. 101 along
the northern Oregon coast.
   ``It's unbelievable in a town this size to have six kids go just
like that,'' said Art Stromsness of Hughes-Ransom Mortuary. The town
has 2,500 residents.
   The victims were identified as Debra Raappana, 19, of Clatskanie,
the driver and owner of the car; Tim Morgan, 17, of Astoria; Jason
Hurly, 16, of Hammond; and Kenneth Goin, 16, Darren Godwin, 15, and
Steven Cory Bingaman-Story, 15, all of Warrenton.
   Morgan's brother, Keith, 16, was among the first to arrive at the
accident scene. The victims had forced him to ride with some other
teens in another vehicle because the compact car was too crowded.
   ``I couldn't see anyone in there,'' he said. ``I called my
brother's name, but he didn't answer.''
   Raappana attended Clatsop Community College in Astoria and the
other five were enrolled at Warrenton High School, which has 250
students.
   Jim Hendrickson, 17, of Warrenton, a junior, knew five of the
victims. ``They were pretty nice folks,'' he said. ``They were
well-accepted in school.''
   The pickup driver, Robert John Larson, a 28-year-old U.S. Coast
Guard member from Warrenton, was treated at a hospital for cuts and
bruises and released.
   Deputy Sheriff Mark Whisler said Larson reported he barely had
time to hit the brakes before the teen-agers' car crossed his path.
Raichl said it did not appear the pickup had been speeding.
</TEXT>
