<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Korea-Hungary     12-05 0122</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Korea-Hungary,0127</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary Opens Permanent Mission in South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary opened a permanent diplomatic
mission in Seoul on Monday, becoming the first communist nation to
do so, the Foreign Ministry said.
   South Korea opened a permanent mission in Budapest Oct. 25.
   The two countries have agreed to continue negotiations toward
full diplomatic relations.
   Communist North Korea is strongly opposed to the diplomatic link
between Hungary, its ally, and rival South Korea.
   Seoul is seeking ties with communist countries, including China
and the Soviet Union, to try to ease tension on the divided Korean
peninsula.
   Yugoslavia also has opened a trade office in Seoul, and Poland,
Bulgaria and the Soviet Union have signed accords to do likewise.
</TEXT>
