<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Pope-Bulgaria     12-05 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Pope-Bulgaria,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Discusses Religious Freedom With Bulgarian Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Monday discussed
religious freedom with the Bulgarian foreign minister, a Vatican
spokesman said.
   Foreign Minister Petar Mladenov, who is on a two-day official
visit to Italy, had a 20-minute private audience with the pope.
   The talks were held ``in the framework of normal contacts that
the Holy Father maintains with civil authorities with the aim of
guaranteeing Catholics real space for religious freedom,'' said
spokesman Joaquin Navarro.
   It was Mladenov's second meeting with John Paul. The previous
visit was in December 1978.
   Navarro said there are 80,000 Roman Catholics in Bulgaria, which
has a population of 9 million.
   Freedom of religion in guaranteed by law in Bulgaria, although as
in most Soviet bloc countries, it has a state organization to
oversee religious affairs.
</TEXT>
