<2ND_LINE>PM-Sununu-Environment,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sununu Says Bush Will Protect Environment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VAIL, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu says George
Bush will maintain his interest in Western and environmental issues
after he becomes president because he has had a ``lifelong love
affair with the outdoors.''
   ``I think you are going to see a lot of attention paid by George
Bush to outdoor issues,'' Sununu, the president-elect's choice for
chief of staff, said over the weekend during a break from skiing.
   Sununu, who will assume his new post when Bush takes office in
January, spent several days skiing at the Vail and Beaver Creek
resorts in the Rocky Mountains and visiting with friends. Though New
Hampshire has its share of ski areas, most are not yet open for the
season.
   He said the Bush administration hopes to strike a balance between
the concerns of environmentalists and the nation's need to use
natural resources.
   ``It's a shame in this country that, during the political season,
some of the constituency groups have a natural affinity for one
party or the other,'' he said. ``It is difficult for Republicans to
wean environmental groups away from the Democrats.''
   A recent meeting between Bush and environmentalists was just the
beginning of a dialogue between the two, he said.
   ``Since the election, they've had a chance to look at the reality
of Bush's background and what he wants to accomplish,'' Sununu said.
   Sununu said he plans to make a special effort to see that Bush
gets input from regular citizens as well as Washington insiders.
   ``We will have an outreach effort to keep in touch with the
states, the communities and individual citizens,'' he said.
</TEXT>
