<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BodiesExhumed 2ndLd-Writethru a0570 12-05 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bodies Exhumed, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0570,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested in Deaths Of Nursing Home Residents
^Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after the 2nd to update with police news
conference; Subs the 10th graf previous, ``Walker Police,'' to
delete redundant first reference to chief; and Subs the last 2 grafs
with 1 to delete redundancies and tighten.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WALKER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested two women in connection
with the suspicious deaths of eight nursing home residents whom
authorities originally believed had died of natural causes.
   Both women are former employees of the Alpine Manor Nursing Home,
where authorities say eight residents may have been suffocated in
their beds.
   Walker Police Chief Walter Sprenger declined to speculate on the
motive during a news conference today.
   ``A lot of this will come out during the trial,'' Sprenger said.
``I cannot share evidence that will be detrimental to the case.''
   He said the results of autopsies conducted on two bodies that
were exhumed were inconclusive.
   Police in this Grand Rapids suburb arrested a 26-year-old Grand
Rapids woman early today and were holding her in the Kent County
Jail, Deputy Thomas Zlydaszyk said.
   A 25-year-old woman was arrested late Sunday in Tyler, Texas, and
was being held in the Smith County Jail, Sheriff Jay B. Smith said
today.
   Authorities in both counties withheld the women's names pending
arraignment.
   The Grand Rapids Press reported today that the women lived
together while working at the nursing home, according to the
ex-husband of the Grand Rapids woman and other friends and former
co-workers. The woman in Texas worked as a nurse's aide at a
hospital until recently, the newspaper said.
   The eight deaths being investigated occurred during the first
half of 1987. At the time, their deaths were considered natural and
no autopsies were done.
   The Texas woman worked at the home from June 1986 to June 1987,
according to Ginny Seyferth, spokeswoman for Alpine Manor. The Grand
Rapids woman worked there from July 1985 to October 1988 and most
recently was a supervisor of nurse's aides, Seyferth said.
   The state Department of Public Health said Sunday it also was
investigating the Alpine deaths as standard procedure in cases of
unusual occurrences that involve patients, said Walter Wheeler III,
acting chief of the bureau of health facilities.
   Sprenger confirmed Saturday that the investigation had expanded
to cover eight deaths.
   Police said earlier that the investigation was limited to the
deaths of Marguerite Chambers, 60, and Edith Cook, 98, whose bodies
underwent autopsies after being exhumed last week.
   About 40 patients died at the nursing home during January-April
1987, when the eight suspicious deaths occurred, Seyferth said
Sunday.
   Sprenger said detectives began investigating the deaths in early
October, using a list of ``eight potential victims'' provided by a
source he refused to identify.
   ``We've continued on because we are convinced that something has
occurred,'' Sprenger said, adding that police were investigating
reports that some victims had been suffocated.
   Sprenger said at least one other body might be exhumed. Three of
the eight were cremated.
</TEXT>
