<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dali     12-05 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dali,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dali Leaves Intensive Care Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvador Dali was transferred from the
intensive care unit to a room Monday, a week after he was
hospitalized because of heart trouble and blood clots in his lungs.
   The 84-year-old painter ``continues to improve favorably'' and he
was no longer receiving medication intravenously, according to his
doctors.
   Dr. Juan Garcia San Miguel said complications still could arise,
but ``the possibility he could suffer a setback is greatly reduced.''
   King Juan Carlos visited Dali briefly Monday at the Quiron
Clinic. The monarch said Dali told him he was hoping to get well
enough to return to painting.
   The artist was taken to the clinic Nov. 28 from a hospital in his
hometown of Figueras, 60 miles north of Barcelona. He had entered
Figueras hospital the previous day suffering from pneumonia.
   Dali has been in poor health since 1984, when a fire broke out in
the bedroom of his Pubol Castle residence in La Pera, 40 miles south
of Figueras.
   After leaving the hospital three months later, Dali moved to his
Galatea Tower mansion attached to his Theater-Museum in Figueras.
   He received a pacemaker in 1986.
   Dali, a founder of the surrealist movement, is the last living
member of an outstanding generation of Spanish painters that
included Pablo Picasso, who died in 1973, and Joan Miro, who died a
decade later.
</TEXT>
