<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Centenarian     12-05 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Centenarian,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Village Patriarch Believes He's 149 Years Old</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wispy, white-haired man living in a
remote village believes he is 149 years old, The Times of India
reported Monday.
   Kellabhai Navrabhai Rathwa was surrounded by five generations of
his family when he was interviewed in Borkhad, 500 miles southwest
of New Delhi, the newspaper said.
   The 1989 Guinness Book of World Records lists the authenticated
longevity record of 120 years, 237 days, for Shigechiyo Izumi of
Japan, who died in 1986.
   The Times of India said the illiterate farmer reckons his age by
the region's great famine of 1856, when his mother told him he would
have to leave home.
   The newspaper reporter pointed out that Rathwa's mother was
hardly likely to know his age in an area where even today parents
cannot precisely relate their children's ages.
   ``I could not have been less than 16 years, otherwise I would not
have been paid the wages paid to an adult laborer then _ eight annas
per day,'' Rathwa said.
   An anna, a coin that has been out of circulation for three
decades, would be worth 3 cents today.
   Rathwa, father of 22 children, said he chopped trees and helped
build roads until the famine passed.
   The Times said Rathwa's memory was sharp, but because of the
isolation of his village he was unaware of great events. He did not
know that World War I and World War II had happened and had no
concept of a bomb.
   But he had heard of Bombay, the metropolis 220 miles south,
because ``those white-skinned men who once ruled the land of India''
used to hunt near his village.
   He said a nearby narrow-gauge railroad was laid ``only
recently.'' Records show the track is more than 60 years old.
   The Times said Rathwa walked with the help of a cane and his
vision was blurred but his hearing was perfect and most of his teeth
were intact.
</TEXT>
