<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Sicily-Strike     12-05 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sicily-Strike,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike By Public Employees in Palermo Ends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grave diggers, clerks, garbage collectors
and other public employees went back to work Monday after a two-week
strike that crippled this Sicilian capital.
   The strike closed schools in the absence of city-employed
janitors, affected traffic control, and halted the issuing of birth
certificates. Newborn babies were left stranded in hospitals because
under Italian law they cannot be released without the certificates.
   The strike ended after unions urged workers to return to their
jobs pending a Dec. 14 decision on their demands by a provincial
commission.
   The strike began 13 days ago because of a dispute over the
schedule of retroactive pay to city employees. A court ruled the
payments should be made in installments over a 24-month period, but
employees demanded they be paid over a 12-month period.
</TEXT>
