<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1307EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Carlucci     12-05 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says Iran Learned `Terrorism at Sea Doesn't Pay'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS LA SALLE IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. forces were a
key to halting the Persian Gulf war and taught Iran ``terrorism on
the high seas does not pay political dividends,'' Defense Secretary
Frank C. Carlucci said Monday.
   He delivered the message at an awards ceremony aboard the La
Salle, flagship of the U.S. Navy task force, and repeated it during
a brief news conference on the third day of a four-day gulf tour.
   In answer to a question, Carlucci defended the U.S. denial of a
visa for Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat to
address the U.N. General Assembly in New York. The assembly session
will move to Geneva as a result.
   Arab gulf states joined a ``not surprisingly negative reaction''
to the decision by U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz, he said,
but added that none had raised the issue during his trip. Shultz
refused the visa on grounds Arafat condones terrorism.
   Carlucci came here from Oman was to visit Saudi Arabia and Kuwait
before returning to Washington on Wednesday.
   He delivered a personal message from President Reagan to Sheik
Isa bin Salman al Khalifa, emir of Bahrain, and confered with Sheik
Khalifa bin Ahmed al Khalifa, the defense minister, who met him at
the airport.
   They discussed ``bilateral relations and issues of common
interest,'' the official Gulf News Agency reported.
   U.S. sources said privately the Bahrainis registered displeasure
about the Arafat visa controversy by what one called a
``downgrading'' of protocol ``so subtle that only the U.S.
government is likely to notice it.''
   The source said the message was conveyed mainly by the fact that
Carlucci was met by the defense minister rather than the crown
prince, Sheik Hamad bin Isa bin Salman al Khalifa, who had greeted
him in January.
   Carlucci said events that culminated in the Aug. 20 truce in the
8-year-old war between Iran and Iraq vindicated the U.S. decision to
have a strong naval presence in the gulf.
   ``Results speak for themselves,'' he told officers and crew
assembled on the La Salle's flight deck.
   ``Through your actions, in large measure, you have helped bring
an end to one of the bloodiest wars in history,'' he said.
   ``We have succeeded in convincing Iran that terrorism on the high
seas does not pay political dividends. We have demonstrated that we
can stand by our friends, and we have demonstrated that we know who
our friends are.''
   He said the largest U.S. naval operation since Vietnam also
``demonstrated to the world our ablity to project power, to show
determination and to defend vital principles including the principle
of freedom of navigation.''
   At the news conference, Carlucci said those actions ``in turn .
.. contributed to a substantial degree to the cease-fire'' and to
``maintaining the flow of oil through the Strait of Hormuz,''
gateway to the Persian Gulf.
   All four gulf states on Carlucci's itinerary have provided some
support to the U.S. effort to keep commercial shipping lanes open
and discourage Iranian threats and attacks.
   Some European navies are pulling out of the gulf, but Carlucci
indicated the United States was in no rush to reduce its forces,
which have been trimmed by two ships to 25 since the truce.
   He said the Pentagon was ``not talking about any specific
drawdown'' and had ``set no numerical targets.''
   ``What we want to do is remain alert and ready, until we're
confident that the cease-fire will take hold,'' he said, and with
U.N.-sponsored peace talks ``going very slowly ... we think it is
prudent for us to maintain a fairly good presence in the gulf until
there are some further developments.''
   Carlucci presented achievement awards to four sailors: Seaman
Kenneth P. Gross of Keewatin, Minn.; Chief Warrant Officer 4 Gary L.
Pugh of Corvallis, Ore.; Quartermaster 2 Terry D. Yarbrough of
Memphis, Tenn., and Intelligence Specialist 2 Ronald S. Fry Jr. of
Miami.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
