<DOCNO> AP881205-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     12-05 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,620</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   PUNITIVE-DAMAGE AWARDS
   
   The court set the stage for an important ruling on the
constitutionality of enormous punitive-damage awards that have
become increasingly common in a range of lawsuits.
   The justices agreed to study the issue in an appeal by
Browning-Ferris Industries Inc., a waste collection business with
headquarters in Houston. The company was ordered to pay $6 million
to a Burlington, Vt., competitor that accused the Texas company of
undercutting its prices in an effort to drive it out of business.
   The case is Browning-Ferris vs. Kelco Disposal, 88-556.
   
   LAWYERS FEES
   
   The court agreed to hear a Reagan administration appeal aimed at
limiting recovery of lawyers' fees for people who win disputes with
the government over Social Security benefits.
   The court said it will review a ruling that the government
reimburse attorneys' fees for an Alabama woman who won disability
benefits.
   The case is Bowen vs. Hudson, 88-616.
   
   TEXTBOOKS
   
   The court refused to revive a $70,000 award to a Tennessee woman
who said her rights were violated in a dispute with public school
officials over ``godless'' textbooks.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Vicki Frost, a
Christian fundamentalist briefly arrested for refusing to leave
school grounds during an attempt to remove her daughter from a
reading class.
   The case is Frost vs. Hawkins County Board, 88-604.
   
   ABA
   
   The court agreed to decide whether a federal law allowing public
scrutiny of governmental advisory groups applies to the American Bar
Association's role in picking federal judges.
   The court said it will review a ruling that shields the ABA's
judicial selection committee from the law.
   The cases are Public Citizen vs. Justice Department, 88-429, and
Washington Legal Foundation vs. Justice Department, 88-494.
   
   SOBRIETY TESTS
   
   The court refused to bar police from conducting roadside sobriety
tests by setting up checkpoints at unannounced locations.
   The court, by a 7-2 vote, let stand a ruling from California that
such tests for drunken driving do not violate the rights of
motorists.
   The case is Richard T. vs. California, 88-318.
   
   GUN BATTLE
   
   The court refused to revive a lawsuit seeking money for six
injured FBI agents and for the families of two agents killed in a
Miami gun battle with two men who also died.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that the agents
and their families should be allowed to use a federal
anti-racketerring law to recover damages from the estates of the two
alleged criminals.
   The case is Grogan vs. Platt, 88-650.
   
   SEABROOK
   
   The court barred a New Hampshire community from removing poles
bearing sirens that could alert townspeople about an accident at the
controversial Seabrook nuclear power plant.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that limits the
power of cities to revoke licenses for the poles.
   The case is Rye vs. Public Service of New Hampshire, 88-621.
   
   INSURANCE TAXES
   
   The court agreed to resolve conflicting decisions by federal
appeals courts in a tax dispute between the Internal Revenue Service
and the life insurance industry.
   The court said it will decide whether the ``ceding commissions''
a life insurance company pays when reinsuring another firm's
policies may be claimed as tax deductions for the year they are paid.
   The case is Colonial American vs. Commissioner of Internal
Revenue, 88-396.
   
   INDIANS
   
   The court asked the Justice Department for its views on whether
states may prosecute non-Indians accused of crimes against Indians
on tribal reservations.
   The court invited government lawyers to comment on an appeal by
Arizona officials seeking to prosecute a non-Indian school teacher
accused of sexual relations with Indian boys on a Navajo reservation.
   The case is Arizona vs. Flint, 88-603.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
