<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Politics Bjt   12-05 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics, Bjt,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Extends Time for Coalition Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president gave Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
another three weeks to form a government, urging him Monday to forge
a coalition with Labor and reform a complex system that has produced
two stalemated elections.
   President Chaim Herzog said Israel's political parties are
bargaining for position while political and economic problems
approach crisis proportions.
   His appeal for national unity came after three weeks of political
jockeying by Shamir's rightist Likud bloc, the rival center-left
Labor Party of Foreign Minister Shimon Peres and small
ultra-Orthodox religious parties.
   Shamir and Peres have been equal partners in a ``national unity''
since inconclusive 1984 elections, and traded jobs two years ago. In
the Nov. 1 elections, Likud won 40 of the 120 parliament seats and
Labor got 39.
   Speaking at the ceremony at his residence in which he gave Shamir
the extension, Herzog said the new government should change Israel's
electoral system, which resulted in parliament seats for 15 parties
Nov. 1 but left no party with a majority.
   ``There is no parallel in the democratic world for our odd and
incomprehensible system,'' Herzog said with Shamir at his side.
   ``I believe that I speak for the great majority of Israel's
people when I express a sense of frustration, helplessness,
humiliation and shame, as well as grave concern.''
   Of anti-religious sentiment resulting from demands by
ultra-Orthodox parties for special laws and regulations in exchange
for joining a coalition, Herzog said: ``Confused and dangerous
emotions are being aroused. ... There are attitudes that recall the
dark days of anti-Jewish persecution.''
   He recommended another Likud-Labor coalition, although Shamir has
been edging in recent days toward a narrow government with small
right-wing and Orthodox factions. Religious parties won a total of
18 seats in the Knesset, Israel's parliament.
   Herzog said: ``I shall repeat what I said three weeks ago: the
state of Israel needs a broad government. It must have a stable
government if it is to stand up to the perils and challenges which
face it.''
   Peres agreed with the president about reform. ``After each
election ... the major parties, instead of arguing between them
about the central issues, compete for the support of the religious
parties,'' he said. ``This is absurd. We must change the system.''
   Shamir would not speak with reporters after meeting with Herzog.
   He has lined up 65 of the 120 Knesset seats with the support of
small parties but his 21-day mandate ran out Monday and he requested
an extension, as allowed by law.
   Religious parties have demanded a law that would recognize only
conversions to Judaism made by Orthodox rabbis, which the
Conservative and Reform movements oppose. They also want important
Cabinet posts and strict enforcement of the Jewish sabbath.
   Agudat Israel, a relgious party with five Knesset seats, kept the
entire country waiting Sunday night while its spiritual mentors, the
Torah Sages, decided whether to honor an agreement signed with Labor
last week. They broke it, opening the way for a Likud government.
   The popular tabloid Yediot Ahronot published a list Monday of 17
promises it said Likud made to Agudat Israel, including three
ministries, the powerful position of Parliament Finance Committee
chairman and pledges to ban abortion and advertisements featuring
scantily clad women.
   Editorial cartoonists have skewered the religious parties almost
daily.
   A cartoon in the Yediot Ahronot showed a tank topped by the black
hat traditionally worn by the ultra-Orthodox, its cannon pointed at
Peres and Shamir. The caption said: ``Your money ... and your soul.''
</TEXT>
