<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     12-05 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Calls For Law and Order, Warns Against Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo called for law
and order Monday after naming a new Cabinet, indicating his
government will crack down on violent protesters.
   ``Democracy means order, not confusion. It is the people's wish
that the government's just public power must be established,'' Roh
told his new Cabinet.
   In the most extensive reorganization since he took office in
February, Roh named a new premier and replaced 19 Cabinet ministers
Monday.
   But opponents said he failed to purge the government of the
``dictatorial'' legacy of his disgraced predecessor Chun Doo-hwan.
   It seemed unlikely the much-heralded changes would have a major
impact on public opinion or help still widespread demands for Chun's
punishment.
   Roh said the new Cabinet's first priority is to maintain law and
order by taking a resolute stand on ``leftist and terrorist groups''
_ official shorthand for violent anti-government forces.
   He named retired general and former ambassador to Britain Kang
Young-hoon as prime minister and replaced all but three of his
ministers in an effort to appease raging public anger over Chun and
show his commitment to democratic reforms.
   Kang said his main concern is to wipe out ``excessive
authoritarianism'' that marked the Chun government.
   The shuffle affected several Cabinet-level posts, including the
promotion of Seoul Olympic organizer Park Seh-jik to head the main
intelligence organization, the Agency for National Security Planning.
   Government officials, requesting anonymity, said Roh is expected
to revamp the leadership of his Democratic Justice Party in the next
few days and remove some Chun confidants.
   Presidential spokesman Lee Soo-jung said the changes would
``ensure further democratic reforms and put the mind of the public
at rest following the anxiety created by problems of the past era.''
   But opposition parties showed disappointment in appointments of
what they called ``hardline rightists'' from the governing party.
   They said Roh has not fulfilled promises to cut ties with Chun's
authoritarian government.
   ``We are surprised that the new Cabinet includes persons who
actively supported dictatorship,'' said Lee Sang-soo, spokesman for
Kim Dae-jung's main opposition Party for Peace and Democracy.
   The Democratic Reunification Party said, ``We are skeptical about
the government's intention to liquidate the Chun government.''
   Opposition leaders are especially critical of keeping in the
Cabinet Administration Minister Kim Yong-gap, whom they consider
``ultra-rightist.'' Most dismissed ministers were little-known.
   Dissident groups that have organized violent protests demanding
Chun's arrest and Roh's overthrow, dismissed the Cabinet changes as
a deception to continue military-backed rule.
   Among major appointments:
   _ Cho Sung, a university economics professor and champion of
balanced economic development, was named economic planning minister.
Analysts said his appointment could signal a shift to more balanced
distribution of wealth.
   Former Gen. Lee Sang-hoon was named defense minister despite
previous government hints the key ministry would go to a civilian.
Lee filled top military posts under Chun.
   _ Legislator Lee Han-dong, who ran the governing party under
Chun, was made home minister with control of police.
   _ Huh Hyong-koo, a former prosecutor-general under Chun, was
named justice minister.
</TEXT>
