<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StrainedClergy     12-05 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Strained Clergy,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Churches To Take Up Special Collections For Retired Clergy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catholic churches nationwide will take up a
special collection this weekend to help support increasing numbers
of retired nuns and priests, church officials say.
   Most religious communities cannot afford the estimated $10,000
annual cost of caring for an elderly member of a religious order
because the number of young clergy men and women who provide
financial support is dwindling, they said.
   The Lilly Endowment Inc., based in Indianapolis, is assisting the
project.
   Without the special collections, some religious orders may have
to break up and sell their property, said Sister Mary Luke Jones,
development director for Our Lady of Grace Monastery in Beech Grove.
   Sister Mary Margaret Funk, the monastery's prioress, said the
100-member community ended the last fiscal year with a deficit
typical of those reported nationwide _ about $250,000.
   Financial problems in religious communities didn't develop
overnight. Men and women worked for years with low salaries and no
money set aside by the church for their retirements.
   Sister Jane Bodine of the Sisters of Providence said many nuns
received only $1,000 a year until the 1970s. And Sister Mary
Margaret noted that the Benedictines did not start making Social
Security payments for members until 1972. Social Security pays a
retired nun about $2,500 a year, she said.
   The Sisters of Providence, based at St. Mary-of-the-Woods near
Terre Haute, has 850 members. More than one-third of them are older
than 70.
   The retirement collections will be conducted each December for 10
years. Donations will be sent to the Tri-Conference Retirement Fund
for Men and Women Religious in Washington, D.C.
   That office, through a Lilly Endowment grant, will provide
management and financial planning assistance for religious
communities with unfunded retirement fund liabilities.
   The Tri-Conference Retirement Fund was set up in 1987 by the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, the Leadership Conference
of Women Religious and the Conference of Major Superiors of Men
after the depth of the crisis was discovered. A study indicated
there would be a $3 billion shortfall even if all assets of
religious communities were used for retirement needs.
</TEXT>
