<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0598 12-05 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0598,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bombs Kill One, Injure Six</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 3 injured in village. SUBS 10th graf
``Police said ...'' with 2 grafs to elaborate on explosion in
village. Picks up 11th graf pvs ``The two blasts...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded Monday across from a
hospital in Moslem west Beirut, killing one pedestrian and injuring
six, destroying cars and hurling patients from their beds, police
and witnesses said.
   A second car bomb exploded near a Syrian army checkpoint in the
easten Bekaa valley, injuring three people, police said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the attacks.
   A police spokesman said a gray Peugeot packed with an estimated
110 pounds of TNT exploded across the street from Baydoun Hospital
in west Beirut's Sanayeh residential district.
   None of the troops manning a Syrian checkpoint about 75 yards
from the hospital was injured, said the spokesman, who cannot be
identified under standing briefing rules.
   Syrian soldiers nervously cordoned off the hospital area as
ambulances with sirens wailing rushed the victims to the American
Unversity Hospital about six blocks away.
   A nurse at the hospital said the force of the blast hurled most
of the hospital's 36 patients out of bed as shrapnel tore through
the windows.
   ``Luckily there were no surgeries under way in the operating
theater,'' said the nurse, who refused to give her name. ``The
explosion would have definitely shaken the hands of the surgeons
which could have affected the lives of the patients.''
   Three cars parked in front of the hospital, which is one block
from Lebanon's central bank and near the prime ministry, were burned
into smoldering piles of metal.
   Police said the other car bomb exploded at 1:30 a.m. in an olive
green Mercedes near a Syrian checkpoint in the village of Saadnayel,
24 miles east of Beirut in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley.
   Police estimated the car that blew up in the village also
contained 110 pounds of TNT. Injured were two Lebanese in a passing
car and a Palestinian bystander, police said.
   The two blasts brought to 20 the number of car bombings in
Lebanon this year. Police say 115 people have been killed and 279
wounded in 18 bombings since April 23.
   Many of the bombings have been aimed at Syrian targets. Among the
wounded have been 23 Syrian troops.
   No one has claimed responsibility for any of the bombings, but
the Syrians have blamed them on right-wing Lebanese Christians
fighting against Syrian-backed Moslems and leftists in Lebanon's
13-year-old civil war.
   In other developments Monday:
   _ Syria withdrew six military observers who have been monitoring
a cease-fire between Palestinian guerrillas and Shiite Moslem
militiamen east of south Lebanon's port city of Sidon for 19 months.
   Police said the move triggered fears of a new round of fighting
between Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization guerrillas
and Nabih Berri's mainstream Shiite Amal militia for control of the
highlands overlooking a Palestinian refugee camp east of Sidon.
   _ Israel released and returned three Lebanese Shiite Moslem
teen-agers seized Sunday in a motorboat off the southern Lebanese
port of Tyre by an Israeli gunboat. Police here theorized the three
were mistaken for guerrillas on an infiltration mission.
</TEXT>
