<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conductor Lorin Maazel led three orchestras through
all nine Beethoven symphonies in a 12-hour, 45-minute marathon on
Sunday to raise money for deaf children.
   Maazel, 58, wearing formal tails and a pair of comfortable shoes,
lifted his baton to begin the Beethoven odyssey at 10 a.m. He
conducted the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra, the Philharmonia and the
London Symphony Orchestra at London's Festival Hall, taking only
brief intermissions to change musicians and symphonies.
   Organizers said they hoped to raise more than $37,000 for the
Beethoven Fund for Deaf Children, which provides musical speech
therapy to hundreds of schools in Britain.
   Beethoven wrote most of his symphonies and many other
masterpieces after he began to lose hearing, completing his final
symphony when he was deaf.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer T. Graham Brown received a
present he didn't expect from his wife during a recent anniversary
celebration.
   ``We had a really good surprise,'' Brown told reporters Sunday as
he watched a Christmas Parade. ``Our eighth wedding anniversary was
Thursday and Sheila told me she was pregnant. This will be our first
child.''
   When asked what he wanted for Christmas, besides a healthy baby,
Brown said he wished for a solution to homelessness.
   ``I just wish that we would have peace and I wish we didn't have
so many homeless people. I wish this whole country could figure out
something to do about that,'' said Brown, known for such hits as
``Hell and High Water'' and ``Don't Go to Strangers.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel Pisar, who at 16 escaped from a Nazi
concentration camp, has received the 1988 Elie Wiesel Holocaust
Remembrance Award for exemplifying ``the triumph of the human
spirit.''
   Pisar, a lawyer from Paris, accepted the award Sunday from the
Israel Bond Organization ``in the name of the children of the
Holocaust,'' and in honor of those who survived.
   Born in Bialystok, Poland, Pisar was sent to Auschwitz at the age
of 13 and later to Dachau, from which he escaped when he was 16.
More than 30 of his relatives died at the hands of the Nazis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Gertrude Elion was the first
Nobel Prize winner to arrive Monday for the annual ceremonies.
   Elion, the only woman among the 12 winners this year, shares the
medicine prize with American George Hitchings and Sir James Black of
Britain.
   Also on Monday, the two daughters of Naguib Mahfouz, winner of
this year's literature Nobel, left for Stockholm to receive the
award from Sweden's King Carl XVI Gustaf.
   The ceremony is Saturday, the eve of Mahfouz's 77th birthday.
   Mahfouz, author of more than 40 novels and several collections of
short stories, has said his doctors advised him not to travel to the
Swedish capital because of frail health.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince William was praised for the little pleats
on his pants, but his mother, Princess Diana, made People magazine's
worst-dressed list for wearing blue jeans and T-shirts.
   Talk show host Morton Downey Jr., one of seven judges, said he is
``sick of royalty that tries to look like common folk.''
   In addition to Downey, others judging the fashion coups and
boo-boos of 1988 in this week's People were Olympic track star
Florence Griffith Joyner, TV's extraterrestrial ALF, country singer
Tanya Tucker and designers Vivienne Westwood, Victor Costa and
Kenneth Cole.
   President-elect George Bush received a worst-dressed citation
because his suit and tie were ``boring,'' while the bare-shoulder
look of actress Joan Collins was judged ``fabulous, elegant,
lovely.''
   Mary Tyler Moore, Barbra Streisand, Corbin Bernsen, Audrey
Hepburn and Kevin Costner also were saluted.
   Madonna, Cybill Shepherd, Lauren Hutton, Raquel Welch and tennis
star Andre Agassi joined Bush as the year's worst dressed.
   ALF said of the navel-bearing attire Cher wore at the Academy
Awards, ``She has finally found a way to stay off the worst-dressed
lists: not wearing clothes.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winona LaDuke will be honored Wednesday at
the United Nations for her commitment to helping her people rebuild
cultural self-respect and for her efforts to regain land for the
White Earth reservation.
   LaDuke, 29 and a Chippewa, will be one of four recipients of the
first Reebok Human Rights Awards honoring outstanding individuals
under age 30 who have made major contributions to the advancement of
human rights.
   LaDuke said she was surprised by the award.
   ``Usually, when people think of human rights, they think of human
rights in other countries,'' LaDuke said from her home in Moose
Factory, Ontario, where her husband, Randy Kapashesit, is a leader
among Cree Indians.
   LaDuke said her love for the continuity of life pushes her in her
work at White Earth, 200 miles northwest of St. Paul.
   ``It was the realization that if I wanted to pass down anything
to our kids _ any of our land _ I'd actually have to fight for it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dustin Hoffman will appear on the London stage in
May playing Shylock in William Shakespeare's ``The Merchant of
Venice,'' publicists said Monday.
   Hoffman will open in late May for a 12-week run at a
yet-to-be-announced theater. It will be the actor's first stage work
since his much-acclaimed 1984 Broadway run as Willy Loman in ``Death
of a Salesman.''
   Sir Peter Hall, former director of London's National Theater,
will direct the play.
   Hoffman will be paid a reported $3,700 a week, well below the $5
million fee he routinely commands for film roles. The production
will tour England for a month prior to its London debut.
</TEXT>
