<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudebakerPensions     12-05 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Studebaker Pensions,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former UAW Local Official Still Fighting For Pensions Lost 25 Years
Ago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former United Auto Workers official is
still fighting to win pension benefits for workers who lost their
jobs when the Studebaker Corp. shut down 25 years ago.
   ``As long as I have breath in my body, I will continue,'' says
Odell ``Duke'' Newburn, former president of UAW Local 5.
   Almost 6,000 workers lost their pensions when Studebaker locked
the gates to its South Bend factory Dec. 20, 1963. Many had at least
10 years of service but lost out because the company's pension plan
was not fully funded.
   In 1975, a federal law was enacted requiring companies to
purchase federal insurance to protect pensions, but that didn't help
the Studebaker workers.
   ``We were the cause of pensions being secured, but no laws were
made retroactive back to them,'' said Newburn. ``They forgot those
who made that law possible.''
   A bill to help those workers and others who have lost pensions
has been introduced annually in Congress since 1979 but has made
little progress, Newburn said.
   Newburn continues to speak in support of the measure and fields
questions about it almost daily from former Studebaker workers. ``I
tell them the issue isn't dead and that someone is still working on
it,'' he said.
   Karen Friedman, education director of the Pension Rights Center,
a Washington lobbying group, said the measure would have helped
about 83,000 people and cost $40 a million a year had it been
enacted in 1979. The cost would diminish annually as deaths reduce
the number of recipients, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
