<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Attack     12-05 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Attack,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Radio: 42 Dead in Bus Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas attacked a passenger bus in
the northern Afghan province of Kunduz, killing 42 people,
Afghanistan's official radio said Monday.
   Only an 8-year-old child survived the Thursday attack, the radio
said.
   Another eight people were reported killed when hundreds of
rockets blasted two Afghan cities, Radio Kabul said.
   There was no independent confirmation of the reports.
   The radio broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said a bus was
attacked by ``criminals who are supported by Pakistan and the United
States,'' presumably referring to Moslem guerrillas fighting
Afghanistan's Soviet-backed Marxist government.
   The sole survivor was an 8-year-old child, said Radio Kabul.
   More than 300 surface-to-surface rockets blasted the eastern
Afghan city of Gardez during the past two days killing six people
and injuring scores more, said Radio Kabul.
   Two people died and four were injured in rocket attacks on the
northern city of Kunduz, the radio said.
   The radio also said Afghanistan has lodged 139 complaints with a
U.N. team monitoring an accord providing for the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Under the accord, signed in Geneva in April, the Soviet Union
agreed to withdraw its 100,000 combat troops from Afghanistan
between last May 15 and next Feb. 15.
   About half already have left, but the pullout is stalled
temporarily because the communists claim Pakistan is violating the
pact by continuing to arm the guerrillas.
   Soviet forces intervened in Afghanistan in 1979.
   In Saudi Arabia, representatives of the seven-party Afghan
guerrilla alliance Monday concluded talks with Soviet deputy foreign
minister Yuri Vorontsov in the resort town of Taif.
   Radio Kabul said Afghanistan's president Najib welcomed the
talks, which he claimed were initiated by Saudi Arabia.
   A guerrilla spokesman, Burhanuddin Rabbani, said the Soviets
instigated the talks. The insurgents said the talks were tacit
recognition by Moscow of the Washington-backed guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
