<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1522EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Tornadoes     12-05 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tornadoes,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Of Emergency Rescinded, Cleanup Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raleigh's state of emergency was rescinded
Monday and police were pulled off guard duty at tornado-ravaged
neighborhoods, a week after killer twisters swept through the area.
   ``We are back to normal at this time,'' said police Capt. R.D.
Williams. ``There will not be any extra police or patrols in the
areas.''
   ``I don't think it would change the cleanup efforts,'' said
Marvin Heller of the city's Emergency Communications Center. ``What
it probably does is end whatever powers they (police) had as far as
trespassing and everything.''
   Police had warned they might use emergency powers to charge
sightseers who got underfoot.
   Williams said he didn't know of anyone being charged under the
emergency powers but couldn't say whether the danger of looting was
over from the tornadoes last week that killed four people and caused
millions of dollars in damage in Raleigh and nearby areas.
   Bumper-to-bumper traffic posed problems over the weekend, as
motorists drove by the rubble with cameras. In Franklin County,
passers-by were asked for donations _ one of dozens of ways people
raised money for disaster relief.
   The American Red Cross relief fund reached about $550,000 by
Sunday afternoon, said Kristine Dewar, a Red Cross spokeswoman.
   State and federal officials met Monday in Raleigh to coordinate
the opening of disaster application centers, which will provide
temporary housing assistance, low-interest loans and grants
agricultural aid to people with uninsured losses.
</TEXT>
