<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Capitol Tree,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Fir Set Up as Capitol Christmas Tree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 50-foot-tall, 50-year-old balsam fir from the
Huron-Manistee National Forests in Michigan was erected Monday on
the west side of the Capitol as this year's congressional Christmas
tree.
   The tree, carried from Michigan on a flatbed truck and hoisted
into place by a large crane, was a seedling when the forest was
founded, said Barbara Anderson, spokeswoman for Huron-Manistee.
   The tree will be trimmed and shaped by Paul Pincus, the Capitol
landscape architect, who has performed the task on Capitol Christmas
trees since 1963. More than 4,000 lights and 8,000 ornaments will
adorn the tree when the decorators are finished.
   The lights on the tree will be lit at a ceremony Dec. 14.
</TEXT>
