<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ortega     12-05 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ortega,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Cancels Trip to United Nations</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega canceled a
trip to the United Nations on Monday, saying the United States had
placed unacceptable restrictions on his travel and on the size of
his party.
   ``The United States has violated international norms and its
promises to the United Nations and has broken the principles of the
United Nations,'' Ortega told a news conference.
   Ortega, in Mexico for the inauguration of President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, said he had been planning to fly to New York to
discuss the latest Central American peace initiative and to plead
for aid for his hurricane battered country.
   U.S. officials noted that the United States had issued expedited
visas for Ortega, his wife, his son, and 15 other Nicaraguans. The
United States turned down the visas of 14 other people because they
were not submitted 15 days before the trip.
   ``Now we guaranteed his right to come to the United Nations, but
we did not guarantee his right to bring unlimited numbers of people
with him, nor did we guarantee his right to tourism in the United
States,'' said Vernon Walters, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
   Ortega said the United States limited his travels to four
boroughs of New York City, which he said would prevent him from
visiting the home of the Nicaraguan ambassador to the United
Nations, who lives outside that area.
   He said the United States had no right to decide ``when, how and
with whom a chief of state can visit an international organization
like the United Nations.''
   In New York, Walters said that ``a lot of people take less than
30 people from a lot larger countries than Nicaragua.''
   ``Secondly, Mr. Ortega came up the last time to the United
Nations, and he was jogging in the park, buying glasses and speaking
in Denver, Colorado, and other places.''
   Ortega said he had hoped to describe the extensive damage done in
Nicaragua by Hurricane Joan in October and plead for international
help.
   He said he also wanted to confer with U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar about a new proposal for the United Nations
to participate in verifying a Central American peace accord.
   U.S. officials said Ortega had planned to meet with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who will address the U.N. General
Assembly and will meet with President Reagan and President-elect
George Bush.
   Ortega said that U.S. policy in Central America had been a
failure during the Reagan administration.
   ``Reagan came into office intending to finish Nicaragua and the
revolution in El Salvador,'' said Ortega. ``In January (when Reagan
leaves office), we'll still be there and he'll be leaving behind an
explosive situation in El Salvador, where the guerrillas are
stronger than they ever were.''
   Ortega said he saw no prospect of renewed negotiations with
Contra guerrillas because the guerrillas are not interested.
   He also rejected criticisms by Mexican leftists who had said
Ortega and Cuban President Fidel Castro were supporting an
illegitimate government by attending Salinas' inauguration.
   ``If they play the electoral game,'' he said, ``they shouldn't
cry about the results.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
