<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0659 12-05 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0659,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kremlin Demands End to Firing for Ethnic Reasons</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT word to reason, sted region.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin on Monday threatened to fire and
prosecute any Communist Party official or economic manager who
dismissed workers for ethnic reasons in the tense republics of
Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   The toughly worded directive from the Council of Ministers and
the Communist Party Central Committee was another step in the
Kremlin's effort to impose order on the republics, where a flare up
of ethnic tension in the last three weeks has left at least 28
people dead.
   Economic managers, party officials and government leaders who
permit workers to be fired for ethnic reasons will be ``brought to
personal responsibility all the way to exclusion from the party,
removal from their post, and in instances forseen by the law,
brought to criminal responsibility,'' the directive said.
   Official media reports have placed the number of refugees fleeing
the threat of violence in Azerbaijan and Armenia at more than
180,000, They are housed in relatives' homes, empty apartments and
recreational camps.
   Tass said the Central Council of Soviet Trade Unions and the
Komsomol, or Young Communist League, were providing space for 24,000
children at sanatoriums and tourist facilities.
   A fund to help the children had been formed by the Soviet
Children's Fund and the Soviet Red Cross and Red Crescent, the
official news agency said. The Education Ministry was ordered to
send teachers to the temporary quarters, it said.
   The Kremlin directive, also distributed by Tass, said the
government and party had received thousands of complaints from
workers in Azerbaijan and Armenia about firings for ethnic reasons.
   It said there was evidence that economic managers and party
leaders not only had not stopped such firings, but in some cases had
participated.
   The republics are deadlocked in a dispute over control of the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan. Ethnic Armenians, who are the
majority in the region, are demanding it be annexed by Armenia.
   Azerbaijan and the Soviet government both have rejected
annexation. Rioting in February led to the deaths of at least 32
people in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait.
   Azerbaijani newspapers have protested that ethnic Armenian
officials in Nagorno-Karabakh have thrown many ethnic Azerbaijanis
out of work, and have deprived Azerbaijani families of food and
medical supplies.
   Similar charges have been made in both republics.
   Moscow radio, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp. in
London, said Monday that 106,000 Armenians had left their homes in
Azerbaijan. Last week, official Azerbaijani sources had put the
number of refugees from Armenia at 75,000.
   Other reports Monday said security forces broke up a meeting in
Baku, the Azerbaijani capital, but tensions had eased in the
Armenian capital of Yerevan, and a curfew there was eased.
   Much of the two republics, located in the Caucasus Mountains
region, have been under curfew and military law.
   Radio Moscow reported Baku ``still remains tense. At a number of
enterprises people have failed to come out to work. No transport is
operating in the center of the city.''
   The broadcast said security forces dispersed about 1,500 people
in the Baku's Lenin Square Sunday night. The forces moved in after
the crowd failed to respond to appeals by the chairman of the city
council and a commandant to disperse.
   Demonstrations and meetings are banned under military law imposed
two weeks ago.
   ``Irresponsible elements among those who gathered tried to put up
resistance. The servicemen fulfilled the tasks that had been put to
them. No weapons were used,'' the broadcast said.
   Some members of the crowd were detained, Radio Moscow reported.
The broadcast did not say why the crowd had gathered or whether they
were demonstrating over the Nagorno-Karabakh issue.
   Lenin Square was closed for ``sanitary work'' following the
dispersal of the meeting, according to Baku radio.
   In Yerevan, a 10 p.m.-6 a.m. curfew imposed Nov. 24 was cut to 11
p.m.-5 a.m., the Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda reported.
More than 2,400 people were detained and 32 were arrested since it
was imposed, Pravda said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
