<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Switzerland-PLO     12-05 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Switzerland-PLO,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Switzerland to Pay Security Bill, Provide Army For U.N. Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Switzerland will pay the bill for the
security surrounding the U.N. General Assembly, which is to meet in
Geneva next week for a special session to be addressed by PLO chief
Yasser Arafat.
   Foreign Minister Rene Felber said Swiss army units will be used
to reinforce police and border guards for the Dec. 13-15 session.
   The New York-based General Assembly has voted to meet in Geneva
because the United States refused Arafat an entry visa to
participate in the session on Palestinian issues.
   It will be the first time in the United Nations' 43-year-old
history that the General Assembly meets outside the United States.
   Felber said the number of reinforcements will be decided this
week. He said officials would draw from experience gathered during a
1983 U.N. Conference on Palestine.
   During that session, 2,000 soldiers and 600 police patrolled the
city, with tanks and barbed-wire barricades surrounding the
sprawling complex of the Palais des Nations, the Geneva offices of
the United Nations.
   About 300 delegates were expected for the special session.
   For security reasons, the exact date of Arafat's arrival and the
time of his speech were kept secret.
</TEXT>
