<1ST_LINE>u w PM-HouseLeaders 4thLd-Writethru a0629 12-05 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Leaders, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0629,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michel Pledges Tougher Ethics Policies; Democrats Elect Black to
Leadership</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS grafs 2-3 to reflect that Michel did not specifically
criticize Wright; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs bgng, `The reputation'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Bob Michel of Illinois pledged today
to pursue tougher ethics policies as he was re-elected House
Minority Leader. The Democrats, meanwhile, voted for the first time
to put a black into their top leadership.
   Michel delivered a shot at the Democratic leadership of the House
over the past decade.
   Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, was running unopposed for a second
two-year term, and he was assured of re-election to his post by
fellow Democrats later today despite an inquiry into allegations of
unethical behavior in his personal finances and his handling of
government secrets.
   ``The reputation of this institution has been smeared by members
who blatantly break our rules and mock the institution's inability
to enforce a penalty,'' Michel told fellow GOP lawmakers, who
elected him to a fifth two-year term as their leader. He was
unopposed.
   Michel did not mention Wright by name, but made it clear that the
Republicans intend to pursue the inquiry against the speaker, which
they initiated. The House ethics committee is investigating the
charges against Wright.
   ``I believe we must more clearly define our ethics rules, and
then we have to enforce them,'' he said. ``The record of enforcement
in this House is a national disgrace.''
   The principal contested races on each side were for the largely
ceremonial tasks of presiding over party meetings.
   Rep. William H. Gray III, the chairman of the House Budget
Committee, won the post of Democratic caucus chairman over Rep. Mary
Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, who has been vice chairman of the caucus, and
Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla. The vote was 146 for Gray, 80 for Ms.
Oakar, and 33 for Synar.
   Gray becomes the first black to climb that high in the leadership
structure, according to House historians. If Ms. Oakar had won, she
would set the standard for a woman in the House.
   The hottest Republican race saw Rep. Jerry Lewis of California
edge out Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois for the chairmanship of the
House Republican Conference, the counterpart to the Democratic
caucus. Lewis won in a runoff by a vote of 85-82 after Rep. Bill
Dannemeyer, R-Calif., was third and dropped out following the first
ballot.
   If Ms. Martin had won, she would have broken new ground for a
House GOP woman.
   The Democrats saw no major changes in their leadership, as
Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., and Majority Whip Tony
Coelho, D-Calif., who were first elected to those posts two years
ago, are returning to face a new president together.
   ``The team is together,'' said Coelho.
   To start 1987, the Democratic leaders came forward with an
aggressive agenda to counter the Reagan administration. This time
they are holding back to give George Bush a chance to offer his own
plans.
   ``We welcome his getting on the wagon'' on issues such as child
care and the environment, ``and we intend to see what he wants to
do,'' Coelho said.
   On the Republican side, Michel, the minority leader for eight
years, served with Bush in the House. The new president will have
another ally in Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., who moved up a rung on the
GOP ladder to fill the slot of minority whip. The No. 2 slot is
being vacated by Trent Lott of Mississippi, who was elected to the
Senate.
   Democratic Rep. Steny Hoyer of Maryland was running unopposed for
Oakar's old job as vice chairman of the Democratic caucus.
   The current Democratic caucus chairman, Rep. Richard A. Gephardt
of Missouri, will be appointed a deputy whip, Coelho said. That
would allow the former presidential candidate to retain a say in
leadership decisions in the House. David Bonior of Michigan will
remain Coelho's chief deputy.
   In addition to electing officers, both parties will begin vying
for changes in the House rules for the new Congress that might give
them an advantage in legislative struggle.
   Democratic Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, is being opposed by
his own party leadership in his quest to force disclosure of the
beneficiaries of special-interest provisions in legislation.
   The proposal would require the listing of the name of each
beneficiary, the cost to taxpayers of the provision, and the name of
the lawmaker who sponsored it.
   Stenholm contends it would sae members of Congress embarrassment
later, but the primary spending and tax-writing panels oppose the
plan.
</TEXT>
