<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--JudicialStrike     12-05 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Judicial Strike,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Strike Paralyzes Portugal's Courts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges went on strike Monday, paralyzing
the court system, and other unions announced protests that could
disrupt trials for two weeks.
   The Union of Judicial Magistrates called the three-day strike
after the government included Portugal's 1,200 judges in a salary
restructuring plan for public employees. The union claims the move
will lead to lower pay rises.
   Other court officials have planned a one-day strike Friday while
public prosecutors have anounced they will stop work for three days
next week.
   This week's action is the first ever national strike by
Portuguese judges.
   Courts are running only a minimum service to handle cases where
the liberty of individuals is at stake.
   Trade union estimates said 90 percent of the judges had accepted
the strike call.
</TEXT>
