<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1926EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Crash     12-05 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Crash,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Blames Ice, Crew Training For Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government investigators Monday blamed ice on the
wings of an Italian airliner and the flight crew's reaction for a
crash that killed 37 people last year.
   Nine people, including French and Italian airline officials, were
indicted in October on manslaughter charges from the Oct. 15, 1987,
crash of a twin-engine turboprop ATR-42 operated by the ATI
subsidiary of Italy's state-run Alitalia.
   The plane, carrying mostly West Germans, crashed shortly after
takeoff on a flight from Milan to Cologne.
   A government report published Monday said the first event leading
to the crash was the formation of ice that altered the aerodynamic
profile of the wings.
   The ice made one wing fall in an unusual action that the crew
almost certainly attributed to a malfunction in the automatic pilot
instead of a stall, it said.
   The report contends sharp manuevers by the crew to raise the wing
increased the longitudinal roll of the plane and kept the pilot from
taking timely corrective action.
   Investigators said the crew was not effectively sensitized to the
phenomenon or the importance of procedures.
   It should have increased takeoff speed and reduced the angle of
ascent because of the ice-forming conditions. Instead, the plane
stalled at a speed faster than normal for takeoff and at a lower
than usual angle of ascent.
   Earlier, investigators said the plane's operation and flight
manuals did not contain instructions to handle icing.
   But Enzo Pacia, lawyer for plane designer Jean Rech, said last
month the plane ``has an anti-icing system conforming with
international norms and the flight manuals and other technical
instruments are suitable so the plane can be flown without risk in
any weather conditions.''
   The indictments named Rech, a Frenchman and an official of
Aerospatiale company; the operations manager and three other ATI
officials reponsible for flight operations, manuals and pilots; an
official who certified the flight-worthiness of the ATR-42; and
three officials of the civil aviation office responsible for flight
manuals and authorizing flight routes.
</TEXT>
