<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Australia 1stLd-Writethru a0640 12-05 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Australia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0640,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov't Expels Australians; Diplomats Return to Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Australian comment. Picks
up
6th graf pvs, ``Security guard ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Monday it is
expelling three Australian diplomats from Belgrade in retaliation
for the closure of the Yugoslav consulate in Sydney.
   They must leave Belgrade within a week, state television reported.
   Australian Charge d'Affaires Peter Shannon said two first
secretaries and a second secretary have been ordered to leave with
their families _ a total of 14 people.
   The announcement came hours after 12 Yugoslav diplomats and
consular staff members expelled from Australia arrived in Belgrade
to a rousing official welcome.
   Foreign Ministry officials met them at the airport, where the
Yugoslav consul to Sydney, Stanojlo Glisic, held a news conference.
   Australian Foreign Minister Gareth Evans ordered the Sydney
consulate closed and gave the staff 72 hours to leave after the
Yugoslav government refused to hand over a consulate security
officer accused of shooting and seriously wounding a 16-year-old
during a Nov. 27 protest by 1,500 ethnic Croatians.
   Shannon said he told the Yugoslavs that none of the expelled
Australians ``could be considered to have breached international
diplomatic conventions or Yugoslav laws.''
   ``I was told explicitly that the action was in response to the
Australian government's closure of the consulate-general in
Sydney,'' he said in an interview.
   Security guard Zoran Matijas, wearing dark glasses and carrying
his 3-year-old daughter, said at the airport, ``I have not been
authorized to say anything.''
   The youth was shot in the throat when demonstrators scaled the
consulate walls and tried to tear down the Yugoslav flag.
   Consul Glisic defended Matijas' action, saying the guard fired
two warning shots during the demonstration.
   ``Zoran was defending me in what was a destructive attack on our
consulate,'' Glisic said. ``The circumstances of the wounding are
unclear. It has not been proven that Matijas did it.''
   Foreign Minister Budimir Loncar praised Matijas. ``He was
defending our territory. He was not attacking. Therefore we refused
to hand him over,'' he told Belgrade television Sunday.
   Loncar said his government will demand ``satisfaction'' for an
alleged Australian breach of the Vienna Consular Convention, under
which consular officials enjoy immunity from criminal prosecution
for acts performed in exercise of consular functions.
   He blamed the Australian government for the shooting, saying it
did not provide adequate police protection during the demonstration,
which he alleged was staged by Ustasha emigres.
   The Ustashas were Croation fascists allied with Nazi Germany
against Yugoslav resistance forces during World War II. Croatian
extremists have been charged with killing at least two Yugoslav
diplomats and wounding others in various attacks in the past 20
years.
   In a separate attack Sunday, extremists firebombed the car of
prominent Australian Yugoslav leader Momir Dacic in Adelaide, police
said Monday. No one was injured.
   Dacic, president of the community-based Yugoslav Center, blamed
Croatian emigres who he said claimed responsibility.
   About 200,000 Yugoslavs live in Australia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
