<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AndersonCards     12-05 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anderson Cards,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christmas Mail Drive For Hostage Attracts 7,000 Cards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A holiday mail campaign for Terry Anderson,
facing his fourth Christmas as a hostage in Lebanon, has attracted
more than 7,000 cards from virtually every state and overseas, an
organizer said Monday.
   ``Here we had Thanksgiving and a lot of people were giving thanks
for the things we have, the freedom we have. With Christmas, we're
aware of not only Terry but all the hostages and all those less
fortunate,'' said Jack LaVriha of Lorain, who is directing the card
campaign for the Free Terry Anderson Committee. Anderson is a native
of Lorain, about 30 miles west of Cleveland.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, has been a captive since March 16, 1985.
   LaVriha, a retired newsman, said cards for Anderson have come
from as far away as the Philippines and from U.S. military post
offices around the world.
   ``We're getting a fantastic response from schools,'' said
LaVriha, who went to school with Anderson's father, Glenn Anderson,
who died in 1986 during his son's first year of captivity.
Anderson's brother also has died during the newsman's captivity.
   Many of the cards are handmade. Some are oversized or banners,
containing many names. LaVriha estimated that the cards include a
total of more than 10,000 signatures.
   The holiday greetings have come from schools such as Pearl
Elementary in Pearl, Miss., which sent 34 handmade cards. Nine
handmade cards came from a school in Milton, Utah.
   Sixty-three nursing home residents at Friendship House in
Hopkinsville, Ky., sent a card, and cards also came from Girl Scout
troops in Rochester, N.Y., and Antioch, Calif., from Walnut Creek
Intermediate School in Walnut Creek, Calif., and Adams School in
Enid., Okla.
   ``Even in the kindergarten classes the teachers have tried to
explain to the class, `Here is someone who is being held against his
will. He can't come home,''' LaVriha said.
   ``I'm told many of these kids actually cry. They become so
concerned. They know what it is like not to be able to go home to
your parents.''
   Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, speaking from her home in Cadiz,
Ky., said such campaigns on her brother's behalf play a key role.
   ``Every ex-hostage, including the French, attribute the publicity
about their plight to saving their lives at several different times
of crisis when their captors very strongly considered executing
them,'' she said.
   She said such card and letter campaigns also help keep the issue
alive in Washington. ``They are vitally important in letting our
administration know that the hostages are important to the American
people,'' she said.
   The Free Terry Anderson Committee plans to box the letters next
weekend.
   The cards are to be delivered to U.S. Rep. Donald Pease, D-Ohio,
who plans to ship them to the State Department and urge that they be
sent to Lebanon, according to his press secretary, Peg O'Laughlin.
   Frances Jones, spokeswoman for State Department's Bureau of
Consular Affairs, said, ``Unfortunately, as a practical matter it's
impossible for us to deliver cards because we don't know where the
hostages are.'' She said An Nahar newspaper in Beirut has offered to
receive mail on behalf of the hostages and suggested that the
committee might want to ship the cards there.
   ``There is no assurance this mail would be passed on, but
sometimes they print it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The deadline for mailing cards to the Free Anderson Committee is
Thursday. The group's address is Post Office Box 391, Lorain, Ohio,
44052.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
