<1ST_LINE>r w AM-UliDerickson     12-05 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uli Derickson,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Honors Uli Derickson for `Heroic Efforts' Aboard Hijacked
Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ulrike ``Uli'' Derickson, the TWA flight
attendant who protected American passengers from Arab gunmen during
a 1985 hijacking, has been tapped to receive the Navy's highest
civilian award, the service said Monday.
   Mrs. Derickson, who was chief flight attendant aboard TWA Flight
847 when it was hijacked on June 14, 1985, will visit the Pentagon
on Tuesday and receive the Navy Distinguished Public Service Award
from Navy Secretary William L. Ball III.
   ``Her courageous and heroic efforts to support and protect the
passengers, including Petty Officers Robert Stethem and Clinton
Suggs, were in keeping with the highest traditions of the U.S.
Navy,'' the Navy said.
   Stethem, a Navy diver, was one of 39 Americans held captive for
17 days after the Athens-to-Rome flight was hijacked. He was shot
and killed by the hijackers despite Mrs. Derickson's efforts to
intervene on his behalf.
   Mrs. Derickson, who hid the passports of passengers with Jewish
sounding names, managed to stop the hijackers from beating Suggs.
   Last September, during courtroom testimony in West Germany where
one of the hijackers is being tried, Mrs. Derickson told how Stethem
``never made a sound'' despite a savage beating.
   The Navy said Mrs. Derickson would be accompanied to Tuesday's
ceremony by her husband and some of the Navy sailors who survived
the hijacking.
</TEXT>
