<DOCNO> AP881205-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pioneer-Venus     12-05 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pioneer-Venus,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pioneer 12 Venus Probe Is 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pioneer 12 was designed to orbit
Venus for just 243 days, but it chalked up a solid decade of work
Monday amid raves from the scientists who've kept the project
working.
   The space probe has helped map 93 percent of Venus' searing-hot
surface while providing a new understanding of volcanics and land
formation on Earth.
   It has sent scientists 10 trillion bits of data, including
information on the extreme ``greenhouse'' effect which appears to be
trapping the sun's heat and driving the planet's surface temperature
to 900 degrees Fahrenheit.
   It also has allowed them to speculate on the ways in which Venus,
once thought to be the Earth's twin because of its similar size,
composition and the presence of continents, mountains and canyons,
is different from our home planet.
   ``We used to think when I was in school that Venus and Earth were
twin planets,'' said Donald Hunten, a professor of planetary
sciences at the University of Arizona's Lunar and Planetary
Laboratory, said at a meeting of scientists celebrating Pioneer's
longevity. ``More recently, we've discovered they are really not
very alike at all.''
   Scientists at the meeting took the opportunity to call for a
return to unmanned space probes in addition to the far more costly
manned missions.
   Steven Dorfman, who works for Hughes Aircraft Co., a major
government space contractor, called for ``a return to a mix of small
and large programs,'' pointing out that the Pioneer project was
relatively cheap at less than $200 million in today's dollars.
   Dorfman said the United States launched 36 planetary launches in
the 1960s, but only 11 in the 1970s. Two are scheduled in this
decade.
   Although Venus has no oceans, Hunten said data suggests there may
have been enough water vapor to form an ocean 4 billion years ago.
   But high temperatures from the planet's severe ``greenhouse''
effect, in which clouds or pollution traps the sun's heat near the
planet's surface, may partially account for the differences between
Venus and Earth, he said.
   Additionally, extreme stratospheric pollution on Venus, where
chlorine is found at levels 100 to 1,000 times the concentration
found in the air above Earth, could further explain conditions on
Venus and provide a warning of our own future.
   ``Venus is not a living, breathing example, but a very dead
example of what a polluted atmosphere is like,'' said Hunten, adding
that the pollution on Venus is natural but the chemistry is the same
as on Earth.
   Lawrence Colin, Pioneer Venus project scientist, said the
anniversary is just ``a step along the way to many of us.''
   Pioneer's variable orbit, which responds to the effect of solar
gravity on Venus, has allowed the spacecraft to come as close as 93
miles to Venus and as distant as 1,426 miles.
   If plans are carried out on scheduled, next year the Magellan
mission will team up with Pioneer to provide high resolution radar
mapping of Venus' surface. In February 1990, Pioneer will be joined
by the Galileo probe when it passes Venus on its way to Jupiter.
   Pioneer will continue to sample Venus' environment, including
monitoring an entire 11-year sunspot cycle.
   In late 1991, it will sample Venus' upper atmosphere. In early
1992, it will begin to burn its remaining fuel supply to maintain an
orbit of 150 kilometers, ``or lower if we can,'' said Colin.
   When the fuel supply runs out, estimated at some time late in
1992, he added, ``Pioneer Venus will meet a fiery death, the end of
the mission.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881205-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LeadersSummit     12-05 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leaders Summit,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious Leaders See Hope In Glasnost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and Soviet religious leaders said
Monday the glasnost policy of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev will
give churches in the Soviet Union more political clout.
   Meeting on the eve of Gorbachev's visit to the United States, in
which he will address the United Nations and meet with President
Reagan and President-elect George Bush, delegates to the
U.S.-U.S.S.R. Emerging Leaders Summit were optimistic Soviet clergy
even may be be allowed to run for legislative offices.
   ``The message is coming through loud and clear that Gorbachev's
initiatives are spilling over and touching upon religious life,''
said Rabbi Gary Zola of Cincinnati, dean of admissions at Hebrew
Union College. ``There is new interest in religious thought and
religious life and the government is not only permitting it but also
is fostering it.''
   Religion and politics are among the topics being addressed at the
weeklong summit ending Wednesday. The summit is sponsored by the
Columbus, Ind.-based American Center for International Leadership
and the Soviet Union's Committee of Youth Organizations.
   Soviet delegates were optimistic Gorbachev's visit with U.S.
officials would be productive.
   ``I hope Gorbachev and President Reagan will advance negotiations
on nuclear disarmament and lead the way for more success with George
Bush,'' said Andrei Rybin, 32, a priest in Moscow's Russian Orthodox
Church.
   Nikolai Mukhin, a member of the U.S.S.R. Council of Religious
Affairs, said, ``I'm sure there will be some initiatives reached for
a continuing dialogue with Bush next year.''
   On the issue of religious freedom in their own country, the
Soviet delegates said Gorbachev's policy of openness is letting
church leaders speak out without fear of reprisal for the first time
in more than 50 years.
   ``We will have a constructive role in the secular society,
especially in terms of culture and self-determination,'' Rybin said.
``Religion will be more open. The Communist Party remains atheistic
in principle, but it now recognizes the role of the church and that
it had been neglecting it.''
   Mukhin, who admitted he's ``not a believer,'' said that under the
new laws ``religious leaders will be able to be elected to
legislative bodies. ... The whole situation is developing in the
direction of Lenin's idea that people are entitled to have freedom
of conscience.''
   Rabbi David Wortman, executive director of the Jewish Community
Relations Council of Greater Philadelphia, said he found ``a
significant change'' in the Soviet position on the issue of allowing
Jews to emigrate.
   ``What was different is that they clearly supported the position
that every person should have the right to emigrate and this gives
rise to cautious optimism,'' Wortman said.
   Rybin said, ``On the problem of Jewish emigration there were many
opinions but we all recognize that every human being has the right
to go and live wherever he wants, and that is the declaration of
human rights we support, not only for Jews but for everybody.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
