<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DemocraticChairman 2ndLd-Writethru a0709 12-05 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Chairman, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0709,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kirk to Step Aside as Democratic Party Chairman</HEAD>
<HEAD>ED: SUBS 4th graf to reflect that Brown expected to announce plans
to seek post at news conference Tuesday morning.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Kirk announced plans Monday to step aside
as Democratic national chairman when his term expires, setting up a
free-for-all when the party picks a new leader early next year.
   Kirk, who had been beseeched by many top-ranking Democrats to
seek a new term, told a news conference that when he took the job in
1985, ``The time I set for myself was four years.''
   ``My plans are as they were at the beginning, which is to return
to the practice of law,'' said the 50-year-old native of Boston. He
quickly added he does not intend to become a ``political dropout.''
   Several candidates for chairman already were jockeying for
position in the event of Kirk's decision to step aside. Ronald H.
Brown, a longtime party activist who played a key role in Jesse
Jackson's campaign, is expected to announce his plans to seek the
post at a news conference Tuesday morning.
   Michigan Party chairman Richard Wiener also said he would run for
the post and said, ``I feel confident I can win.''
   Former Rep. Jim Jones of Oklahoma also said he expected to make
an announcement next Monday. Jones, who practices law in Washington,
said he had contacted some party officials last month and received
encouragement to run for the job if Kirk stepped down.
   Former Rep. Mike Barnes of Maryland said, ``I'm running.'' Former
Rep. Jim Stanton of Ohio also has expressed an interest in the post.
   The Democratic National Committee meets Feb. 9-10 in Washington
to pick a new chairman.
   Kirk won praise for his work even as the competition to succeed
him began.
   ``He leaves the chairmanship with our party rejuvenated and
prepared for the future,'' said Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
the party's losing presidential candidate this year.
   Dukakis' running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, said Kirk's tenure was
excellent and added his departure makes it ``much more difficult to
arrive at a choice without some bloodshed.''
   Kirk said in departing that his purpose had been to ``give
something back and to leave something better than existed before I
was given the honor and the opportunity to serve.''
   He said repeatedly at his news conference that the party was
better off financially and politically than it was four years ago.
He said his biggest disappointment was the loss of the presidential
race last month.
   ``During these four years I have spoken of the value of politics,
and I have worked to practice the politics of values and to enhance
respect for our political parties and for public life and our public
institutions.''
   Kirk said at the news conference he expected a ``spirited
contest'' in the campaigning to pick his successor, but disputed a
suggestion that Democrats are in for a bloodletting.
   Brown alone among the potential successors had not ruled out
challenging Kirk for the job. He is viewed with suspicion by some
party leaders because of his close association with Jackson, a black
liberal who is expected to run for the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1992.
   Kirk is a native of Massachusetts who earned his political
stripes as a lieutenant to liberal Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts.
   He was viewed with suspicion by many in the party when he waged
his winning campaign for the chairmanship, but by the time the
Democratic State Chairs met in Arizona last month, an effort to
draft him for a second term was well under way. Kirk said defeated
presidential candidate Dukakis, Bentsen, the party's congressional
leadership and numerous governors had all urged him to remain in the
job.
   Kirk said little about his own plans, but confirmed widespread
reports he had held a discussion with the owner of the San Diego
Padres, Joan Kroc, about taking a job with the baseball team. He
said he doubted anything would come of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
