<HEAD>Reagan Signs Proclamation Warning Against Evils of Drunken Driving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Monday used the onset of
the holiday season to remind Americans about the heavy costs of
driving under the influence of alcohol and other drugs.
   Reagan called drug-influenced driving ``dangerous and
irresponsible behavior that no one should engage in, tolerate or
permit.''
   He proclaimed the week of Dec. 11-17 as ``National Drunk and
Drugged Driving Awareness Week,'' carrying out the wishes of
Congress as expressed in a Senate joint resolution.
   ``We can all help improve safety on our roads and highways by
refusing to tolerate drunk and drugged driving, by always wearing
seat belts, even for short drives, and by insisting upon prompt and
effective action against alcohol- and drug-impaired drivers,'' the
proclamation said.
