<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1746EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Education     12-05 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Education,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, College Presidents Talk of Government Help, Budget Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush gave and received advice on federal
budget constraints and education Monday in a meeting with university
presidents, who generally praised the man who has vowed to be ``the
education president.''
   ``He reaffirmed that commitment to us today in no uncertain
terms,'' said Benno Schmidt Jr., president of Yale University,
Bush's alma mater.
   ``We recognize that we have a friend of education in the White
House. We're excited and grateful for that,'' Schmidt said at the
outset of the hour-long discussion with Bush, Vice President-elect
Dan Quayle, Education Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos, New Hampshire Gov.
John Sununu, the future White House chief of staff, and transition
co-director Robert Teeter.
   Bush did not join the presidents in speaking to reporters after
the meeting.
   The university chiefs said they had discussed the importance of
the federal role in ensuring access to higher education; a need to
support scientific research on campuses, and a shortage of
scientists and engineers, especially among members of minority
groups.
   Bush aides said Schmidt suggested the meeting and put together
the group, which included: Lamar Alexander, University of Tennessee;
William Cunningham, University of Texas at Austin; William Danforth,
chancellor, Washington University; James Duderstadt, University of
Michigan; David Gardner, University of California; Paul Gray,
Massachusetts Institute of Technology; Frank Rhodes, Cornell
University; Ronald Roskens, University of Nebraska. William Friday,
former president of the University of North Carolina, also attended.
   Schmidt said Bush ``stressed the limits on federal resources and
the need to make hard choices about the federal budget to bring the
deficit under control.'' He said the presidents understood that and
agreed to help Bush by setting carefully ``the educational
priorities and the science research priorities in the country.''
   ``We discussed the essential importance of maintaining the
openness and accessibility of higher education so that all our young
people can aspire to the best that our education system offers,''
Schmidt said.
   ``We expressed our great concern at the shortage of well-educated
people in science and engineering in this country,'' said Schmidt,
who cited the dearth of minorities in these professions.
   The university presidents were all white males.
   Rhodes said the president-elect reiterated his campaign pledge to
``upgrade the position of science adviser to the president'' and
appoint a presidential advisory council on science and technology.
   Alexander, former governor of Tennessee, said federal research
and development has grown by 50 percent after inflation during the
Reagan administration. But much of that spurt has been in military
R&D.
   Rhodes said, ``What we've got to do is to reallocate within the
funds already existing for R&D, and that's a tough decision that
needs to be done with expert help.''
   Alexander, a Bush education adviser during the campaign, said,
``We didn't try to lecture the vice president. We tried to say ...
we're here to help.''
   Gardner said the campus presidents also mentioned West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's interest in expanding international
education and scholarly exchanges with the United States. Gardner
said Bush was ``very understanding of it. He had already talked with
Chancellor Kohl ... and has an intense interest.''
   Schmidt, asked if he were troubled by Bush's campaign digs at
Democratic rival Michael Dukakis and Dukakis' ``Havard Yard''
advisers, said, ``I did not take that too seriously.''
   But, he added, ``any concerns expressed about Harvard in that
regard would also be entirely appropriate with respect to Yale. We
both stand for excellence and we're both very proud of what we stand
for.''
</TEXT>
