<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NursingHomeDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0693 12-05 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nursing Home Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0693,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Women Arrested in Suspicious Deaths of Nursing Home Patients</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with arraignement, names of suspects,
further detail on investigation. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALKER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former nurse's aides were arraigned on
murder charges Monday in the death of patients at a nursing home
where eight people died suspiciously, authorities said.
   Both women worked at the Alpine Manor Nursing Home when the
patients died, Police Chief Walter Sprenger said. Officials
originally believed the patients died of natural causes.
   Catherine May Wood, 26 of Grand Rapids, who worked at the home in
this Grand Rapids suburb from 1985 until October, was charged with
two counts of murder in the deaths last year of two terminally ill
patients, a 98-year-old woman and a 60-year-old woman.
   Gwendolyn Gail Graham, 25, who worked at the home from 1986 to
1987 and now lives in Texas, faced one charge of murder in the death
of the 98-year-old woman.
   Autopsies after the two bodies were exhumed failed to determine
the cause of the two deaths, authorities said. Six other deaths at
the nursing home last year are also under investigation, authorities
said.
   Sprenger said police are investigating reports some victims had
been suffocated.
   He declined to speculate on a motive or to label the deaths mercy
killings. ``I cannot share evidence that will be detrimental to the
case,'' he said.
   He said detectives have investigated but been unable to confirm
allegations that the suspects may have begun choosing their victims
based on initials of the victims' names, which they hoped to use to
spell the word M-U-R-D-E-R.
   The first name of one of the people whose deaths were cited in
the charges Monday began with an ``M,'' the other with an ``E.''
Authorities have declined to give the names of the other six people
whose deaths are under investigation. ``It's a complex motive,''
Sprenger said. ``It's a complex case. It's so complex it's going to
take a lengthy trial ... to make a lot of sense.''
   Reporters were turned away from the nursing home Monday by a
private security guard.
   ``Alpine Manor is devastated but relieved ... that something is
being done,'' Ginny Seyferth, spokeswoman for Alpine Manor, said at
a news conference. ``Both (women) had very good reviews. Both were
well-liked by the patients.
   ``I think the staff is overwhelmed,'' she said, adding that
counseling was being provided for employees.
   Sprenger said nursing home officials were not to blame for the
deaths. ``There was nothing they could have done to prevent it,'' he
said.
   Ms. Wood was arrested early Monday and was ordered held without
bond in the Kent County Jail here, pending another hearing Dec. 16.
Ms. Graham was arrested Sunday night by authorities in Tyler, Texas.
She was ordered held on $1 million bond, and Michigan authorities
said they would seek extradition.
   In both cases, the murder charges brought against the women were
``open,'' meaning the degree of murder was not immediately specified.
   Sprenger said the women were arrested in the deaths of Marguerite
Chambers, 60, and Edith Cook, 98. Other bodies may be exhumed, and
further charges were possible, he said. Three of the eight people
whose deaths are under investigation were cremated.
   The sheriff refused to say if either woman had confessed or made
any comment to authorities.
   The Grand Rapids Press reported that the women lived together
while working at the nursing home. After leaving Michigan, Ms.
Graham worked as a nurse's aide at a hospital in Texas until
recently, the newspaper said.
   The eight deaths occurred during January-April 1987. At the time,
the deaths were considered to be from natural causes and no
autopsies were conducted.
   Sprenger said detectives began investigating the deaths in early
October, using a list of ``eight potential victims'' provided by a
source he refused to identify.
   About 40 patients died at the nursing home during January-April
1987, said Seyferth. She said that was lower than the normal death
rate for such a facility. Alpine has 208 patients.
</TEXT>
