<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MethadoneVan     12-05 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Methadone Van,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobile Methadone Van Takes To Streets Against Heroin Addiction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first mobile methadone van is being
geared up to serve the working-class community of Brockton and
possibly others in an effort to assuage neighborhood worries without
giving up the fight against heroin.
   The van was the brainchild of Massachusetts officials seeking a
way around neighborhood objections to the opening of a permanent
clinic for heroin addicts.
   ``It's part of a statewide drug treatment strategy,'' said John
Stobierski of the state Department of Public Health, which is
overseeing the project.
   Methadone, a synthetic substitute for heroin, is given to addicts
to reduce their craving for the drug.
   The van, a version of which has been tried successfully in
Europe, would operate out of the police station parking lot in
Brockton, a city 20 miles south of Boston. Operators of the van made
a dry run Monday without providing methadone services.
   ``It provides us with the flexibility to bring the service into
communities,'' Stobierski said. ``There was some concern in Brockton
over the siting of a methadone service. We broached the idea of
using the van.''
   Brockton Mayor Carl Pitaro has not given final approval for the
van to operate permanently out of Brockton, said mayoral aide John
Buckley. The city is seeking an agreement with the state that would
limit the amount of time the van spent in Brockton and would
restrict the van's clients to Brockton residents.
   Dennis McCarty of the health department's Division of Substance
Abuse said the van was designed to address Brockton's concerns about
addicts flocking to their city.
   ``One concern is that programs (in buildings) tend to draw people
from a wide geographic area,'' McCarty said. ``By having a mobile
program, we have a chance to reach out to other communities without
burdening any one community too much.''
   McCarty said similar van programs are being considered for other
parts of the state.
   The Brockton methadone program stems from a Public Health
Department effort aimed as much at stopping the spread of AIDS as at
combating heroin addiction. The virus that causes acquired immune
deficiency syndrom can be spread through the sharing of hypodermic
needles.
   The state estimates there are 600 to 800 needle-using addicts in
Brockton, but opponents of the methadone program say those numbers
are inflated. Fifty to 70 heroin addicts are expected to receive
methadone treatment at the van during the initial stage of its
operation.
   According to David Mulligan, Public Health director of substance
abuse, some 300 addicts are already in treatment in Brockton, 20
percent of whom use methadone.
   Stobierski said state officials confirmed the van was the first
in the nation because it required approval from federal health
officials and the approval was the first of its kind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
