<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GorbachevSecurity 1stLd-Writethru a0591 12-05 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev Security, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0591,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Tight For Gorbachev Visit; Traffic Officials Warn of
`Gorbylock'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 7 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `Gorbachev and,' to UPDATE
with itinerary, comments from police chief; EDITS for transition;
picks up 9th graf pvs, `A tear,' INSERTS new 16th graf on protest
groups, new 18th graf on size of NYC police force.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officials are preparing the
ultimate in security for Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
three-day visit this week to New York City and forecasting one of
the worst traffic nightmares in years _ ``Gorbylock.''
   ``Security will be probably as comprehensive and as important as
any visit we have had in years and years,'' said Gillian Martin
Sorensen, the city's liaison to the United Nations.
   On Wednesday, Gorbachev is scheduled to address the General
Assembly, and have lunch with President Reagan and President-elect
George Bush, as well as other U.S. and Soviet officials.
   ``We're talking about one of the superpowers and a visit by a
very important world leader,'' Ms. Sorensen said. ``It will be
ultimate security; the New York City Police Department and the
Secret Service will do all they can do.''
   When asked how the security was going to affect the city's
motorists, Joe O'Brien, a spokesman for the city's Transportation
Department, summed it up in one word: ``Gorbylock.''
   Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, are expected to stay at the Soviet
Mission to the United Nations, at 136 East 67th St., a short drive
from the U.N. complex.
   Gorbachev's itinerary, released by the Police Department on
Monday, includes a visit to the observation deck atop one of the
World Trade Center towers after the Soviet leader's luncheon meeting
Wednesday.
   Gorbachev's 45-car motorcade is then to ride past the New York
Stock Exchange and head up to Times Square _ all in the heart of
rush hour, on avenues closed for the convenience of the visitors and
to the torment of local drivers.
   On Thursday, Gorbachev is to attend a Soviet trade show at the
Jacob Javits Convention Center, then head across town for a visit to
Central Park and a look at the Metropolitan Museum of Art's European
paintings.
   Police also said Mrs. Gorbachev might visit a department store,
but they did not say which one or when. Speculation had centered on
Macy's and Bloomingdale's, although a Soviet official noted that a
trip to the former was problematic because of crowds attracted by
its pre-Christmas sales.
   On Friday morning the Gorbachevs would go directly to Kennedy
Airport for a flight to Cuba, police said.
   During his last visit to the United States, the Soviet leader
made an unexpected stop in downtown Washington to greet the
lunchtime crowd, and Chief Robert Johnston Jr., indicated the New
York police are prepared for such an occurrence.
   ``We have contingency plans,'' he said.
   Security is expected to be tight because of the past history of
anti-Soviet incidents here, some linked to members of the militant
Jewish Defense League.
   A tear gas bomb forced the opening night audience for the
Moiseyev Dance Company to flee from the Metropolitan Opera on Sept.
2, 1986. There was a bomb scare when the Bolshoi Ballet opened at
Lincoln Center in July 1987. A car at the Soviet residential complex
in the Bronx was firebombed in 1984.
   Five protest groups have obtained permits to demonstrate outside
the United Nations during Gorbachev's appearance before the General
Assembly, including the Coalition for Soviet Jewry, the Students for
Soviet Jewry and organizations representing Afghans, Ukrainians and
Armenians.
   Police spokesman Sgt. Peter Sweeney said, ``This is going to be a
major, major operation by the New York City Police Department, in
both manpower and traffic problems.''
   Police Chief Robert Johnston Jr., said 6,600 officers will be
assigned to work overtime on the visit at a cost of more than $1
million. ``We are going to document every cop's assignment and apply
for reimbursement to the State Department,'' he said.
   The police will coordinate the security effort with the Secret
Service, the State Department and the United Nation's 250-member
police force.
   When asked to characterize the force that will be in place,
Anthony O'Connell, the United Nation's security chief, said ``the
standards of security that are normal at this headquarters for the
visits of heads of state.''
   When about 90 heads of government attended the United Nation's
40th anniversary, hundreds of city police, as well as teams of
police scuba divers, helicopter patrols and mounted officers watched
the events, conscious of possible terrorist attacks.
   The Police Harbor Unit stationed patrol boats off the U.N.
complex on the East River around the clock. Teams of police divers
performed daily searches of the riverfront piers for bombs
   In 1981, when Prince Charles of Britain paid a one-day visit to
New York City, and lunched with President and Mrs. Reagan, he was
guarded by a 2,000-member security force, which included 1,725 city
police officers.
   The biggest and most costly security and crowd and traffic
control operation was the October 1979 visit of Pope John Paul II.
The two-day papal visit involved more than 13,000 city police
officers and cost more than $3 million.
</TEXT>
