<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FireProbe     12-05 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Probe,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman, Fire Fighters Call for Probe of Fatal Kansas City Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Congressional Fire Services
Caucus and representatives of the nation's fire fighters called
Monday for investigations of the Nov. 29 fire and explosion in
Kansas City, Mo., that killed six firemen.
   Caucus chairman Rep. Curt Weldon, D-Pa., a former firefighter,
told a Capitol Hill news conference that government support for such
services is insufficient and he complained that fire safety becomes
an issue only after major incidents occur.
   ``Unfortunately, the fire service community, of which I have been
a part virtually all of my life, must seize tragic opportunities
such as this to emphasize the real need for greater awareness to the
fire problem in America,'' said Weldon, who was joined at the news
conference by representatives for the nation's fire fighters.
   Weldon accused local, state, and federal government agencies of
providing ``modest, to little, to no resources,'' for fire services,
and called for the establishment of comprehensive safety regulations
regarding hazardous materials for emergency response employees.
   The six firefighters were killed when a construction trailer
loaded with 30,000 pounds of ammonium nitrate exploded, ripping a
large crater in the ground and virtually obliterating a fire truck.
Investigators determined arson to be the probable cause.
   Weldon said that he has requested a full investigation into the
circumstances surrounding that incident and that the administrator
of the U.S. Fire Administration, part of the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, had agreed to conduct the probe.
   Alfred K. Whitehead, president of the International Association
of Fire Fighters, requested a congressional inquiry into the matter
as well, saying, ``I am hopeful the Congress will address the
question of fire department notifications, hazardous materials
training for emergency response teams and the quantities of
hazardous materials appropriate for community safety.
   ``What took place in Kansas City can take place in nearly every
community in America,'' Whitehead said.
   Jim Estepp, a spokesman for the International Association of Fire
Chiefs, said his organization joined with Weldon and other fire
associations in ``asking that the deaths of these fire fighters not
be in vain and that the new administration and Congress will keep
the needs of the nation's fire and emergency service as a major
priority to maintain the safety of the public and of fire fighters.''
   The Congressional Fire Services Caucus is one of the largest on
Capitol Hill and has 277 members from the House of Representatives
and the Senate.
</TEXT>
