<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Transition     12-05 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Transition,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Invites Mrs. Dole for Breakfast Amid Job Rumors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush, who has promised
to recruit more women and minorities to top jobs in his
administration, has invited former Cabinet member Elizabeth Dole to
breakfast on Tuesday, her husband's aides said Monday.
   Mrs. Dole, a former transportation secretary and wife of Senate
minority leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., has been rumored to be in line for
a top job, possibly that of ambassador to the United Nations.
   On Sunday, Walt Riker, Dole's spokesman, said it was ``simply a
rumor'' that Mrs. Dole would be tapped as the U.N. ambassador. There
has also been speculation that Mrs. Dole could be a candidate to
head the Department of Health and Human Services, although she is
not considered a leading contender for that job.
   Susan Pelter, another aide to Dole, confirmed that Mrs. Dole, now
a private citizen, would meet Bush on Tuesday at his office.
   Mrs. Dole did not return a telephone call to discuss her future.
Alixe Glen, a spokeswoman for the Bush transition office, said she
had no information about appointments.
   Mrs. Dole, a Harvard-trained lawyer from Salisbury, N.C., quit
her post at transportation in late 1987 to campaign full-time for
her husband in his failed attempt to gain the Republican
presidential nomination.
   After Bush won the GOP nomination, Mrs. Dole worked for him,
campaigning frequently among evangelical groups. Before she went to
the Transportation Department, she work for President Reagan as a
White House liaison with women and minorities. She also has been a
member of the Federal Trade Commission.
   So far, no woman has been given a high-level job by Bush.
   There was no hint when Bush would make other appointments to top
jobs, including that of defense secretary. Bush spends Tuesday in
Washington and travels to New York on Wednesday for a meeting with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Former Sen. John Tower, D-Texas, is still thought to have the
inside track for defense secretary. The Washington Times reported
that Norman Augustine, the president of Martin Marietta Corp., a
defense contractor, would take the No. 2 slot at the Pentagon.
   Bill Harwood, Augustine's spokesman, said he could not confirm
the report. Other sources close to the transition, speaking on
condition they remain anonymous, said Augustine was the type of
management expert who might work well with Tower to control Pentagon
spending.
   Augustine, a former Pentagon official, has writtren extensively
about eforming the procurement process.
   Meantime, jockeying continued for jobs at the State Department,
which will be headed by James Baker III.
   Two of the contenders for Assistant Secretary of State for
European Affairs are Richard Haas, who specialized in Greek and
Turkish affairs and now teaches at Harvard; and James Dobbins, a
specialist on Western and North Europe who is a deputy to the U.S.
ambassador to West Germany.
