<1ST_LINE>r w AM-O'HareImprovements     12-05 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare Improvements,320</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0737 to correct category code</NOTE>
<HEAD>FAA Cites Progress on Improving Control-Tower Operations at O'Hare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has
completed action on six of 102 measures it proposed to improve
control-tower operations at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport,
aides to Sen. Paul Simon said Monday.
   Simon's office released a report from the FAA outlining progress
on its plans to reduce flight-handling errors by air traffic
controllers at O'Hare.
   Controllers at the nation's busiest airport committed 30 such
errors in the first 10 months of 1988, surpassing the previous
record of 22 mistakes in 1986 and 12 in 1987.
   Responding to a Senate resolution demanding a timetable for
improvements, the agency submitted a detailed action plan to Simon,
D-Ill., in October and promised him monthly status reports.
   Press secretary David Carle said the most noteworthy measures
outlined in the first update were adding five experienced
controllers to the O'Hare tower, replacing aircraft situation
display equipment there and at a regional traffic center in Aurora,
Ill., and acquiring additional display equipment which will be
installed later.
   Although the FAA listed six recommendations as ``closed,''
including the addition of the situation display equipment and
budgeting money for overtime pay, the designation does not mean a
proposal was adopted.
   For example, the agency said a proposal to modify a telephone
system to allow conference calls among various personnel handling a
flight was closed because the system changes were not practical.
   A proposal to add consoles for training was closed because it
said FAA personnel in Chicago advised the agency no additional
consoles were needed.
   Other steps listed as ``closed'' were reviewing ``swap'' control
procedures with the industry and speeding the installation of a
communications switching system.
   ``There are no major problems with the existing (switching)
system, and AT&T assured the FAA that they can maintain the existing
system at O'Hare for at least the next five years,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
