<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     12-05 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor's Condition Stabilizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's condition stabilized Monday after
he weathered his most serious setback since falling ill more than
two months ago, palace officials said.
   The 87-year-old monarch's blood pressure plummeted to its lowest
level since Hirohito first coughed up blood Sept. 19, registering in
the low 40s early Monday, a senior palace official said.
   Palace doctors removed ``large amounts of blood'' caused by
internal hemorrhaging from Hirohito's stomach using a tube after
they noticed swelling of his abdomen, palace spokesman Kenji Maeda
told reporters.
   Doctors gave Hirohito emergency blood transfusions, and his blood
pressure recovered to 113 over 50 by Monday evening, Maeda said.
   Hirohito's condition ``is picking up ... as can be seen by his
blood pressure,'' Maeda said.
   His other vital signs had returned to near normal levels, and
``We've gotten past the worrying stage as far as the blood loss this
time is concerned,'' Maeda said.
   The frail emperor's setback Monday was the worst during his
current illness and the damage it inflicted is unclear, said the
palace official, who spoke on condition he remain unidentified.
   Doctors believe the world's longest-reigning living monarch is
bleeding mostly in the upper intestinal area where he underwent a
bypass operation in September 1987.
</TEXT>
