<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral 2ndLd-Writethru a0697 12-05 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0697,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daley Makes Second Run for Mayor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 16th, `The City ..., to UPDATE with
Sawyer's comment.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley, bearer of the most recognizable
name in big-city politics and seasoned by an unsuccessful run five
years ago, announced Monday he will seek the mayor's office his
father occupied for 21 years.
   Daley's entry into the race expands the Democratic field to
seven, with an eighth, Mayor Eugene Sawyer, expected to announce
within a week that he also is a candidate.
   According to a recent poll, the 46-year-old Daley, who last month
overwhelmingly won a third term as Cook County state's attorney,
jumps into the race as the clear front-runner.
   Daley said he is not concerned by a crowded field.
   ``I don't need anyone in or out. If I stood here worrying bout
this scenario or that, or about odds, I would not be running as a
candidate for mayor of Chicago.
   ``I'm running,'' he told a packed news conference, ``and I'm
going to win.''
   Daley becomes the fourth white candidate in a city that made the
late Harold Washington its first black mayor in 1983 and has split
its vote along racial lines since.
   ``I'm not interested in running as the white candidate, or
serving as mayor for half the people,'' Daley said.
   ``Fighting crime is not a white issue or a black issue. Schools
is not a white or black issue. Protecting taxpayers is not a white
or black issue,'' he said.
   The Democratic primary, which has been the stepping stone to the
fifth floor office at City Hall for every Chicago mayor since 1931,
is scheduled for Feb. 28.
   The special election, set last month by the Illinois Supreme
Court to complete Washington's second term, follows on April 4.
   Richard J. Daley, who controlled a political army through
patronage jobs and earned the moniker ``Boss'' for his iron-fisted
grip on both local and national politics, served as Chicago's mayor
from 1955 until his death in 1976.
   The younger Daley, who served as a state legislator during part
of that time before moving to the prosecutor's post, made a first
attempt to fill his father's shoes in 1983.
   Daley split the white vote in that Democratic primary with
then-Mayor Jane Byrne, coming in third and catapulting Washington
into the mayor's chair.
   But in an almost complete reversal of events, Washington's death
last November has fractured the black voting bloc that was so
unified behind the former congressman.
   The City Council, in a tumultuous session after Washington's
death, appointed Sawyer as acting mayor to serve until the next
election. Neither Sawyer nor Alderman Tim Evans _ the other leading
black candidate _ appears able to muster the monolithic support that
made Washington the first mayor since the elder Daley to win
re-election.
   ``The mayor's office is not an heirloom to be passed on from one
generation to the next,'' Sawyer said Monday. ``Richard M. Daley's
announcement in no way changes my plans. I expect to win handily
against any opposition.''
   A Gallup poll in October, the most recent survey pitting
announced and expected Democrats against one another, found Daley
winning with 37 percent to 22 percent for Evans and 10 percent for
Sawyer.
   The other Democratic candidates are Aldermen Edward Burke,
Lawrence Bloom and Danny Davis, former Chicago Park District
Superintendent Edmund Kelly and former state Sen. James Taylor.
   City GOP leaders were still looking for a candidate to back,
though at least one Republican, Edward Howlett, announced on his own.
</TEXT>
