<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Estonia     12-05 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Estonia,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estonians Postpone Confrontation on Autonomy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLINN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Estonian activists indicated Monday they
will postpone confrontation with Moscow over running their own
affairs, in hopes time and negotiation will work in the Baltic
republic's favor.
   ``The finger was waved but the door was not slammed,'' when the
Kremlin nullified Estonia's declaration of sovereignty last month,
said Tonis Avikson, spokesman for the broad-based People's Front.
   Activists in Estonia said they have great hope for a new national
commission that is to define the powers of Moscow and the republics.
   Monday was opening day of a session of the legislature to
consider economic reforms and making the Estonian language official.
   After the legislature declared Nov. 16 that it had a right to
veto national laws, there were calls to cancel a federal statute
setting rules for demonstration permits. But Estonian deputies in
Tallinn, the Estonian capital, said Monday they were in no hurry to
veto anything.
   ``At present we are striving for our Presidium to fix the
procedure'' for ratifying Soviet laws or arranging a vote of the
legislature on them, said Edgar Savisaar, a leader of the People's
Front and a recently elected member of the legislature.
   Another deputy, Arno Almaniv, said a more liberal local law
automatically supersedes the national statute under Estonia's
proclamation of sovereignty.
   Members indicated they would compromise on demands for the
closure of Tallinn's most serious polluter, a paper mill under a
Moscow ministry's control, and were leaning toward a phased closing
over two years.
   A new mill built jointly with a Finnish company should be ready
in two years and is expected to replace the jobs and production lost
by closing the old one. It will use the latest low-pollution
technology and concentrate on making toilet paper, a chronically
scarce commodity in the Soviet Union.
   Conciliatory tactics, including repeated statements that
sovereignty does not mean independence, are critical to preventing a
repeat of the Czechoslovak experience 20 years ago, when a
Soviet-led invasion force crushed the liberal ``Prague spring,''
said Marju Lauristin, a People's Front leader.
   Responding to a reporter's question, she said such an event would
set Estonia back decades and endanger the reforms of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev that made the Estonian action possible.
   ``We cannot imagine perestroika going forward with tanks in
Estonia,'' she said.
   Estonia is pressing ahead with some elements of its autonomy
campaign and has formally proposed opening a consulate-type office
in Sweden, said Valle Feldman, spokesman for the Estonian Foreign
Ministry.
   The republic also is pursuing plans for economic sovereignty,
even though the Kremlin rejected Estonian ownership of all factories
and natural resources on its territory.
   Rein Otsason, head of the Estonian Planning Agency, said the
government is pursuing de facto economic control even if ``legal
ownership'' remains with national authorities.
</TEXT>
