<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 2106EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LeadersSummit-Military     12-05 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leaders Summit-Military,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, USSR Military Meet On A Personal Level</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER SHINKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a scene from a peace activist's dream:
a Soviet military analyst held a report given him Monday by a U.S.
Army major and offered to send related material about the Soviet
Army to his American counterpart.
   ``That's great, because the more we can read, the better, and we
fear less,'' said Maj. Robert Butto, who had just given Alexander
Savelyev an American compilation of Soviet military terms.
   Savelyev, a nuclear disarmament researcher at the Institute of
World Economy and International Relations in Moscow, said he later
gave Butto a copy of his own analysis of Soviet strategic
communications.
   The two met as part of the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Emerging Leaders Summit,
a weeklong gathering of young Soviet and American leaders in 16
different fields.
   Other topics being discussed mostly in closed-door sessions
include government and political affairs, international trade, the
arts, education, global environment, social services and medicine.
   Savelyev said the military meetings were important because the
delegates had come to ``better understand, even purely on a personal
level, that we are the same people as you, that we don't want to go
to war, just as you don't.''
   U.S. delegates said the meeting was unique because low-level U.S.
and Soviet officers were seeking common ground in a manner that has
not occurred since World War II, when the Soviet Union and the
United States joined to fight Nazi Germany.
   ``After history has taken its course, the common purpose now, 40
years later, is to come back and perhaps see if we can find some new
common ground within the context of the way the world is today,''
said Scott Salmon, a Defense Department analyst.
   ``It's extraordinary that you're in the room with Soviet officers
conversing on a day-to-day basis.'' said Butto, a Pentagon analyst
of Soviet armed forces.
   The material Butto exchanged with Savelyev is publicly available,
but ``Just the fact of an ongoing dialogue with the (Soviet) armed
forces is an eye-opener,'' Butto said.
   The delegates agreed to set aside divisive issues such as
military strength in Europe, reductions in nuclear forces and
regional conflicts. Those issues, they said, are more likely to be
resolved in high-level negotiations.
   ``We are trying to find common concepts, common approaches to the
questions of mutual understanding,'' said Lt. Col. Anatoly F.
Shatalov, representing the Chief Political Department of the Soviet
Army and Navy. ``We are not counting tanks and cannons.''
   ``Just the fact that we have come together to discuss area of
concern to each of us is a step forward,'' said U.S. Navy Cmdr.
Michael Simpson.
   ``One area that we've discussed is why we perceive threats from
each others' military forces _ the way they're structured, the
strategy,'' Simpson said. ``And we've discussed what changes might
be made to make each other appear less threatening.''
   One threat discussed was the number of Soviet tanks in Eastern
Europe, said Simpson, who added, ``We've been able to express that
concern, and hear how the Soviets responded to it.'' But he declined
to go into detail.
   ``Our goal is really just to honestly and openly share our
perceptions and concerns with each other,'' Simpson said. ``There
will be great interest in what we discuss'' in the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
