<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gorbachev-UN 1stLd-Writethru   12-05 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-UN, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0676,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev's Itinerary a `Christmas Surprise'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with schedule changes, more
comment from Soviet officials; clarifies that Gorbachev first party
leader to visit since Khrushchev; PICKS up 9th pvs: Grachev said...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials mapping the agenda for
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's trip to New York said Monday that the Soviet
president wants to ``take as many bites as possible out of the Big
Apple.''
   Gorbachev arrives Tuesday, addresses the U.N. General Assembly
and meets President Reagan and President-elect George Bush on
Wednesday, and goes sightseeing Thursday. He leaves Friday for
Havana.
   Soviet officials were mum on the more tourist-oriented aspects of
the agenda, declining to say whether such visitor venues as Macy's
or the Statue of Liberty were on the itinerary.
   ``This will be a Christmas surprise,'' Andrei Grachev, senior
official in the Ideology Department of the Communist Party Central
Committee, told a news conference. ``It is common to keep such
preparations (secret) until the last moment.
   ``His route is still being worked out, but there is a natural
desire to take as many bites as possible out of the Big Apple,''
Grachev said.
   But New York police said the couple would visit the Observation
Deck of the World Trade Center in lower Manhattan on Wednesday and
drive past the Stock Exchange and through the Broadway area. Opening
a Soviet export show, viewing European paintings at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art and visiting Central Park were on the schedule
Thursday.
   Police said Mrs. Gorbachev might visit a Manhattan department
store Wednesday afternoon.
   But Soviet officials who last week said that Trump Tower _
considered New York's epitome of capitalist ostentation _ was on the
tentative schedule said Monday that it was not on the itinerary.
   Dan Klores, a spokesman for real etate developer Donald Trump,
said the visit to Trump Tower was no longer on the program and that
Trump and his wife, Ivana, instead would dine at the Soviet Mission
Thursday with other public figures.
   Soviet officials, bombarded by questions about the propriety of a
visit to to monuments to capitalism, appear to have been somewhat
embarrassed about the tentative itinerary for the world's most
powerful communist leader.
   But at a news conference Monday, Georgy Arbatov, director of the
Soviet Institute on the United States and Canada, told reporters:
   ``At Macy's or Bloomingdale's, or any other store, our
understanding is that they ask for your cash or credit card, and
that's all.
   ``No one asks about whether you belong to the (Communist) party,
or about your moral behavior.''
   Gorbachev's U.N. visit will be the first by a Soviet party leader
since former leader Nikita S. Khrushchev banged his shoe on a U.N.
desk in 1960 in the General Assembly.
   Soviet Premier Alexei Kosygin visited the United Nations in 1967.
At the time, he shared power with party leader Leonid Brezhnev.
   Vernon A. Walters, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, said
U.S. authorities were aware of Gorbachev's schedule but that the
Soviet side wanted to release it later.
   Grachev said Gorbachev's U.N. visit and meeting with Reagan and
Bush ``will not disappoint the hopes and expectations for a better
and safer world that Americans and others outside this country have
placed on him.''
   U.N. observers said they expected Gorbachev's speech to be a tour
de force of Soviet diplomacy that could contain major surprises and
initiatives.
   Asked about the topics Gorbachev would raise, Grachev said: ``We
are 100 percent sure he won't be silent on the Middle East and a
settlement there.''
   The visit comes at a time when the United States has offended the
United Nations, Arab nations and many U.N. members by denying a visa
to Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat to address
the General Assembly.
</TEXT>
