<DOCNO> AP881205-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 2221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO     12-05 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Will Require Greater Soviet Bloc Cuts in Conventional Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO will demand that Warsaw Pact
nations make bigger reductions in their forces than the West when
the sides meet for talks on conventional arms, a U.S. negotiator
said Monday.
   ``It's really quite a forward-looking position,'' Paul Nitze,
special assistant to President Reagan on arms control issues, said
in a meeting with reporters.
   ``It would carry out the principle ... of unequal reductions on
the two sides in order to bring about an endpoint of equality,'' he
said. ``This would require ... substantially greater reductions'' on
the Warsaw Pact side.
   ``The exact figures of the tanks, armored personnel carriers,
bridging equipment'' and other forces ``still remain to be worked
out,'' Nitze said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz and foreign ministers of the
other North Atlantic Treaty Organization countries are to confer
Thursday and Friday in Brussels about a joint position for
negotiations on reducing conventional arms in Europe.
   In a speech later, Nitze declared: ``There is opportunity for
great progress in reducing the level of East-West military
confrontation across the board. But complacency is unjustified. Much
hard work lies ahead if this potential is to be realized.''
   On conventional arms, he said: ``It would be imprudent to assume
that the huge imbalance between NATO and Warsaw Pact conventional
capabilities can be redressed solely through arms control
negotiations.
   ``One must also consider the fact that, given the record of past
efforts at conventional arms control, any relief from arms control
in this area is likely to come only several years in the future.''
   Negotiations on conventional arms by the 16 NATO and seven Warsaw
Pact nations are expected to begin early next year in Vienna,
Austria, under the name Conventional Stability Talks.
   NATO issued a report last month saying the Warsaw Pact has a huge
advantage in such weapons. It cited 51,500 main battle tanks for the
Warsaw Pact and 16,424 for NATO, along with 22,400 armored infantry
fighting vehicles for the East and 4,153 for the West.
   Nitze said progress has been made toward reducing long-range, or
strategic, nuclear weapons, ``but many hurdles must yet be crossed
before the finish line is reached and it is by no means a foregone
conclusion that they will be.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
