<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0644,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Activist Makes First Trip Abroad in 20 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with Hajek's arrival,
comments; picks up 5th pvs: Mock and ... </NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jiri Hajek, a human rights activist and
former Czechoslovak foreign minister, was allowed to leave his
country for the first time in 20 years on Monday for a visit to
Austria.
   Hajek, foreign minister during the 1968 ``Prague Spring'' reform
period, was accompanied by his wife when he arrived in Vienna.
Czechoslovak authorities gave them 10-day travel permits.
   Hajek, asked by reporters in Vienna whether Czechoslovak
authorities were changing their attitude toward dissenters, said:
``I would not like to project my simple adventure into a broader
(political) context ... I don't want to make any speculation for the
time being.''
   He called the decision to allow him to visit Austria ``a very
pleasant surprise.
   ``I was invited in September and in the meantime things were
arranged'' between his Austrian hosts and the Czechoslovak
authorities, he said.
   Hajek, 75, was invited to lecture Wednesday at a peace research
institute in the southern city of Graz.
   Hajek's trip came as Czechoslovak Foreign Minister Jaromir
Johanes held talks Monday with his Austrian counterpart, Alois Mock.
Johanes is on his first trip abroad since becoming foreign minister
in October.
   Mock and Johanes signed an agreement to exchange cultural
institutes in the two capitals. According to Austrian radio, it will
be the first such institute established in Prague by a Western
country.
   Hajek, a signatory of the Charter 77 human rights manifesto, was
ousted as foreign minister after the Soviet-led invasion of
Czechoslovakia that crushed the social and economic reforms of
Communist Party leader Alexander Dubcek.
   In 1970, Hajek was expelled from the party, along with a
half-million other people. Hajek has been repeatedly harassed by
authorities and was recently detained along with more than 20 other
activists to prevent an independent symposium on Czechoslovak
history from taking place in Prague.
   Last month, Dubcek was permitted to travel to the West for the
first time since 1970 to receive an honorary degree in Italy.
   In his meeting with Johanes, Mock asked that Dubcek also be
granted permission to travel to Austria for a lecture. The
Czechoslovak foreign minister's reaction was not known.
</TEXT>
