<DOCNO> AP881205-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 2253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-IranAir     12-05 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Iran Air,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aviation Council Weighs Iran Air Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. aviation agency on Monday put off a
decision on whether to condemn the United States for shooting down
an Iranian passenger jet.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization's governing council
met to discuss a report from its technical staff, which said the jet
only had 40 seconds to respond to a warning before it was blown up
by a U.S. warship.
   Assad Kotaite, the organization's president, said the group met
for three hours but came to no conclusions.
   He said the 33-nation governing council would hold further talks
Wednesday. But he said the group favors asking the organization's
Navigation Commission to make a recommendation on the report at the
governing council's next session in February.
   The Iran Air Airbus A-300 was shot down over the Persian Gulf by
the U.S. warship Vincennes on July 3. All 290 people on board were
killed.
   The report was made available Friday to the Canadian Press news
agency. According to CP, the report said U.S. warships in the
Persian Gulf had no way to hear radio transmissions between the Iran
Air flight and air traffic controllers.
   The Iranian delegation to the governing council's meeting called
for immediate condemnation of the United States. The country does
not have a vote on the council.
   ``This tragic incident has one very big technical aspect,''
spokesman Mahmood Hajighasemali said. But he added, ``The most
important aspects are the humanitarian and legal aspects.''
   Edmund Stohr, the U.S. delegate, declined comment.
   The report concluded that several warnings were issued to the jet
before the Vincennes downed it, but only one warning _ from another
U.S. vessel in the area _ was coded specifically for Iran Air Flight
655.
   The plane only had about 40 seconds to react to that warning
before it was shot down, the report said. It said the ``absence of a
clear method of addressing challenged civil aircraft'' in U.S. Navy
procedures probably contributed to the failure of the airliner crew
to heed radioed warnings.
   The Pentagon had no comment Monday. Its investigation found that
a series of events aboard the Vincennes led the ship's crew to
believe the Airbus was an attacking Iranian war plane.
   A total of 159 nations belong to the International Civil Aviation
Organization, headquartered in Montreal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
