<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL-JessicaHahn     12-05 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL-Jessica Hahn,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Church Secretary Says She Won't Mind If Jim Bakker Goes To
Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-PTL, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BURT GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former church secretary turned Playboy model and
disc jockey Jessica Hahn said Monday that indicted PTL founder Jim
Bakker was playing for sympathy when he said he would kill himself
if it would help Christianity.
   Bakker and three former aides were indicted Monday on federal
charges of mail fraud, wire fraud and conspiring to defraud the
public.
   ``In March of 1984,'' she said, ``John Fletcher (a PTL colleague
of Bakker's) came to me and said, `Jessica, Jim Bakker told me to
tell you if it would save Christianity, he would blow his head off.'
He's used it on me, he's used it on the church, and now he's trying
to use it on you.''
   Ms. Hahn, speaking at a news conference, predicted that Bakker
would be convicted on the charges and said she would testify against
him in court.
   Ms. Hahn, who engaged in a sexual encounter with Bakker in a
Flordia motel room eight years ago, was paid $363,000 in hush money
but later gave most of the money back.
   She lived at one time in the Playboy Mansion in Los Angeles and
wrote an article for Playboy about her affair with Bakker. The
article appeared with bare-breasted photos of the church worker
turned rock music video vamp.
   Earlier this year she began work as an announcer at KOY in
Phoenix.
   Ms. Hahn was one of those who testified before the grand jury
that returned the 24-count indictment. She said she knew about the
indictment a year ago and was told they would be handed up after the
November elections.
   Ms. Hahn disputed charges that she had brought down the PTL,
saying it would have happened without her.
   She told reporters her involvement with the story had cost her
her family.
   ``My mother and I have not talked, I have not seen my family, in
one year,'' she said, adding that she was hoping to finally put the
controversy behind her.
   ``This is where it ends for me,'' she said. ``I have lived with
this for eight years ... I refuse to be a slave to this any longer.''
