<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-PatrickKennedy     12-05 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Patrick Kennedy,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patrick Kennedy Awed by Legislative Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was driving up to the Statehouse on
Monday that Patrick Kennedy, soon to be state Rep. Patrick Kennedy,
was struck by the awesomeness of it all.
   ``I guess it was when I drove up today and wondered whether I
should go in the legislative parking lot or just park out front,''
Kennedy said during a break in an all-day orientation for freshmen
legislators.
   At 21, the Providence College junior is the latest member of the
Kennedy clan to begin a political career. He won a bitterly fought
Democratic primary in September over a five-term incumbent and was
automatically elected from the west-side neighborhood because he
faced no Republican opposition.
   Kennedy, the son of Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and nephew of
former President John F. Kennedy, knows his arrival in the House
will attract more than normal attention.
   ``There is a certain responsibility you're held accountable for,
not just as a representative from your district, but you're held
accountable for what my family's commitment to public service has
held for so many people,'' he said.
   The legacy of public service doesn't ease the nervousness felt by
freshman legislators.
   ``I was so nervous getting up today with the microphone. I'm
going to have to practice,'' Kennedy said. ``Even my father's still
nervous when he gets up to speak.''
   He says he plans to do his legislative homework early and get to
legislative leaders while they still are considering changes in
bills in which he has an interest.
   The social science major has trimmed down his class load so he
can handle his legislative duties. As for graduation: ``I'm in no
rush,'' he said.
</TEXT>
