<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 11,0546</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Dec. 11, the 346th day of 1988. There are 20
days left in the year. Hanukkah, the Jewish Feast of Lights,
concludes at sunset.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1936, Britain's King Edward VIII abdicated in order to marry
American divorcee Wallis Warfield Simpson. In a radio address,
Edward said he ``would have found it impossible'' to carry out his
duties as king ``without the help and support of the woman I love.''
   On this date:
   In 1719, the first recorded sighting of the aurora borealis took
place in New England.
   In 1792, France's King Louis XVI went on trial, accused of
treason. (Convicted and condemned, he was sent to the guillotine the
following January.)
   In 1816, Indiana became the 19th state.
   In 1872, the first black U.S. governor took office as Pinckney
Benton Stewart Pinchback became acting governor of Louisiana.
   In 1882, Boston's Bijou Theatre, the first American playhouse to
be lighted exclusively by electricity, gave its first performance,
of Gilbert and Sullivan's ``Iolanthe.''
   In 1928, police in Buenos Aires thwarted an attempt on the life
of President-elect Herbert Hoover.
   In 1937, Italy withdrew from the League of Nations.
   In 1941, Germany and Italy declared war on the United States.
   In 1946, UNICEF was established.
   In 1961, a U.S. aircraft carrier carrying Army helicopters
arrived in Saigon _ the first direct American military support for
South Vietnam's battle against Communist guerrillas.
   In 1981, the U.N. Security Council chose Javier Perez de Cuellar
of Peru to be the fifth secretary-general of the world body.
   In 1985, General Electric agreed to acquire the RCA Corp. and its
subsidiary, NBC.
   In 1986, the South African government drastically expanded its
6-month-old media restrictions by imposing prior censorship and
banning coverage of a wide range of peaceful anti-apartheid protests.
   Ten years ago: Six masked men bound and gagged ten employees at a
Lufthansa cargo area at New York's Kennedy International Airport and
made off with $5.8 million in cash and jewelry, only a fraction of
which has been recovered.
   Five years ago: Pope John Paul II paid a historic visit to a
Lutheran church in Rome, the first visit by a Roman Catholic pontiff
to a Protestant church in his own diocese.
   One year ago: NATO allies urged the U.S. Senate to ratify the
intermediate-range missile treaty quickly, and underscored their
support by pledging to let the Soviet Union inspect missile bases in
five European countries.
   Today's birthdays: Producer Carlo Ponti is 75. Exiled Soviet
author Alexander Solzhenitsyn is 70. Actress Betsy Blair is 65.
Actor Jean-Louis Trintignant is 58. Actress Rita Moreno is 57. Actor
Ron Carey is 53. California state Assemblyman Tom Hayden is 49. Sen.
Max Baucus, D-Mont., is 47. Actress Donna Mills is 45. Singer Brenda
Lee is 44. Actress Lynda Day George is 42. Movie director Susan
Seidelman is 36. Actress Bess Armstrong is 35. Singer Jermaine
Jackson is 34.
   Thought for today: ``The fear of life is the favorite disease of
the 20th century.'' _ William Lyon Phelps, American educator and
journalist (1865-1943).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
