<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 13,0476</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, Dec. 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Dec. 13, the 348th day of 1988. There are 18
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1928, George Gershwin's musical work ``An American in Paris''
had its premiere at Carnegie Hall in New York.
   On this date:
   In 1577, five ships commanded by Sir Francis Drake embarked on
Drake's famous circumnavigation of the globe.
   In 1642, New Zealand was discovered by Dutch navigator Abel
Tasman.
   In 1769, Dartmouth College in New Hampshire received its charter.
   In 1835, Phillips Brooks, the American Episcopal bishop who wrote
the words to ``O Little Town of Bethlehem,'' was born in Boston.
   In 1862, Union forces suffered a major defeat at the hands of the
Confederates at the Battle of Fredericksburg.
   In 1918, President Woodrow Wilson arrived in France, becoming the
first chief executive to visit a European country while in office.
   In 1944, during World War II, a Japanese kamikaze crashed into
the U.S. cruiser Nashville, killing 138 crewmen.
   In 1964, in a ceremony in El Paso, Texas, President Lyndon B.
Johnson and Mexican President Gustavo Diaz Ordaz set off an
explosion that diverted the Rio Grande, reshaping the U.S.-Mexican
border and ending a century-old dispute.
   In 1977, 29 people, including the entire University of Evansville
basketball team, died when their DC-3 crashed after takeoff from
Evansville, Ind.
   In 1977, a dormitory fire at Providence College in Rhode Island
claimed the lives of 10 students.
   In 1981, authorities in Poland imposed martial law in a crackdown
on the Solidarity labor movement. (Major provisions of the decree
were lifted a year later; martial law was formally ended in 1983.)
   In 1984, artificial heart recipient William J. Schroeder suffered
his first stroke after receiving the Jarvik-7 device at Humana
Hospital Audubon in Louisville, Ky.
   Ten years ago: The Philadelphia Mint began stamping the Susan B.
Anthony dollar, which went into circulation the following July.
   Five years ago: Martha Layne Collins was inaugurated as
Kentucky's first female governor, declaring, ``This first for
Kentucky will be ever dedicated to putting Kentucky first.''
   One year ago: Before leaving for Oslo, Norway, Secretary of State
George P. Shultz told reporters in Copenhagen, Denmark, the Reagan
administration would begin making case-by-case funding requests for
the proposed ``Star Wars'' defense system.
   Today's birthdays: Secretary of State George P. Shultz is 68.
Actor-comedian Dick Van Dyke is 63. Actor Christopher Plummer is 61.
Singer John Davidson is 47. Singer Ted Nugent is 40.
   Thought for Today: ``In any assembly the simplest way to stop the
transacting of business and split the ranks is to appeal to a
principle.'' _ Jacques Barzun, American author, educator and
historian.
</TEXT>
