<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 14,0588</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, Dec. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, Dec. 14, the 349th day of 1988. There are 17
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1799, the first President of the United States, George
Washington, died at his Mount Vernon, Va., home at age 67, nearly
three years after leaving office.
   On this date:
   In 1819, Alabama became the 22nd state.
   In 1861, Albert, the prince consort of England and the husband of
Queen Victoria, died in London.
   In 1911, Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen became the first man
to reach the South Pole, beating an expedition led by Robert F.
Scott.
   In 1939, the Soviet Union was dropped from the League of Nations.
   In 1945, Josef Kramer, known as ``the beast of Belsen,'' and ten
others were hanged for crimes committed at the Belsen and Oswiecim
Nazi concentration camps.
   In 1946, the U.N. General Assembly voted to establish the United
Nations' headquarters in New York.
   In 1962, the U.S. space probe Mariner II approached Venus,
transmitting back information about the planet's atmosphere and
surface temperature.
   In 1975, six South Moluccan terrorists surrendered to police
after holding 23 persons hostage for 12 days on a train near the
Dutch town of Beilen.
   In 1977, representatives of Egypt and Israel gathered in Cairo
for the first formal, face-to-face peace conference between Arabs
and Jews.
   In 1980, fans around the world paid tribute to John Lennon, six
days after he was shot to death in New York City. Hundreds of silent
vigils were held at the request of Lennon's widow, Yoko Ono.
   In 1981, in a move that drew widespread denunciation, Israel
abruptly annexed the Golan Heights, which it had seized from Syria
in 1967.
   In 1984, the Reagan administration and Cuba reached an agreement
under which Cuban criminals and mental patients who had come to the
United States as part of the 1980 ``Freedom Flotilla'' would be sent
back.
   In 1985, former New York Yankee Roger Maris, who broke Babe
Ruth's single-season home run record by hitting 61 in 1961, died in
Houston at age 51.
   In 1986, the experimental aircraft Voyager, piloted by Dick Rutan
and Jeana Yeager, took off from Edwards Air Force Base in California
on the first non-stop, non-refueled flight around the world. (The
trip took nine days.)
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter told ABC-TV interviewer
Barbara Walters it was up to Israel to accept or reject a proposed
peace treaty with Egypt.
   Five years ago: The U.S. battleship New Jersey turned its big
guns on Syrian positions in Lebanon for the first time after
American F-14 reconnaissance flights were fired on.
   One year ago: Supreme Court nominee Anthony M. Kennedy told his
confirmation hearing he had no hidden agenda for abortion and
privacy cases. Chrysler pleaded no contest to federal charges of
selling several thousand vehicles as new even though they'd been
driven by employees with the odometer disconnected.
   Today's birthdays: Retired Gen. James H. Doolittle is 92. Former
U.S. Sen. Margaret Chase Smith, R-Maine, is 91. Comedian-actor Morey
Amsterdam is 74. Country singer Charlie Rich is 56. Singer Abbe Lane
is 56. Actor-director George Furth is 56. Actress Lee Remick is 53.
Actress Patty Duke is 42.
   Thought for Today: ``If love is the answer, could you rephrase
the question?'' _ Lily Tomlin, American comedian and actress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
