<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 16,0513</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday, Dec. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, Dec. 16, the 351st day of 1988. There are 15
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1773, the Boston Tea Party took place as American colonists,
disguised as Indians, boarded a British ship in Boston Harbor and
dumped more than 300 chests of tea overboard in a protest against
taxes.
   On this date:
   In 1653, Oliver Cromwell became lord protector of England,
Scotland and Ireland.
   In 1770, the German composer Ludwig van Beethoven was born in
Bonn, Germany.
   In 1809, Napoleon Bonaparte was divorced from the Empress
Josephine by an act of the French Senate.
   In 1905, the entertainment trade publication Variety came out
with its first weekly issue.
   In 1916, Gregory Rasputin, the monk who wielded powerful
influence over the Russian court, was murdered.
   In 1944, the World War II Battle of the Bulge began in Belgium.
   In 1950, President Harry S. Truman proclaimed a national state of
emergency in order to fight ``Communist imperialism.''
   In 1960, 134 people were killed when a United Air Lines DC-8 and
a TWA Super Constellation collided over New York City and crashed.
   In 1976, the government halted its swine flu vaccination program
following reports of paralysis apparently linked to the vaccine.
   In 1981, police clashed with striking coal miners at the Wujek
pit in Katowice in southern Poland. Nine miners were fatally injured.
   In 1982, Environmental Protection Agency head Anne M. Gorsuch
(later Burford) became the first Cabinet-level officer to be cited
for contempt of Congress for her refusal to submit documents
requested by a congressional committee.
   In 1985, at services in Fort Campbell, Ky., President and Mrs.
Reagan offered condolences to the families of 248 soldiers killed in
the crash of a chartered plane in Newfoundland.
   In 1985, reputed organized-crime chief Paul Castellano was shot
to death outside a New York City restaurant.
   Ten years ago: Former California Gov. Ronald Reagan joined other
conservatives in denouncing President Jimmy Carter's decision to
recognize the People's Republic of China, calling it an ``outright
betrayal of our close friend and ally,'' Taiwan.
   Five years ago: A judge in Riverside, Calif., denied a request
from cerebral palsy victim Elizabeth Bouvia to starve herself to
death in a county hospital. (Bouvia, a paraplegic, had said she did
not want to live ``trapped in a useless body.'')
   One year ago: Former deputy White House chief of staff Michael K.
Deaver, a close associate of President and Mrs. Reagan, was
convicted of lying under oath to a grand jury and a congressional
subcommittee.
   Today's birthdays: Author Victor S. Pritchett is 88. Author
Arthur C. Clarke is 71. Actress Liv Ullmann is 49. CBS News
correspondent Lesley Stahl is 47. Football player William ``The
Refrigerator'' Perry is 26.
   Thought for today: ``Nations, like individuals, have to limit
their objectives or take the consequences.'' _ James Reston,
American journalist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
