<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1412EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--SemiticSoap Adv18   12-05 0949</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Semitic Soap, Adv18,0979</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Soap operas are not known for heavy social
philosophy or ethnic diversity. So it was unusual, to say the least,
for two Orthodox Jews to make an appearance on NBC's ``Day of Our
Lives.'' The explanation is Leah Laiman, and she knew whereof she
wrote.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By NANCY SHULINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leah Laiman's life would make a lousy soap opera.
   She was raised an Orthodox Jew in Hamilton, Ontario, where she
spent her weekends reading the classics. She moved to New York and
attended a Jewish women's college. She did hang around Greenwich
Village one summer, though she didn't exactly blend into the crowd.
``I was the only orthodox kosher virgin beatnik in New York,'' she
says _ until her father showed up to take her home.
   It is, therefore, no small irony that Laiman, a woman with barely
a nodding acquaintance with life's seamy side, should wind up as the
head writer for one of the seamier soaps, NBC's ``Days of Our
Lives.''
   Soap Opera Digest rated it the most violent soap on television.
``Bad planning,'' Laiman explains. Murder and mayhem are simply ``a
cheap way to end a Friday. The show did go through a period where
there was a lot of violence toward women. I'm sorry for that.''
   Other than that, though, Laiman makes no apology for the violence
and sex served up on her soap. ``Sure, soap operas are full of sex
and violence,'' she says. ``But they are not like movies and they
aren't rated `R.' There is a limit to what you can do.
   ``And in a way, soaps are very moralistic. Yes, people do naughty
things, but the bad people always get punished. The good guys always
win and get lots of fan mail.''
   Salem U.S.A., the show's fictional location, is a slightly more
enlightened place than the ``white-bread town'' Laiman found when
she moved over from ABC's General Hospital three years ago.
   Like most soap opera settings, Salem remains overwhelmingly white
middle class. ``There are two blacks,'' she says. ``And everybody's
Christian.''
   Not quite everyone, it turns out.
   Enter the first Orthodox Jewish characters in the soap opera's
history.
   ``Some people who watch these shows probably don't know any
Jews,'' she explains. ``I just wanted to show they have no horns.''
   She created Robin, a beautiful young doctor who just happened to
be an Orthodox Jew. Robin fell in love with Mike, also a doctor and,
as luck would have it, a Christian.
   ``Robin's father was a pharmacist. He wore a yarmulke all the
time. Robin never ate out. In the (non-kosher) cafeteria at the
hospital, all she could eat was salad.''
   Since intimate dinner dates are a soap opera staple, Laiman
created a kosher deli and saw to it Robin stayed home on the
Sabbath. On Friday nights, ``she lit candles and wouldn't answer the
phone or ride in the car unless it was a medical emergency.''
   Mike gave serious thought to converting, then realized he
couldn't give up his heritage. Eventually, Laiman resolved the plot
by having Robin and her father leave town.
   Laiman regrets that their departure meant there were no more Jews
in Salem. Still, the alternatives would have been worse. For Robin
to marry a non-Jew or worse, to abandon her own religion, would be
out of the question.
   In charting the soap's plot, Laiman remains mindful of her
influence over the audience. ``I would never let a woman have an
abortion and go crazy about it,'' she says. ``I might not have an
abortion myself, but it's not up to me to put that in the show and
influence people.''
   After six years in the soap opera business _ she worked on
``General Hospital'' for three years before moving to ``Days'' _
Laiman says, ``I'm still shocked to this day that people respond to
the show the way they do. They identify so totally with these
people's lives, they see them only as these characters.''
   As head writer, Laiman's job is to map out the story, which is
subject to approval by the network. Associate head writers break the
plot down into daily segments. Dialogue writers fill in the daily
scripts.
   The show is filmed in Los Angeles, but Laiman prefers to stay in
New York. She travels to the West Coast for meetings, but spends
most of her time in the Manhattan apartment she shares with her
husband, producer-director Ralph Toporoff, her stepdaughter,
Melinda, 19, and her 15-month-old baby, Danielle. The couple also
has a stepson, Ian, 23.
   Writing a soap opera ``doesn't require tremendous writing talent,
though it does require skill and understanding of the medium,''
Laiman says.
   ``Soaps appeal to middle-of-the-road conservatives. Television is
not about public service. It's about advertising dollars and ratings
and not offending viewers.''
   Still, she keeps an eye out for ways to incorporate her values
into the show, and to pass along responsible information whenever
possible.
   When the story line dealt with sex abuse, Laiman included a
hot-line number at the end of the episode. She also tried to ``make
it very clear that sexual abuse is not the victim's fault.''
   With Robin's departure, Salem is, for the time being, once again
an all-Christian town. But Laiman says plans are already in the
works to bring Robin back.
   In the meantime, there are other ways to get her points across.
Coming up: a love story involving a plastic surgeon who happens to
be black.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
