<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1413EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--MingoPower Adv18-2Takes   12-05 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Mingo Power, Adv18-2 Takes,0706</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ West Virginia seemed like a prime proving ground
when Congress created the Office of Economic Opportunity in 1964.
One of the first and one of the biggest of the anti-poverty agencies
was set up in Mingo County, one of the most stubborn pockets of
poverty in all of Appalachia. But over the years the Mingo County
Economic Opportunity Commission fell into the hands of a corrupt
political establishment it was created to fight.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 1960s, when Congress voted to
fight poverty by organizing the poor to fight for themselves, the
rallying cry was, ``power to the people.''
   What developed in Mingo County lends credence to a much older
adage, ``power corrupts.''
   In 1965, when the Mingo County Economic Opportunity Commission
was formed, the anti-poverty agency quickly became a thorn in the
side of the political establishment. But over the years it became an
ally of the establishment, until federal prosecutors started sending
EOC officials to jail.
   ``The EOC was a product of the 1960s, and the 1960s was a very
anti-establishment period,'' says Carl Bradford, trustee director of
the Mingo County EOC. ``All this was done the way the EOC wanted it
done. And the idea was to give them lots of money to go out and beat
up on the establishment.''
   ``Lots of money'' was the key, especially in a place like Mingo
County, where it seems there is never enough to go around. Today,
the EOC's annual $1.6 million budget is a major economic force in
the county, second only to the county commission, which has a budget
of $2.74 million, and the board of education, which controls 20
percent of the jobs in the county. The EOC provides jobs and
essential services to some 2,000 Mingo residents.
   But somewhere along the way, the power and money corrupted: At
least five top EOC officials have been convicted on federal charges
of defrauding the agency, including long-time director Larry
Hamrick. He was sentenced to 12 years in a federal prison for
siphoning off anti-poverty funds for his personal use and to
influence county politicians.
   Hamrick allegedly defrauded the anti-poverty commission of more
than $60,000. Prosecutors said he ordered checks totaling more than
$42,000 to be written to one individual, purportedly for hauling
coal to low-income families. They said, however, that the bulk of
the money was kicked back to Hamrick.
   Hamrick also allegedly arranged for employees to be listed on the
commission books as job-training developers when they actually had
jobs within the agency. Prosecutors said Hamrick also arranged for
about $10,500 to be given from the EOC's administrative account to
relatives of a commission employee, money that also came back to
Hamrick.
   Hamrick, after pleading guilty to charges of fraud, obstruction
of justice and conspiracy, testified in another Mingo County trial
that he on several occasions approved travel checks for Don Chafin,
an EOC official who also pleaded guilty to fraud charges. Hamrick
said there was ``no basis'' for the checks other than ``Chafin said
he was short money in his checking account.''
   On other occasions, Hamrick said, he and Chafin shared the
proceeds of checks made out to another EOC employee who ``cashed
them and gave the money back to me and I split it with Don Chafin
exactly even.''
   ``Money is what runs through the veins of the political system
and they found the fountain of youth,'' says assistant U.S. attorney
Joe Savage.
   West Virginia seemed like a prime proving ground when Congress
created the Office of Economic Opportunity in 1964. The act spawned
community action agencies nationwide, all based on the idea that
poverty could be eradicated by giving poor people the power to
challenge the forces that kept them poor. One of the first, and one
of the biggest, was quickly set up in Mingo County, one of the most
stubborn pockets of poverty in all of Appalachia.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881205-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1414EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--MingoPower Adv18-1stAdd   12-05 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Mingo Power, Adv18-1st Add,0722</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>WILLIAMSON, W.Va.: of Appalachia.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Congress decided that low-income people were suffering because
government _ and the rest of the establishment _ wasn't giving them
their fair share,'' Bradford says. ``It was set up to attack local
government as a grass roots organization.''
   Organization was the second key. Bradford said the way to attack
the local power structure was obvious.
   ``Once you get past picketing and protesting as a method of
forcing change, the more effective way is at the ballot box,''
Bradford says. The EOC's first director, a young Mingo County
teacher named Huey Perry, capitalized on the ``power to the people''
mandate and quickly organized the poor into a counter political
structure.
   Perry, now a Huntington businessman manufacturing medical
equipment, contends that the success of the concept was its
downfall. He described his experiences with the EOC and its fight
with the Mingo power structure in a 1975 book called, ``They'll Cut
Off Your Project.'' That success was a threat, Perry said, and, in
1968, Congress changed the laws governing the Offfice of Economic
Opportunity to take away the anti-poverty agencies' independence and
return control to county governments.
   ``All of our expectations were very high _ that we were going to
be able to turn things around,'' Perry says. ``But at the national
level, they didn't want it. It was too much upheaval. That had to be
stopped, and I don't think we'll ever see that kind of social
experiment again.''
   With those changes, the ``social experiment'' soon became part of
the existing power structure. Perry moved on to other projects, and
the man he had hired as his deputy _ Larry Hamrick _ took over as
director.
   ``Hamrick would literally have taken the shirt off his back and
given it to you if he thought you needed it,'' Perry says. He tells
how one day he and Hamrick spotted a car that had gone off the
narrow highway and into a stream badly swollen by recent rains.
   ``Larry didn't hesitate,'' Perry says. ``He jumped out of our car
and was in that water waist deep to pull people out of that car.''
   A very different man was described in the federal indictments
that sent Hamrick to prison. According to one indictment, Hamrick
threatened a hospitalized man who was a prosecution witness.
Pointing to the oxygen tank by the bed of Kenneth ``Bubby''
Phillips, Hamrick told him, ``There could be carbon monoxide in
it.'' Hamrick also was accused of intimidating another grand jury
witness, putting his hands around her throat and threatening to
choke her to death.
   After the federal government returned power over the poverty
agencies to county government, Perry said, ``I guess Larry chose to
work with them, became entailed in the system and became part of
it.''
   ``At first, he probably rationalized that he was protecting the
poor people in what he was doing...Had he not chosen the path he
did, he would have been fired within the year and the director would
have been somebody else the machine could have controlled.''
   These days, the Mingo County EOC is firmly in the control of the
establishment. This time, however, the establishment appears to be
Republican, an oddity in heavily Democratic Mingo County. A group
calling itself ``Voices of Concern'' has demanded the resignation of
executive director Tim Crum, a registered Republican who was elected
mayor of the town of Kermit on a non-partisan ticket, and has
expressed concern that the agency has become a GOP stronghold.
   Crum was recommended to the EOC board by Bradford, who was
appointed EOC trustee director by Republican Gov. Arch Moore when
Hamrick was indicted.
   Regardless of who is in control in Mingo County, Perry says he
believes that the economic system the EOC tried to challenge is the
source of Mingo's political quagmire. ``There's no question, in my
mind, that the poverty there breeds this kind of politics,'' he says.
   ``People who are ambitious see politics as the way you make
money, the way you succeed, the way you get power. But, if the
economy were better, ambitious people might try to succeed in some
economic sense.''
   End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 18
</TEXT>
