<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv18   12-05 0885</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv18,0908</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's no mystery why actor Sam Robards quit the
legitimate theater and went hunting for a television series.
   ``I needed to make some money,'' says Robards, who comes from a
distinguished acting family with roots in New York. ``I spent seven
years working in the theater. I was tired of making $160 a week and
being in debt all the time.''
   Robards and his wife, actress Suzy Amis, packed up, moved from
New York into a rented house in Los Angeles and bought furniture at
garage sales. Their marriage was a case of life imitating art. They
played husband and wife in the movie ``Fandango,'' and afterward got
married.
   ``I came out for the pilot season and read for a whole mess of
things,'' he says. ``I was offered two pilots, and I chose this
one.''
   The one he chose was ``TV 101,'' a one-hour drama on CBS about a
high school journalism teacher who brings the school newspaper into
the electronic age. He sets up a television news show on the
school's internal network, which enables the student journalists to
learn (according to network publicity) as much about themselves and
their own lives as they do about television.
   Robards stars as Kevin Keegan, an iconoclast whose return to
teaching at his alma mater doesn't inspire enthusiasm from the
principal who remembers his troubled days as a student.
   Robards had to read seven times for the role, twice after he did
a screen test. ``I was the first person they saw for the role,'' he
says, ``but they were committed to the great American talent search.
They went to New York, Chicago, they saw everybody. I had to fight
for the role.''
   On a lunch break at the Culver Studios, Robards eats soup from a
large Styrofoam cup in a barren conference room. He has the flu, but
is fighting it rather than miss a day's work.
   Robards has butted heads with the producers at Grant Tinker's GTG
Entertainment over interpretation of his character.
   ``The way I play him is decidedly different from the way the
creators saw him,'' he says. ``I guess we're ironing it out as we go
along.
   ``To me, Keegan's a guy who's lost. He's been through a lot, he's
seen a lot, but he's lost, especially in this environment. Their
idea is that he's sort of able to get by. There are no
life-and-death issues for him, except when it comes to his daughter
and ex-wife.''
   The story presents Keegan as a former free-lance television
newsman who has worked in Latin America.
   ``He witnessed a lot of unpleasantness, but he was just an
observer,'' Robards says. ``That was how he got by. `I'm just
shooting it with my camera, so I'm not responsible for any of it.'
So, after being complacent and irresponsible, he comes into the
school and tries to make a difference.''
   Like most of the cast on ``TV 101,'' Robards is a virtual
newcomer to the television audience. He starred earlier this season
with Valerie Bertinelli in ``Pancho Barnes.'' He has also done a few
guest roles on series and has a tiny role in the movie ``Bird.'' He
has an equally small part in director Brian de Palma's upcoming
Vietnam film ``Casualties of War.''
   ``I guess it was deliberate to put so many new people in the cast
so you wouldn't have anyone overshadowing the concept of the show,''
he says.
   Robards is the son of Jason Robards Jr. and Lauren Bacall. His
grandfather was the late character actor Jason Robards Sr.
   Although he grew up in an acting household, he went through the
usual boyhood ambitions, such as policeman and ballplayer, before
becoming an actor at the age of 19.
   ``I was ejected from Sarah Lawrence College for lousy grades,''
he says. ``I'd always played football throughout my school years.
When I left school I went to the Eugene O'Neill Theater Center in
Connecticut and studied there for a while. Then I went on an
audition and got a job as an understudy and assistant stage manager.
   ``Acting wasn't something I'd dreamed about. I'd been around it
all my life. I knew the business side of it. It wasn't so glamorous.
The stage is where you do the best acting, but there's no money in
it. I tried films. If I can make a name for myself I can get better
parts instead of being the first man they see after lunch.''
   With his father he has done only a few scenes _ excerpts from
O'Neill's ``Long Day's Journey into Night'' that deal with
alcoholism.
   ``I guess we did it in part because my father had been
addicted,'' he says. ``That play illustrates so clearly its effects
on a family.''
   Robards isn't sure whether having famous parents was a help or
not.
   ``I think I was seen for a lot of things because of my parents,''
he says. ``People wanted to see if I was capable of doing anything.
Some people had a preconception and looked for something bad. It's
getting better now. I can be more on my own.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
