<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1419EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv18   12-05 1057</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv18,1092</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 19, Barry Williams was a television
heartthrob, receiving 800 fan letters a week. At 25, he had to
scramble for work, redirecting his faltering career from television
to theater.
   Now, nearly 20 years after he first played older brother Greg
Brady on ``The Brady Bunch,'' the 34-year-old Williams finds himself
doing both theater and television.
   He's making his Broadway debut in the musical ``Romance Romance''
and appearing in a new ``Brady Bunch'' special, ``A Very Brady
Christmas,'' to be televised Sunday, Dec. 18, on CBS.
   ``Part of an actor's life is just being ready, tuned and
stretched to work,'' he says, although he asked to look at the
script before he decided to do the new Brady movie. But when the
chance came to audition for ``Romance Romance,'' he didn't hesitate.
   It's not as if Williams hadn't done any musicals recently. In
fact, he has done four in the last year in places such as Kansas
City, Pittsburgh and Birmingham, Mich.
   Williams joined the cast of ``Romance Romance'' in October. The
show, running since May at the Helen Hayes Theater, is two small
musicals in one. In Act I, the actor plays an amorous
turn-of-the-century Viennese dandy. In the second act, he's a
happily married man contemplating an affair.
   ``I don't think I've had a better role in terms of scope and in
terms of growth,'' he says. ``They are two separate musicals with
completely different acting styles. I have to be in top shape for
this show.''
   Williams wasn't always a singer. He started studying at 16 during
the glory days of ``The Brady Bunch.'' The show, which ran for five
seasons on ABC, was one of the last of the innocent family comedies.
The cast included a widow, a widower, six kids, a maid and a dog.
Problems were resolved happily before the last commercial.
   Williams, who was raised in California, started performing at age
11 after persuading his parents to let him attend acting classes.
   ``I was pretty precocious as a child,'' he recalls. ``I liked the
idea of being different people and characters, kind of what acting
is. It looked like a fun thing to do.''
   Before being cast on ``The Brady Bunch,'' Williams appeared on
just about every well-known television series of the late 1960s.
From ``The FBI'' to ``That Girl'' to ``Gomer Pyle'' to ``It Takes a
Thief'' to ``Mod Squad'' to ``Marcus Welby,'' he found work. ``The
Brady Bunch'' pretty much monopolized his teen-age years.
   ``When you've only got one childhood, you don't know if you're
missing a normal one or not,'' he says. ``I think being a teen-ager
is a fate akin to illness. It's a very difficult period, any way you
cut it.''
   Williams' problems started later.
   ``In my own life, I found that I went through my own teen-age
rebellion in my mid-20s because I had to be so serious and
responsible as a teen-ager,'' he says. ``I didn't have time to
rebel.''
   Typecast because of his association with ``The Brady Bunch,'' and
regarded within the television industry as only capable of light
comedy, he was thought of as a teen-ager, even after he passed 21.
   ``I didn't understand why I had to audition,'' Williams recalls.
``After all, I had credits. I had been working a long time. It's a
very arrogant attitude, ludicrous in this business. I was back on
the proving block again and I didn't feel that I was supposed to
prove myself.''
   Still, Williams got jobs. He always was able to do several
musicals or regional theater offerings a year, but that would leave
periods of six or seven months when he didn't work.
   ``I was in trouble for a while,'' Williams says. ``I borrowed
money, sold a house and I gambled. I even dissolved investments to
get some sort of cash going. I was dipping from the well.''
   What saved him was that he got hungry for a career and realized
he wasn't having one.
   ``What I did was change my attitude,'' he says. ``I came to
realize that refusing to audition was kind of an excuse for not
really putting myself back on the line.
   ``I decided I wouldn't use `The Brady Bunch' to work against me,
and I wouldn't use it to work for me. I just had it as a credit, one
part of my career. It was like starting over again.''
   The theater has given him employment during the lean years.
Eventually, he would love to do an action adventure television
series.
   ``I'm always looking for something else,'' Williams says. ``When
I have a steady job and I'm working, then the business is fine. But
if I'm out of work for more than 10 days, I'm already looking for
something else to do.''
   ``The Brady Bunch'' may have left network television in the
mid-1970s, but it lives on in rerun heaven. The series is still
televised by many local stations as well as by Ted Turner's
Atlanta-based SuperStation.
   Williams doesn't watch the old episodes.
   ``It's a little like home movies,'' he says. ``I know how they
turn out.''
   The TV movie was a natural, considering television's insatiable
appetite for nostalgia, even for something that occurred as recently
as 1974. But before Williams agreed to do the movie, he asked to see
the script. He liked what he read, particularly the fact that Greg
was now grown up and responsible _ a doctor, married and with a son.
   Williams filmed the Christmas movie last summer along with most
of the original cast members, including Florence Henderson, Robert
Reed and Ann B. Davis.
   ``It was a good experience, working with people I like a lot,''
he says. ``I'm glad we're doing a reunion because it somehow sort of
legitimizes all of those early years. It almost makes them current.
   ``I could go my whole life and never do another `Brady Bunch'
episode and it would be OK because Greg has a kid and he's a doctor
and he's married. It answers the question `Whatever happened to Greg
Brady?'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 18</NOTE>
