<DOCNO> AP881205-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-OmanGoesModern Adv11   12-05 1200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Oman Goes Modern, Adv11,1236</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Oman, Where Time Once Stood Still, Moves into Space Age</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: An accompanying item is BC-Oman-Glance, b0768.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until just a few years ago, the gates of this
old walled city were closed every night at 9 o'clock, as they had
been for centuries in a country where slavery still existed.
   Strangers had to carry oil lanterns so that guards would not
shoot them as intruders.
   Medicines, radios, schools, eye glasses and even trousers were
forbidden.
   The country, the size of New Mexico and perched on the
southeastern tip of the Arabian peninsula, was trapped in the Middle
Ages by a despotic and eccentric sultan, Said bin Taimur, who sought
to keep the 20th century at bay.
   Now, with its oil wealth, Oman has been transformed into a modern
state that has survived the traumas of the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war
at its doorstep.
   The war has also heightened Oman's strategic importance as one of
the guardians of the Strait of Hormuz, the gateway to the Persian
Gulf. It shares control of the narrow waterway with Iran.
   The transition from the 16th century to the space age has taken
Oman, the second largest country on the Arabian peninsula after
Saudi Arabia, less than two decades.
   Oman was propelled through this time warp by Sultan Said's only
son, Qaboos bin Said, who toppled his father in a bloodless coup at
his palace in Salalah, in southern Oman, July 23, 1970.
   The old sultan was flown by Britain's Royal Air Force to
well-appointed exile in London's swank Claridge's Hotel, where he
died two years later, surrounded by the very modernity he had shut
out since he took power in 1932.
   Qaboos, who trained at Britain's Sandhurst military academy and
travelled throughout Europe, had been under virtual house arrest by
his father for the previous three years in the belief he had been
tainted by foreign influences.
   Although Qaboos, 48, opened up his country to the outside world,
it remains partially veiled, its society still deeply rooted in
traditional Islamic values and customs.
   Omanis were among the first to embrace Islam when it spread
through the Arabian peninsula in the 7th century.
   Qaboos is an absolute monarch who permits no elections or
political parties. A couple of years ago he formed a consultative
assembly of appointed officials.
   Omanis are not allowed to marry foreigners. If they marry abroad,
they can't bring their families home, and they run the risk of
losing their citizenship. In the past, many Omani men sought foreign
wives to avoid having to pay dowries, traditional in the Arab world.
   In an effort to phase out what he has called ``the evil dowry
system,'' Qaboos last year ruled that no man should pay more than
2,000 riyals ($5,180) for a bride. He regularly exhorts sheiks and
other leaders to curb the dowry system during his annual three-week
meet-the-people safaris around the country.
   Drinking in public is prohibited. But foreigners, and a growing
number of younger Omanis, can imbibe freely in Muscat's hotels. The
penalties for drunkenness are severe, however.
   The news and journalists are restricted, as they are in most Arab
countries.
   Despite its breathtaking 1,800 miles of lagoon-studded Arabian
Sea coastline, tourists were kept out until a couple of years ago
because they were seen as a potential threat to Oman's traditions.
   Commerce and Industry Minister Salim bin Abdullah al-Ghazali
noted in a recent report: ``We don't want to see hippies with long
hair and dirty jeans ... in any part of the sultanate. We want
tourists who are mature in both behavior and outlook.''
   Despite the idiosyncracies of the old Sultan Said, Oman has a
long history of contact with the outside world.
   In the first millenium B.C., Omani seafarers sailed with the
monsoon winds to India and East Africa. In the 7th century, Omani
traders were sailing as far as China in their ocean-going wooden
dhows.
   Oman became a key trading center between the Arabian hinterland
and the Orient.
   The coming of steamships in the 1860s dealt a death blow to
Oman's mercantile power. It remained a key maritime and trading
crossroads for a while, but gradually slipped back into
near-medieval stagnation that ended only when Qaboos took power.
   On the steep, jagged cliffs that form Muscat's natural harbor,
sailors who have dropped anchor over the centuries have carved or
painted the names of their ships in big letters in the rock in a
bizarre visitors' book.
   Adm. Horatio Nelson, the victor of Trafalgar, was among the
visitors when he was a lowly midshipman aboard a Royal Navy vessel,
a British official noted.
   Today, Qaboos' gleaming Al-Alam palace, built in 1979, dominates
the seafront at Muscat, which means ``anchorage.'' Old brass cannons
on wooden carriages sit outside _ alongside modern anti-aircraft
guns on the seawall.
   When Qaboos seized power, Oman was wracked by an insurgency in
southern Dhofar province. With British, Jordanian and Iranian help
he crushed that revolt, which was backed by neighboring South Yemen,
the only Marxist country in the Arab world.
   With the oil discovered in 1964, although modest in volume
compared to other Persian Gulf states, Qaboos launched his
modernization program.
   In Sultan Said's day, there were only a few miles of paved road,
three religious schools, 15 telephones, two small hospitals, no
hotels and one small electricity generator in Muscat, installed in
the late 1960s.
   Now, Oman has nearly 2,000 miles of hardtop highways, about 700
schools, technical colleges and a university with some 220,000
students, 130 hospitals and clinics, nearly 50,000 telephones linked
by satellite to the outside world and 24 power stations.
   Annual per capita income has soared from $400 to nearly $6,000.
Schools, hospitals and other welfare programs are subsidised.
   But a generation is growing up with no experience of the
pre-Qaboos era.
   This has brought fears that young people will take today's
benefits for granted, raising expectations that may not be
sustainable at present levels once Oman's oil runs out. At the
current production rate of 600,000 barrels a day, this is expected
sometime in the next century.
   ``No one under 20 can remember how bad things were before 1970,''
said a Westerner who has lived in Oman for several years. ``People
have got used to the good things and unless that quality of life can
be maintained, there's some uncertainty about the future.
   ``Qaboos is trying to diversify the economy so he's not dependent
on oil.''
   The fall in oil prices has slowed development. But diplomats
noted that major projects and the basic infrastructure were already
completed before prices tumbled.
   ``We're concerned about oil prices, but there's no use crying
over spilt milk,'' Information Minister Abdul Aziz bin Mohammed
Rowes said. ``But we're cautiously optimistic that prices will
recover. We've lived without oil before and we'll just have to
tighten our belts.''
   He added: ``We're proceeding with a policy of Omanization,
gradually trimming the expatriates who've helped us develop. The
results so far are encouraging and we haven't sacrificed
performance. We're aiming for harmony.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
