<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1314EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   12-05 1172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv00,1220</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Stand and Deliver,'' ``Vampire at
Midnight,'' ``Bad Dreams,'' ``Call Me''
   
   ``Stand and Deliver'' (Warner Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95; Rated
PG)
   
   The first thing one needs to know about ``Stand and Deliver'' is
that it is a true story. Because if one didn't know in advance that
it really happened, some of the events in this film might be hard to
swallow.
   The setting is Garfield High, a school in poor and heavily
Hispanic East Los Angeles on the brink of losing its academic
accreditation. Jaime Escalante (Edward James Olmos) shows up one day
as the new computer science teacher. He is told the computers never
arrived and is shunted off to teach basic math.
   Undaunted, Escalante walks into the classroom and announces to
the unruly and apathetic students: ``Knowing math will only get you
a job at a taco stand. I will teach you algebra.'' And so he does.
Cajoling, badgering, bullying, humoring, Escalante gives these
11th-graders, many of whom don't even know their multiplication
tables, a reason to try harder.
   And harder. And harder. Because as soon as he teaches them
algebra, Escalante decides he wants to teach them calculus in their
senior year. With calculus, he tells his incredulous colleagues,
they will be able to take the Advanced Math Placement Test and gain
college credit. It's a ticket to scholarships, to a world heretofore
unattainable to these barrio kids.
   The 18 students take the rigorous course and pass the Advanced
Placement Test with flying colors. And here's where the movie gets
really interesting _ the Educational Testing Service decides that
the scores are so high that the students must have cheated, and
invalidates them. As Escalante says, the world that the students
have worked so hard to become a part of turns out to be not worthy
of them. The students decide to take the test again _ to stand and
deliver.
   Olmos gives a riveting performance as the dogged Escalante, a
mumbling, funny, believably rumpled teacher. Kudos to the casting
directors who chose the balding, acne-scarred Olmos over a flashier
screen-idol type. Of the students, the only actor with name
recognition is ``La Bamba'' star Lou Diamond Phillips, who plays a
hood afraid to look too brainy.
   The film was directed by Ramon Menendez, who co-wrote the
screenplay with producer Tom Musca. Although simplistic at times,
``Stand and Deliver'' should be heralded for letting the story line
stand and deliver and not succumb to schmaltz.
   _ By Geneva Collins, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Vampire at Midnight'' (Key Video; VHS-Beta, $79.98; Rated R)
   
   Want a GREAT idea for a STUPID movie?
   Take Svengali and Trilby, right? And make him a VAMPIRE SERIAL
KILLER and make her a, um, let's see ... make her a, um, this,
REALLY BUILT CONCERT PIANIST, that's it! With a mental block, right?
   Only there's this WISE-CRACKING REBEL COP, you know, with a crush
on her, who like WASTES a couple of nasty armed robbers in the first
scene ... KABLOOIE! ... you know, to establish his character. So a
bunch of people get SLASHED and STABBED and OTHERWISE WASTED and
BLOOD-SUCKED, you know, and PLUS, get this, there's a couple of
naughty scenes with bare breasts to like set up this ENORMOUS
PSYCHOLOGICAL TENSION, right? And then the Svengali guy goes to make
her his topless bride and the cop gets bushwhacked but in like, the
next-to next-to last scene ... KABLOOIE!!!
   For the record, this sociopathic yawn stars the wooden Jason
Williams, an actor. It's from an idea by Jason Williams, and the
screenplay is co-written by Jason Williams. It was directed by
Gregory McClatchey. And, oh, yeah, it's close-captioned for
hearing-impaired viewers.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Bad Dreams'' (CBS-Fox Video; VHS-Beta, $89.98; Rated R)
   
   ``Bad Dreams'' is a chilling horror tale for grownups, starring
Jennifer Rubin as Cynthia, sole survivor of a Jonestown-like mass
immolation. When she awakens from a 13-year coma, the ghost of
messianic cult leader Harris (Richard Lynch) wants her back. He
calls to her; she can't refuse.
   Question if you must the logic of easing her into the 1980s by
feeding her psychotropic drugs and locking her in a psychiatric
clinic with a bunch of emotionally disturbed people _ but hey, this
is the '80s, right?
   Director Andrew Fleming (who co-wrote with Steven de Souza) has a
great cast, including Susan Ruttan (``L.A. Law'') as a bitter
neurotic and Dean Cameron, whose glib, mellow, self-destructive
LA-style psycho is worth the price of the rental. Special honors to
Michele Burke's gory makeup.
   Alexandr Gruszynski's brilliant cinematography narrative neatly
wanders the hallucinary borderline of fantasy and reality as one by
one Cynthia's fellow patients die off. Is Harris killing them?
   ``Bad Dreams'' takes a great premise and fulfills its
possibilities. Its splash and spatter, while minimal, would be too
much for the squeamish. Still, this movie proves again that
humanity's ideas are still the scariest thing about it.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Call Me'' (Vestron Video; VHS, $79.98; Rated R)
   
   Anna works for a downtown newspaper similar to the Village Voice.
She lives in an expansive loft in Brooklyn where she profiled a
sleazy neighborhood gin mill called the Polish Bar.
   One night she gets an obscene phone call from a man she presumes
to be her wimpy, narcissistic boyfriend who's as sexy and sensual as
sunbaked cement. He breathily asks her to meet him at the Polish
Bar, in sexy heels, leather skirt sans undies. Idiot that she is,
she goes.
   Needless to say, it was not Mr. Wonderful. And once this idiot
woman calls and discovers her boyfriend home and in bed she rushes
to the ladies room instead of rushing home. There she is witness to
the brutal slaying of a transvestite by a vicious crooked cop.
   From here on the movie adapts a lackluster thriller mode with a
stop or two at erotica. Of special note to citrus fans: Anna does
curious things with an orange.
   Patricia Charbonneau, who gave a nice off-beat performance as the
lesbian in ``Desert Hearts,'' is rather limp here but that probably
has more to do with the script by Karen Kay and Sollace Mitchell,
who also directed. It's a good idea that doesn't have enough iron to
give it that harder edge.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
