<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   12-05 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv00,0738</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Every Dog Has His Day'' (IRS) _ Let's Active
   
   We promise, Mitch. If you go back to doing what you do best,
we'll never use the word ``jangly'' in a Let's Active review again.
   Much to Mitch Easter's chagrin, his band has always been lumped
with the ``jangly guitar'' groups that followed in the wake of
underground faves R.E.M. Easter, who produced R.E.M.'s first few
albums, has tried to carve an identity for his own band since its
bright, tuneful debut in 1983.
   Unfortunately, he's done it lately by turning Let's Active into
Lead Active. The self-conscious effort at hardening the band's sound
turns the promising ``Every Dog Has His Day'' into a disappointment.
   It's not that Let's Active can't rock out _ the title tune is
quite successful. It's just that Easter's high-pitched, nasal voice
and intriguing melodic sense tends to drown in a sea of metallic
shards. Most of the hard rockers here, such as the thrashing ``Ten
Layers Down'' or ``Too Bad,'' are simply uninteresting.
   The album's two best songs are comparatively quiet and performed
by guitarist Angie Carlson. ``Mr. Fool'' is intricately beautiful
and ``Forty Years'' shows a country flavor by this North Carolina
band.
   Easter seems intent on erasing an image problem in his mind and
he's succeeded.
   But at what cost?
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Pattern Disruptive'' (Epic) _ The Dickey Betts Band
   
   ``Pattern Disruptive'' features the first new music from former
Allman Brothers guitarist Dickey Betts since 1981. It's remarkable,
then, that the record contains not one fresh idea. Betts clings to
the 1970s Southern rock formula with a passion that, alas, is
missing from his singing and playing.
   The one cut that makes ``Pattern Disruptive'' worth hearing is
the instrumental ``Duane's Tune.'' The flashy guitar work and a
complex melody make for a quick six minutes of music. The tune is up
to the standards of such Allman Brothers instrumentals as
``Jessica'' and ``In Memory of Elizabeth Reed,'' which Betts also
wrote.
   Much of the rest of the album is pale blues. Betts and fellow
guitarist Warren Haynes offer a few lively breaks, usually in
tandem, but a lot of their riffs are as hackneyed as heavy metal.
And the singers and rhythm section sound as bored by the material as
the audience is sure to be.
   Next time, Betts should try an album of instrumentals. At least
that formula is a winner.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Buenos Noches From A Lonely Room'' (Reprise) _ Dwight Yoakam
   
   Yeah, I know. A lot of people don't seem to like Dwight Yoakam.
He has that nasal twang, he wears silly skintight pants, and his
self-proclaimed ``hillbilly music'' seems a mite contrived to some
people.
   Yoakam's first two albums may be partly to blame. ``Guitars,
Cadillacs, Etc.'' and ``Hillbilly Deluxe'' were promising _ after
all, no one had heard much like this lately _ but he still sounded
calculating as well as creative.
   But not here. No sir. ``Buenos Noches From a Lonely Room'' is a
genuinely brilliant record, 11 songs that sound like Dwight Yoakam
sat down and invented country music all by himself.
   He didn't, of course. Yoakam is well aware of where he comes
from, and he again pays homage to old masters. His anthemic
rendition of the Buck Owens classic, ``Streets of Bakersfield,'' a
duet with Owens himself, is the finest track on the album, a
rousing, full-throttle synopsis of what country music is all about.
   And the rest of ``Buenos Noches'' is fine as well, from the
funereal ``I Sang Dixie,'' one of seven Yoakam originals here, to
the semi-obscure Johnny Cash cover ``Home of the Blues'' and a
pretty duet with Lone Justice's Maria McKee on Roy Acuff's ``Send Me
the Pillow.''
   With this album, Dwight Yoakam has hit his stride, his singing
fluid and powerful, his sound his own. Forget the permanent scowl
and the silly pants. This is great stuff. This is for real.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
