<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Glasnost Gives America Celebrated Pianist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The day before Vladimir Horowitz performed in
Moscow two years ago, Philipp Viardo played the middle movement of a
Mozart sonata as a sound check for the TV cameras.
   After the concert, Vladimir and Natalia Viardo were introduced to
Horowitz as the parents of Philipp, who was then 9.
   But for everybody else, Vladimir Viardo is a symbol of
``glasnost.'' He's the first Soviet musician to receive permission
to live in the United States, to have his family join him and to
retain his Soviet citizenship.
   At 23, Viardo won the 1973 Van Cliburn International Piano
Competition in Fort Worth, the only Russian who has won it. He
toured, with much acclaim, in the United States and Mexico in 1974
and '75 then wasn't allowed to return until 1988. He now has been
given permission to live in Texas and pursue his career for two
years. Natalia Viardo, a former teacher, was to bring back sons
Philipp, 11, and Alexander, 4, this month.
   The Soviet concert bureau already had fixed about 25 appearances
for the 39-year-old Viardo. Ten U.S. solo recitals are scheduled for
April.
   ``The next year is completely free. I hope it will be full. I
want to compensate,'' he said.
   He said the desire to stay in the United States came in a flash.
``I was driving in a car with a friend in Texas. I thought, `I'm
missing a chance _ to play concerts, meet people, attend concerts.
Why should I?'''
   Viardo said the reason he can stay is ``glasnost.'' It also is
timing. When pianist Vladimir Feltsman received permission to leave
the Soviet Union last year, Viardo said Feltsman stayed two months,
applying for an open visa that would allow him to return. When that
was denied, he left and now lives with his wife and son in New York.
   ``He didn't want to leave forever. Russian nostalgia is a very
famous thing,'' Viardo said.
   After deciding he wanted to stay here, Viardo wrote a letter
explaining ``the practical and creative music reasons'' to the
Soviet ambassador in Washington. After ``three very nervous weeks,''
the Viardos were invited to talk with the Soviet consul general in
New York. Three weeks later he called them in again and said Moscow
had given the green light.
   He has ``seven bloods,'' including Jewish, gypsy, Russian and
Polish _ ``it's borscht,'' Viardo says, and his wife, whose brother
lives in Chicago, is Jewish.
   Viardo thought about leaving the Soviet Union forever during the
13 years he wasn't allowed to visit the United States. ``I couldn't.
I had a strong connection with my teachers and friends,'' he said.
   ``I was bitter. There was psychological torture. This is the age
when I had to establish myself; it was very important in my life.''
   He said that his touring to the West ``just stopped without any
explanation. I don't know what I've done. Maybe once somebody didn't
like my face.''
   Asked if he was treated fairly in those 13 years, he said, ``I
don't connect too much musical things to money. Certainly, they paid
me for concerts. If you consider salary for workers, I was paid
more. If you consider people who came abroad, it was much less.
   ``I was allowed to play big halls and with any orchestra. I
learned my repertoire from six concertos to 35.
   ``It is miraculous I was not broken down psychologically in those
years,'' he said. ``In the Russian language musician means executor.
Somebody else creates the music and we execute it. It puts in the
minds of officials we are not creative.''
   Viardo was allowed to give concerts only inside the Soviet Union
from 1976 to '80. For the next seven years, he could perform also in
Eastern Europe. In 1987 France, Germany and Denmark were added and
in 1988, America.
   Viardo hasn't yet decided what he'll play in his upcoming U.S.
concerts.
   ``As a grown-up artist I have a taste to play one name _ an
all-Chopin recital,'' he said. ``As a very young pianist for the
United States, I must show I can play different styles. I want to
show something like some Shostakovich which was never played in this
country.''
   His new position may put pressure on him, but Viardo said he's
ready.
   ``I don't make political noise to bring attention to me, because
I think it is not very good for a musician. I believe it should be
strictly music,'' he said.
   But he sees classical music as ``softening spirits in a political
world.''
   ``In 1974, after some concert, somebody came to me and said, `I
cannot shoot in such a world like you.' If I play well and soften
his heart, he cannot shoot at me. It really can work in a political
way.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec 16-18</NOTE>
