<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 16-18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Down to Earth With Hits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robbie Nevil held a up picture of himself, smiled
and said, ``Nice guy, real down to earth.''
   But Nevil, who made his mark on the music business in 1986 with
``C'est La Vie,'' seems ready to take off at any moment.
   ``There's an energy that comes across. I do love it,'' said
Nevil, who has released his second album, ``A Place Like This.''
   ``I like to do what I do for a living, how many people can say
that?''
   Nevil recently talked about his career in a recent interview at
offices of his record label, EMI. He is animated in conversation,
peppering his observations with renditions of songs, and doing an
inspired impersonation of his idol, Stevie Wonder.
   ``I don't take myself too seriously,'' he said. ``I don't think
I'm better or worse than anybody else, really. I like music and play
guitar. I've been very lucky and I'm making the music I want without
compromising on any level.
   ``I'm having a good time.''
   Nevil grew up in Los Angeles in the 1970s. Show business was in
his blood.
   ``My mom used to play classical piano. My father was a child
actor, he was Junior on the Dick Tracy radio show. My younger
brother's an actor.''
   So Nevil didn't take long to decide he wanted to be a musician.
   ``Maybe not when I was five, but by the time I was 11 I started
to play guitar,'' he said. ``From that point I started working at
it. I believe in getting good at what I do. A lot of people are
better than me, but that makes you push harder. I believe in setting
my goals high.''
   Nevil also began singing early. ``I remember singing in grade
school. I used to love singing loud, that feeling of power. This
principal heard me sing; she just picked me out and at graduation I
sang `Lavender Blue.'''
   He worked at a stationery store and then a delicatessen. But he
kept on writing songs and five years ago, composed ``C'est La Vie.''
He had no idea it would be such a major hit.
   ``I wasn't thinking that was the first single, but everybody
seemed to react to that. It's strong, immediate and fun. The sound
had its own distinct style.''
   Despite the success of ``C'est La Vie,'' he decided not to tour
in support of his self-titled debut album. ``I had to go to Japan
many times for promotion. You can't really do that if you're on the
road.''
   But now he's anxious to play live.
   ``I want to get a chance to get to know the fans,'' said Nevil,
who will start touring in March. ``This time, even though I'm more
than a name, I want to start small, just nightclub gigs.''
   Nevil admits to having some jitters about touring, but considers
that an asset.
   ``It's a healthy nervous about wanting to make it good, to have
the best players so I can have fun with it,'' he said. ``I think
people are going to see the show and get a sense of the band. George
Michael tends to be more of a solo artist and the band backs him
up.''
   Michael's name popped up frequently. Not only does Nevil admire
his singing, but Michael's producer, Chris Porter, worked
extensively on ``A Place Like This.''
   ``His attitude was so great. He didn't just say, `I do this.' If
I had to go into a studio and make a record with no effects, I'd
choose him. He doesn't need the effects that a lot of new cats need.
Their stuff is great but without processing they'd be lost.''
   Nevil confesses to a little processing himself, but says that ``A
Place Like This'' is a fairly simple production.
   ``I used punched-in vocals on the first album, but this album has
a lot less going on. I went for more performance,'' he said. ``I
loved the last album, but this album is a new face. Here I am, if
you like it. If you don't, well, this is what I do.''
   And what he does, sells. Nevil is well informed on how to write
hits, and talked about ``Back on Holiday,'' his new single.
   ``I think it was a good choice for a first single because it was
very sonically hard-hitting. It doesn't take long to get to the
point. It's not the kind of song you have to hear five times.''
   Does Nevil really think about writing hit singles?
   ``I think to say no would be a lie,'' he said. ``If I have a
groove and it's catchy, I'd be a fool to write something weird in
the middle. I like to think what makes it feel good. I think of it
as a single in wanting to make sure it's watertight.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec 16-18</NOTE>
