<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--SchizophreniaSaga Adv08   12-05 1028</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Schizophrenia Saga, Adv 08,1063</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Dec. 8, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Schizophrenia Wrecked Former Football Star's Life</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto
^By MALCOLM RITTER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lionel Aldridge, a 6-foot-4, 225-pound former
Green Bay Packer, was afraid to go home. He believed his wife was a
witch.
   Once part of NBC's television sportscasting team, Aldridge was
driven from job to job in city after city by imaginary voices. He
now sorts mail on the 3:30 p.m. to midnight shift in Milwaukee.
   Schizophrenia cost him a career, a marriage and ``just about
every person I had in my life at that time.''
   ``I figure,'' he said recently, ``it cost me everything.''
   Such are the stakes in schizophrenia.
   That's why research advances, such as the recent evidence that a
single gene may cause some cases, are more than just nifty bits of
science. They are another step in understanding a devastating
disease that strikes perhaps one in every 100 people at some point
in their lives.
   Schizophrenia usually begins with an apparent personality change
that may include social withdrawal, difficulty in communicating and
lethargy. Later, in its more active phase, it can make victims see
hallucinations and hear voices.
   They may feel controlled by invisible agents or believe their
thoughts are being broadcast to others. They may adopt new
identities.
   Nobody knows what causes the disease, a key question in finding
better treatments. Aldridge said the gene discovery is ``just the
tip of the iceberg'' toward finding a cause.
   Scientists have long suspected an inherited influence, and the
new study provided biological evidence for a gene in a few families.
But that gene has been shown not to be a factor in other families,
supporting the longstanding suspicion of multiple factors, perhaps
environmental and genetic.
   The voices and hallucinations are gone now for Aldridge, 47,
thanks to daily medication that keeps his illness at bay. ``I'm
enjoying relatively good health now,'' he said, but ``nothing is
guaranteed me'' for the future.
   For the Louisiana native, the schizophrenia battle began after
his athletic career. He played defensive end for the Packers and was
part of the most famous defensive line in National Football League
history when the team won three straight NFL championships and the
first two Super Bowls.
   He was traded to the San Diego Chargers in 1971 and retired from
pro ball after two seasons, taking up radio and TV sportscasting in
Milwaukee. NBC used him as an analyst for several seasons, including
its 1977 Super Bowl coverage.
   But the first signs of trouble had already appeared in early
1974. He had trouble concentrating. He couldn't get his work done on
time, and as a result his broadcasts often ran shorter than planned.
   ``I became very suspicious of people, especially the people I
worked with. The workplace became very difficult, a very unhappy
place.''
   Aldridge sought psychotherapy. But later that year, he began to
have bouts of psychosis, with imaginary voices and hallucinations.
   ``It was like suddenly discovering another world ... one that had
been here all along, one that was totally foreign and frightening.''
   While his behavior on the air appeared normal, his life at other
times was bizarre. He feared that his wife was a witch. He ran
barefoot through the snow in search of his therapist.
   Soon, he was hospitalized. ``I knew I needed help,'' he said. But
the medication he received for a couple years ``zombied me out so
bad I couldn't work.'' He had to work, so he gave up the medication.
   He continued to fight the voices that told him to quit his job
and leave town, and that nobody liked him. He battled the delusions
that the station was underground, that he had to hide from others
and watch out for himself.
   ``That was the existence I chose because I wouldn't take the
medication, because I figured I could take care of myself.''
   In 1981 he took a leave of absence from his job. ``I simply could
not do it any more,'' he said. His wife had already filed for
divorce.
   He left Milwaukee and traveled the country for as long as his
money held out, then he sold the car and continued by bus and train.
Within a few months of leaving town, he was living on the streets.
   But he found some respectable jobs: sports director at a
Louisiana radio station, prison counselor, football coach at a high
school and a college.
   ``I could keep myself straight during the interview,'' he
recalled, and when the employers found out who he was, they were
happy to hire him.
   But ``the voices ... wouldn't let me stay anyplace for any length
of time,'' he said. One by one, he left his jobs or was let go.
   In 1984 he found himself back in a Milwaukee hospital, thanks to
friends alarmed by his behavior. The doctors talked about medicine
again, and Aldridge figured he would give it a try. ``I had nothing
to stay straight for on the outside,'' so being ``zombied out''
would not be a problem, he reasoned.
   So it went for about three months. But then his doctor cut the
dose until Aldridge was taking just enough medication to keep the
voices and hallucinations away while avoiding the side effect.
   In late 1984 he left the hospital for a nursing home, then went
on to his own apartment. He started work at the post office in 1985,
and apart from a brief interruption, he has been there since. Now
Aldridge speaks publicly about schizophrenia, hoping to encourage
research. He was recently honored for his efforts by the National
Mental Health Association.
   Looking back at what schizophrenia cost him, he said, ``I'm
trying to find out what good it brought.
   ``It brought me the ability to travel around the country and talk
to people about it. It made me stronger in some ways ...
   ``It made me comfortable in situations where I was uncomfortable
before. I can't think of any situation where I can be intimidated,
because the worst has already happened. How much more can you lose
than everything?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 8</NOTE>
