<HEAD>Patients Sick Of Waiting For Doctor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leon Johnson had a bruised chest when he went
to see the doctor, but waiting two hours for treatment made him sick
to his stomach.
   ``I finally did get treated by the doctor, but I was so upset by
the time he was through I didn't care whether it hurt or not. I just
told him off,'' said Johnson, 74, of Oakhurst, Calif.
   ``He was too busy for me and I didn't need his services that bad.
It is particularly frustrating to some of us senior citizens who
don't have that much time left to wait.''
   In the face of increasing competition, some doctors and dentists
are becoming more concerned about time-conscious patients like
Johnson and are taking a cue from hard-driving executives on how to
manage time.
   ``People have become more sensitized to the consumer age and
realize that patients aren't going to wait. They're going to go
somewhere else,'' said Mark Samuels, a dentist who teaches practice
administration at the University of Pittsburgh's dental school.
   To determine how long patients wait, time management expert
Michael Fortino recently kept track of how much time 350 patients
spent in the waiting rooms of 75 general practitioners and 90
dentists in the Pittsburgh area.
   Fortino881; March 3, 1901; March 10, 1922; June 8, 1934; and June 28,
1966.
   A great quake like the one Jackson believes is possible would
rupture the fault well into Southern California, and could kill
14,000 people, hospitalize 55,000 and cause $17 billion damage,
according to a 1980 federal report.
</TEXT>
