<HEAD>Study Indicates Mothers Of Deformed Babies Cuddle Less</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mothers of babies with severe head and
facial deformities cuddle and smile at them less than those with
normal infants, but claim greater satisfaction from parenthood, a
new study suggests.
   The researchers made 18-minute videotapes of 10 mothers and their
4-month-old babies, five of whom were normal and five of whom
suffered from disorders producing serious deformities but no
neurological or mental deficiencies. The infants were matched in
terms of age, sex, birth order _ all first-born _ ethnic status, and
the mother's age, marital status and education.
   The sessions included 10 minutes of play, five minutes in which
the mothers tried to get their babies to vocalize, and three minutes
of babies face-to-face with their mothers, who had to imitate the
babies' expressions and actions.
   Mothers of deformed babies touched them a fifth as much as
mothers of normal infants, spent a third as much time demonstrating
toys to them, and smiled or laughed at them half has much, said R.
Christopher Barden, a University of Utah psychologist who directed
the study.
   In turn, the deformed infants touched their mothers and smiled or
laughed at them a fourth as much as the normal babies, cried more
than twice as much, and responded to their mother's voice a fifth as
much, Barden found.
   The mothers of deformed children, however, claimed greater
satisfaction with parenthood, suggesting they ``are either unwilling
to admit or unaware of the difficulties and stress imposed by their
deformed child,'' he said.
   Braden collaborated with Martin E. Ford of Stanford University
and Kenneth Salyer, Marcy Rogers-Salyer and Gayle Jensen of the
International Craniofacial Institute and the National Craniofacial
Foundation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Ferret Biologists Working On Canine Distemper Vaccine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife researchers are turning to
relatives of black-footed ferrets to develop a vaccine against
canine distemper, which led to the removal of the last known North
American ferrets from the wild.
   ``The problem that we have is that on canine distemper for dogs
and cats, a vet will give those animals a live vaccine,'' said Art
Reese, Wyoming Game and Fish Department chief of habitat and
technical services. ``You can't do that with a ferret. We tried that
with the first ones and it killed them.''
   Biologists using Siberian, Fitch and domestic ferrets have
succeeded only in developing a three-month inoculation, Reese said.
``In a lab setting that would be all right, but in the wild it isn't
worth a darn.''
   Since the ferrets were taken from their colony in 1985,
researchers have bred 58 in captivity. Six kits went in October to
the National Zoo and eight go to the Henry Doorley Zoo in Omaha,
Neb., this month for breeding.
   Using five breeding facilities around the country to bolster the
genetic makeup of breeding populations, Reese said, experts hope by
fiscal 1991 to have 50 ferrets, enough to return some to the high
plains desert around Meeteetse. The next year they hope to begin
reintroduction in other states, including Montana, Colorado, Idaho,
Utah and Nebraska.
   The department is building prairie dog towns that will be used to
train the laboratory-bred ferrets, Reese said. ``The ferrets will
essentially be trained in prairie dog towns to hunt prairie dogs and
interact similarly to an environment in which they're going to be
placed.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Scientists Concerned Over Vole Population in Tundra</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEDERLAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest population of voles in 30
years is playing havoc with the fragile Rocky Mountain tundra as the
thumb-sized rodents chew their way through grass and leave areas
open to erosion.
   They have altered the high-country growth as profoundly as fire
changed Yellowstone, scientists say. ``It's just far greater than
anything we have ever guessed at,'' said University of Colorado
researcher Norm French.
   There may be 25 times more voles this year than at the low point
of their 30-year population cycle, said researcher Jim Halfpenny.
Their kin, the Arctic lemmings, are famous for extreme population
fluctuations.
   ``It could make major changes not only in vegetation but changes
in animal communities up there. And when you consider this is Front
Range-wide, it could be a major event in a significant part of the
Rocky Mountains,'' French said.
   Outbreaks have been found in Montana and Wyoming, and Denver-area
residents have reported vole-chewed lawns. The vole explosion could
have a serious impact on the food supply of the pica, another small
tundra rodent, he said.
   But Halfpenny doesn't see the chewed terrain as damaged. ``The
tundra you see now is already a product of voles,'' he said. ``We've
been looking at the picture for ages, and this year, we're learning
how the picture was made.''
   The National Science Foundation has funded a study of the voles.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 8</NOTE>
