<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC-Production     12-05 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC-Production,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Hit Production High in November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC's daily production hit almost 23
million barrels in November, when cartel members were debating how
to cut output, the weekly Middle East Economic Survey reported
Monday.
   The agreement in Vienna in late November sets production for the
13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries at 18.5
million barrels per day starting January 1.
   The economic newsletter said the November daily production hit a
new peak of 22.98 million barrels and that projected December output
figures are pegged even higher. Actual production could drop as
members cut back, the weekly said.
   The new agreement sets a quota parity for Iran and Iraq at 2.64
million barrels per day. Iraq rejected its quota under the previous
1986 agreement, saying it needed to finance its war against Iran.
   Other members started ignoring their quotas, leading to an oil
glut that saw prices drop below $13 a barrel. OPEC is looking for a
benchmark price of $18 per barrel.
</TEXT>
