<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-HitProducts     12-05 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Hit Products,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Luxury Products Suit Japan's Affluence, Changing Habits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most popular products this year for the
increasingly affluent Japanese have been resort condominiums, bidets
and high-tech appliances, says a study by Japan's leading ad firm.
   ``Demand for safe and prosperous living is becoming stronger.
Enjoyable meals, health and peace of mind are all required elements
for creating a rich life,'' according to ``Hit Products and Consumer
Trends for 1988,'' an annual study on market trends released
recently by Dentsu Inc.
   Long accustomed to living in sparsely furnished, unheated rooms,
the Japanese are rearranging their homes and ``starting to live
according to individual tastes,'' the study says.
   The most remarkable trend is a proliferation of new homes and
expensive household products. Rental dwellers have given up on
buying homes in urban centers and are instead investing in resort
condominiums outside the city, where they can spend their weekends
in spacious comfort, the report says.
   Over 10,000 resort condos have been supplied to
``leisure-oriented'' Japanese in 1988, it says.
   Imported furniture to fill those homes is another hit. The
Japanese spent about $829.7 million on high quality European
furniture in the first nine months of the year, according to the
report.
   Cordless irons, multi-functional telephones and fully automatic
washing machines are popular time-savers, Dentsu says. It estimates
that 40 percent of the 4.3 million washing machines sold this year
will be automatic rinse and spin washers.
   Phones with answering-phone and other devices will account for
about half of the 6.9 million telephones sold this year, due in part
to a 30 percent price reduction in the past two years, the report
says.
   Japanese are turning to these time and labor-saving products, as
well as housecleaning services, to enhance their leisure time. By
1995, housecleaning services will become a $2.48 billion market, the
report says.
   Toilets with warm-water bidets and heated seats are another hit
this year, Dentsu says.
   Japanese are also pampering themselves with imported tableware,
fresh foods and chocolates to fulfill desires for
``self-realization,'' the report said.
   ``They seek satisfaction in mind and spirit through the pursuit
of luxury in life. The strong yen also allows them to step into what
had been a `dream world' in the past,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
