<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices opened higher on Wall Street today, led by
buying in blue chip issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 7.12 to
2,099.40 as of 10 a.m. EST.
   Advancing issues led decliners by a margin of about 13-to-9, with
517 stocks rising, 358 falling and 514 unchanged in early New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled a light 18.29 million shares
after the first 30 minutes of trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks rose 0.30 to
153.32. The American Stock Exchange's market value index moved up
0.26 to 295.53.
   Buying in blue chip issues carried the market higher, said Jack
Baker, head of block trading with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``The market looks like it wants to do better,'' Baker said,
although he said Wall Street still expected the Federal Reserve
Board to raise its discount rate to counter inflationary pressures.
   Concerns about rising interest rates have weighed on the market
recently.
   There was no specific news to affect trading today, but the
market had ``a little better tone,'' Baker said.
   Early gainers included IBM, up | to 119~, Texaco, up | to 47|,
and UAL, up 1 to 108}.
   Among decliners, Occidental Petroleum was off [ at 25~, and
Upjohn slipped | to 27~.
   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 9.60 to
2,092.28, but still emerged from the week with a 17.60-point gain.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by about 4-to-3 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 822 issues falling,
616 rising and 504 unchanged.
   Volume totaled a sluggish 124.61 million shares, down from 129.38
million the previous session.
