<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Pillsbury     12-05 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pillsbury,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Extends Pillsbury Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BARBARA DEWEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC on Monday extended for
the sixth time its $60-a-share takeover bid for Pillsbury Co., and
said about 88 percent of Pillsbury's outstanding shares have been
tendered.
   The British conglomerate said its $5.23 billion offer now will
expire at midnight Friday EST, unless extended.
   Grand Met's previous offer expired at midnight last Friday, at
which time 75,446,595 shares of Pillsbury common stock had been
tendered, the company said. When Grand Met made a previous extension
on Nov. 28, it said that 85 percent of the food and restaurant
company's common stock had been tendered as Nov. 25.
   Pillsbury spokesman Johnny Thompson said Monday he had no comment
on the latest Grand Met extension. ``It's just another one,'' he
said.
   Last week, Pillsbury Chairman Philip L. Smith sent a letter to
Grand Met Chairman Allen Sheppard saying the offer was ``financially
inadequate'' and, therefore, a meeting between the two would serve
no purpose.
   Grand Met, a liquor, gambling and specialty products
conglomerate, launched its unsolicited bid for the Minneapolis-based
Pillsbury on Oct. 4.
   Pillsbury's board of directors has rejected the offer as
inadequate and urged shareholders not to tender their stock.
   Pillsbury had planned to spin off its Burger King subsidiary, but
delayed the move at the request of a Delaware court that is hearing
Grand Met's challenge of the plan.
   Grand Met also is challenging Pillsbury's anti-takeover ``poison
pill'' defense, which makes hostile takeovers prohibitively
expensive.
</TEXT>
