<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0295</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices rose sharply on Wall Street today as stock
traders apparently shrugged off worries about rising interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 22.76 to
2,115.04 as of 11 a.m. EST.
   Advancing issues led decliners by a margin of about 2-to-1, with
758 stocks rising, 394 falling and 534 unchanged on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 43.42 million shares at
mid-morning.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks rose 1.18 to
154.20. The American Stock Exchange's market value index moved up
0.65 to 295.94.
   ``The market looks like it wants to do better,'' said Jack Baker,
head of block trading with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Analysts said Wall Street still expected the Federal Reserve
Board to raise its discount rate to cool down the economy and
counter inflationary pressures.
   However, even with the specter of rising interest rates, the
market appeared to be buoyed by its own resilience, said Michael
Metz, an analyst with Oppenheimer & Co.
   Stock prices slipped on Friday after the Labor Department's
employment report indicated the economy continued to surge, but did
not fall as much as market watchers had feared.
   ``Anyone had to be impressed _ all that bad news, but the market
didn't give much ground,'' said Metz.
   A stable bond market and improved dollar lent support to Wall
Street today, Metz said.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE was British Steel,
which was unchanged at 11|.
   Big gainers included IBM, up 1{ to 120}, Ford Motor, up 1 to 52},
and Digital Equipment, up 1[ to 96].
