<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher, Turn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade following a selloff in
the soybean market.
   Analysts said Iowa Grain Co., a large speculative brokerage firm,
sold a large amount of soybean contracts in the first 15 minutes of
the session. The soybean market had opened higher on reports that
little rain fell over the weekend in the major soybean-growing
regions of South America.
   Grain prices also turned mixed early in the session despite a
strong lineup of countries, including South Korea, Morocco and the
Philippines, seeking to buy U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   ``There are a lot of export bonus wheat tenders in the offing but
in terms of the real giant business _ from China or the Soviet Union
_ it just hasn't materialized,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading wheat was 1 cent lower to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.18 a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to { cent higher with December at $2.58{ a bushel; oats were 1
cent lower to 1} cents higher with December at $1.96 a bushel;
soybeans were 1} cents lower to 1{ cents higher with January at
$7.67 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .20 cent lower with December at
71.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .32 cent lower
with January at 82.30 cents a pound; hogs were .07 cent lower to .15
cent higher with December at 40.30 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .22 cent to .40 cent lower with February at 45.10 cents
a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Friday while pork futures were
mixed.
