<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Heinz     12-05 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Heinz,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heinz Reports Increased Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H.J. Heinz Co. said Monday its profit rose 14.5
percent in the second quarter due in part to hefty sales for its
Weight Watchers food products.
   For the three-month period ended Oct. 26, Heinz' after-tax profit
totaled $109.9 million, or 83 cents a share, up from $96.05 million,
or 72 cents a share, in the year-ago period.
   The company's revenue rose 11.4 percent in the period to $1.42
billion from $1.28 billion in the second quarter of 1987.
   Heinz attributed its second-quarter growth to healthy sales of
its Weight Watchers food products and strong attendance at Weight
Watchers meetings. The company also said it was helped by strong
volume increases in sales of its tuna, foodservice ketchup and
frozen potatoes.
   For the first six months of its fiscal year, H.J. Heinz reported
a profit of $220 million, or $1.67 per share, on sales of $2.8
billion. That compares with a first-half 1987 profit of $193.2
million, or $1.45 a share, on sales of $2.52 billion.
