<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Deer     12-05 0128</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deer,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tuberculosis Threatens Deer Herds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities plan to kill about 5,000
deer to try to halt the spread of bovine tuberculosis in commerical
deer herds, it was reported Monday.
   Agriculture Minister Laurits Toernaes applied to the parliament's
finance committee for about $3.8 million to pay for the three-year
plan, according to state television.
   Most of the money will go to farmers as compensation for lost
stocks. The animals are slaughtered for meat sold in domestic and
foreign markets.
   About 25,000 to 30,000 head live in captivity in the country's
500 deer ranches. Herds on 12 ranches are suspected of being
infected with bovine tuberculosis.
   Farmers and milk producers expressed fears the disease might
spread to cattle, but no cases have been reported.
</TEXT>
