<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices rose sharply on Wall Street today as
investors, encouraged by the market's resilience in recent trading,
put aside their worries about rising interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks soared 31.12 to
2,123.40 as of 2 p.m. EST.
   Advancing issues led decliners by a margin of nearly 2-to-1, with
927 stocks rising, 490 falling and 505 unchanged on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 89.98 million shares at
mid-afternoon.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks rose 1.70 to
154.72. The American Stock Exchange's market value index moved up
1.38 to 296.65.
   Analysts said the market was boosted by its own ability to
rebound from negative news.
   ``We held together fairly well Friday despite the non-farm
payroll leap,'' said Alfred Goldman, a market analyst with A.G.
Edwards Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
   Stock prices slipped Friday after the Labor Department reported
463,000 new jobs _ known as the non-farm payroll _ were created last
month.
   The figures indicated the economy continued to thrive, but
although the report heightened fears that the Federal Reserve would
move interest rates higher, stock prices did not fall as much as
market watchers had feared.
   ``It seems people are being encouraged by the market's
invulnerability to bad news, said Michael Metz, an analyst with
Oppenheimer & Co.
   Goldman said investors who were expecting a year-end rally on
Wall Street might be doing some early shopping. However, he warned,
``Interest rates remain very high ... I think they will dampen any
rally attempt.''
   A stable bond market and improved dollar lent support to Wall
Street today, Metz said.
   In addition, Goldman said, strength in transportation issues was
spilling over to other stocks. UAL was up 1| to 109], and AMR rose 2
to 53~.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE was Occidental
Petroleum, off [ at 25~.
   Big gainers included IBM, up 1~ to 121[, Ford Motor, up 1 to 52},
and Digital Equipment, up 1 to 96\.
