<HEAD>Public Transport, Other Services Still Hit by Labor Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transit strike entered its fourth week Monday as
negotiations reopened with workers seeking higher wages while
commuters struggled through heavy rain.
   Two of the four regional express subway lines remained paralyzed
except for small stretches of the network.
   The transport authority said slightly more than half the
capital's bus fleet was on the street. Two subway lines were at a
standstill.
   Other subways offered service ranging from 64 percent to 85
percent of normal or were not affected at all.
   Traffic has jammed the Paris ring road and major highways into
the city as many commuters drive to work.
   Newspapers said the strike is costing $333 million a day.
Department store owners said business is down 30 percent as they
head into the Christmas season.
   Throughout autumn, nurses, postal employees, government office
workers and other public service staff have gone on strike for wages
higher than those called for in Premier Michel Rocard's policy of
economic rigor.
   Rocard aides told reporters they expect labor unrest in the
public sector to continue, even after the transit strike is settled.
   The top government official for the Ile de la France region,
which includes the Paris area, said 150,000 people are being
transported each day by private buses or the 365 army trucks orderedroadcast
said security forces dispersed about 1,500 people
in the Baku's Lenin Square Sunday night. The forces moved in after
the crowd failed to respond to appeals by the chairman of the city
council and a commandant to disperse.
   Demonstrations and meetings are banned under military law imposed
two weeks ago.
   ``Irresponsible elements among those who gathered tried to put up
resistance. The servicemen fulfilled the tasks that had been put to
them. No weapons were used,'' the broadcast said.
   Some members of the crowd were detained, Radio Moscow reported.
The broadcast did not say why the crowd had gathered or whether they
were demonstrating over the Nagorno-Karabakh issue.
   Lenin Square was closed for ``sanitary work'' following the
dispersal of the meeting, according to Baku radio.
   In Yerevan, a 10 p.m.-6 a.m. curfew imposed Nov. 24 was cut to 11
p.m.-5 a.m., the Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda reported.
More than 2,400 people were detained and 32 were arrested since it
was imposed, Pravda said.
</TEXT>
