<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Intelsat-Fraud     12-05 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Intelsat-Fraud,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INTELSAT Executive Sentenced for Role in Kickback Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top executive of INTELSAT was
sentenced Monday to 16 months to four years imprisonment for his
role in a $4.8 million kickback scheme involving construction of the
satellite consortium's headquarters.
   In imposing the sentence, U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell
said Jose L. Alegrett, former deputy director general of INTELSAT,
would receive credit for the five months he has been in custody
since his arrest in Aruba last summer.
   Gesell, noting the defendant's cooperation with a continuing
federal investigation of alleged corruption by former INTELSAT
executives, said he would recommend that Alegrett be paroled after
serving 11 months.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David F. Geneson told Gesell that since
his arrest as a fugitive last summer, Alegrett ``has cooperated with
the government in a very substantial manner.''
   Alegrett has not only aided the government's investigation of the
construction kickback scheme but was providing information of
``great value'' for a probe of ``two other areas,'' Geneson said.
   Geneson was referring to an investigation of allegations that
consultants hired by two communications satellite manufacturers,
Hughes Aircraft Co., and Ford Aerospace Corp., had paid kickbacks to
former INTELSAT officials.
   Defense attorney Alan Bayles told the court of a letter from
General Motors Corp., which owns Hughes Aircraft, citing Alegrett's
cooperation.
   Alegrett pleaded guilty Sept. 16 to interstate transportation of
money obtained by fraud in connection with the kickback scheme.
   As part of the plea, Alegrett paid INTELSAT $1.1 million in
restitution, according to a source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The case stemmed from a scheme by INTELSAT's director general,
Richard R. Colino, Alegrett and two businessmen to siphon $3.8
million to $4.8 million in kickbacks from construction contracts to
build the consortium's new world headquarters.
   INTELSAT, acronym for the International Telecommunications
Satellite Organization, provides a global communications network
with satellites that serve 114 member nations.
   Gesell told Alegrett that the sentence was intended to punish
rather than rehabilitate him. ``I think you are a man who comes from
a tradition of honor,'' Gesell said.
   But ``this was not a case of a simple mistake,'' Gesell said.
``This was a deliberately, continuing, conniving scheme carried out
with deceit.''
   Alegrett was arrested last July in Aruba, where he had traveled
from his native Venezuela to meet with a federal agent. Aruban
authorities agreed to arrest Alegrett on a U.S. warrant, which was
issued after lengthy plea negotiations with federal prosecutors had
been broken off.
   Colino is serving a six-year term for criminal fraud and
conspiracy. He has denied knowledge of kickbacks by Hughes or Ford
Aerospace.
   But the civil suit filed by INTELSAT againt Colino charges that
he and an associate arranged for Ford Aerospace to hire a Chilean
consulting firm to perform a study to forecast satellite demand.
   Of the $125,000 that the firm was to be paid, Colino arranged for
him and an associate to receive $100,000, according to the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
