<DOCNO> AP881205-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1834EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LilcoTrial     12-05 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lilco Trial,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Says Lilco Lied To PSC To Get Rate Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury found Monday that the Long Island
Lighting Co. and a former executive engaged in a pattern of lies to
obtain rate increases to help pay for its Shoreham nuclear power
plant.
   The verdict under the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations statute awards $22.8 million in damages to Suffolk
County and could make Lilco liable for $1.8 billion if the trial
judge certifies the suit a class action on behalf of all ratepayers.
   The utility, through its attorney Michael Lesch, immediately
issued a one-sentence statement that said the verdict was
``insupportable'' and that Lilco would seek to set it aside or
reverse it on appeal.
   The seven-member jury in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn found
that Lilco and a former president, Wilfred O. Uhl, violated the RICO
statute by lying to the Public Service Commission on three occasions
about the completion schedule of Shoreham in order to obtain rate
hikes.
   The verdict followed a two-month trial of the county's civil
racketeering suit against Lilco. The jury awarded $7.6 million in
damages to the county for what it overpaid on utility costs because
of fraudulently obtained rate increases in 1978 and 1984.
   That amount is tripled to $22.8 million under the federal
racketeering statue. The county had sought up to $72 million in
damages.
   The jury rejected the county's charges that Lilco deceived the
PSC in obtaining other rate increases in 1975, 1976, 1979 and 1981.
   It also found no violations by three other former Lilco officials
who were defendants.
   ``I think the jury spoke loud and clearly that Lilco had been
engaging in a pattern of fraud for a decade,'' said Kenneth
McCallion, who was the county's lead attorney during the two-month
trial.
   ``A verdict in this case has to send a message to all parties
that the fraud engaged in by Lilco has to be a major factor for
those who are considering the fate of Shoreham,'' McCallion said.
   Last week in Albany, the state legislature let pass by a deadline
for approving a plan that would keep Shoreham closed and give Lilco
5 percent annual rate hikes over the next decade.
   Lilco has said that while the plan could be revived, it would
proceed toward licensing the plant.
   Suffolk County Executive Patrick Halpin called the verdict ``a
great victory for the county and Suffolk's ratepayers.''
   According to testimony at the trial, the Shoreham plant, which is
located 55 miles east of Manhattan, had originally been scheduled to
be in operation in 1978 at a cost of $77 million. Construction was
completed in 1985, but the plant was never opened because of public
opposition.
   The county alleged that Lilco spent $8 billion in the
construction of Shoreham, but Lilco says the plant cost $5.3 billion.
   Originally, the county had wanted to make the suit a class action
on behalf of all Lilco customers, but U.S. District Judge Jack B.
Weinstein limited the scope of the suit before the trial started.
   After the verdict, Weinstein said he would now accept a motion
asking him to certify the class and indicated that if he granted the
request, Lilco could be liable for up to $1.8 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881205-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1835EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SocialSecurity     12-05 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Social Security,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Hit Now-Dead Plan To Limit Social Security Appeals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats called Social Security officials on
the carpet Monday over draft regulations to limit the rights of
people trying to obtain benefits, even though Commissioner Dorcas
Hardy already killed the controversial proposal.
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.,
said the plan would have violated Congress' intent that the benefits
hearings process be ``non-adversarial and simple enough for an
individual claimant to navigate without legal representation.''
   He said that based on past actions, he feared what steps the
agency might take in the future.
   Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., said: ``The administration does not have
a track record on Social Security that I feel comfortable with.
There's suspicion.''
   Downey, acting chairman of the public assistance subcommittee,
cited an instance last Christmas when he said the Reagan
administration ``tried to count as income the blankets and food that
poor (Social Security) recipients might get from local charities.''
   Hardy over the weekend rejected the draft staff regulations, one
of which would have required claimants to submit all evidence in a
proceeding at least seven days before it began.
   Deputy Commissioner Louis Enoff assured the Ways and Means
Committee on Monday that Hardy's decision was final.
   ``They've been tossed,'' Enoff said of the regulations. ``They
will not be considered or started (anew). They will not officially
be brought forward in the Social Security Administration.''
   Most of the 300,000 people who request hearings each year before
administrative law judges are seeking disability benefits, and most
who appeal denials eventually win. An appeal through the
administrative process to the court level takes an average of nearly
two years.
   Under questioning by Downey, Enoff denied that the draft
regulations were developed to cut the number of appeals. ``Our
primary concern is getting the correct decision at the earliest
point in the process,'' he said. He said 110 administrative law
judges were added last year, bringing the total to more than 700.
   Republicans complained bitterly that the hearing was unnecessary
in light of Hardy's action and inconvenient since it was held while
GOP members met to elect leaders for the 101st Congress.
   ``I must conclude that the majority is unwilling to let the media
down,'' said Rep. Hal Daub, R-Neb. He said even without Hardy's
action, given the glacial pace of regulatory change, the hearing
would have been premature.
   Downey defended the hearing, saying Congress is ``extraordinarily
sensitive'' to any Social Security changes and ``brooks no effort''
to instill among the elderly and disabled fear of their own
government.
   ``The people who did these draft regulations were not out to
intimidate or hurt anybody,'' Enoff replied. He said one reason for
proposing the advance evidence requirement is that some lawyers
introduce evidence at the end of a proceeding simply to prolong it,
because they make more money that way.
   He said the system remains targeted for change and he challenged
committee members to ask other witnesses, most of them from senior
advocacy groups, ``if they would deny that the hearings and appeals
process sorely needs improving.''
   In testimony to the committee, many groups agreed the process
needed to be improved. The most common suggestion was that the
Social Security Administration hire more people in order to better
determine the validity of disability claims when they are first made.
   And several witnesses said administrative law judges need more
independence from the Social Security bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
