<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0211</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose sharply today as investors put
aside concerns about interest rates.
   Analysts said the market was boosted by its own ability to
rebound from negative news.
   ``We held together fairly well Friday despite the non-farm
payroll leap,'' said Alfred Goldman, a market analyst with A.G.
Edwards Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
   Stock prices slipped Friday after the Labor Department reported
463,000 new jobs _ known as the non-farm payroll _ were created last
month.
   The figures indicated the economy continued to thrive, but
although the report heightened fears that the Federal Reserve would
move interest rates higher, stock prices did not fall as much Friday
as market watchers had feared.
   ``It seems people are being encouraged by the market's
invulnerability to bad news, said Michael Metz, an analyst with
Oppenheimer & Co., said of today's trading.
   Goldman said investors who were expecting a year-end rally on
Wall Street might be doing some early shopping. However, he warned,
``Interest rates remain very high ... I think they will dampen any
rally attempt.''
   A stable bond market and improved dollar lent support to Wall
Street, analysts said.
