<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BritishSteel     12-05 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-British Steel,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Instant Profit on First Day Of Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Steel PLC's shares rose in active trading
Monday as they began changing hands, but dealers said the gain was
disappointing because it was not big enough to bring instant profit
to small investors, as past privatizations have.
   The shares immediately rose to 62.25 pence, or $1.16, up 2.25
pence, or 4 cents, from the partly paid offering price, soon after
trading began at 2:30 p.m. on London's Stock Exchange. They finished
the session at that early level.
   Volume amounted to 261 million shares.
   The British Steel shares were priced at 125 pence, or $2.34 each,
valuing the entire company at 2.5 billion pounds, or the equivalent
of $4.7 billion. But the shares were offered on an installment basis
with an initial payment of 60 pence, or $1.12 a share.
   The offering was more than three times oversubscribed, the
government said. Private investors made around 650,000 applications
for more than 1.5 billion shares, compared with the 452 million
shares on offer to them.
   The government decided to allocate 842 million shares to the
private investors, or 42 percent of the total 2 billion shares, by
cutting the size of the portions which had been provisionally placed
with British and overseas institutions.
   Market watchers described the first day of trading in British
Steel as ``anti-climactic'' and ``much ado about nothing.''
   Dealers said the premium was disappointing because it was too
small to give private investors any profit by selling their shares
on the first day of dealing, after taking dealing costs into account.
   Trading activity was mainly due to buying and selling among
institutions, with some of the issue's British sub-underwriters
seeking to reduce their holdings somewhat on the first day of
dealing, dealers said.
   ``At the moment we are seeing selling from those U.K.
institutions that were happy to underwrite the issue but aren't
long-term holders, and buying from the institutions that are more
optimistic,'' one senior dealer said.
   Dealers said some participants were discouraged by Monday's
overall fall in prices on the stock market.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed off 3.4
points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,761.6.
   Meanwhile, advisers to the government, the investment firm Samuel
Montagu and Co., said they were investigating around 2,000 of the
650,000 applications put in by private British investors for
suspected multiple applications. It's illegal to put in more than
one application for shares in Britian's privatizations.
</TEXT>
