<DOCNO> AP881205-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 1706EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SteelImports Bjt   12-05 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Imports, Bjt,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Importers Urge Modified Import Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel importers conceded Monday that they are
unlikely to win a repeal of import quotas and proposed ways to make
the program more palatable.
   ``We're trying to be realistic,'' said John Griffin, newly
elected president of the American Institute for Imported Steel.
   The New York-based importers association, the Texas Association
of Steel Importers and the West Coast Metal Importers Association
said President-elect George Bush should, among other things, soften
the strict product-by-product quotas that created shortages over the
last two years.
   The more than 30 product quotas prevented foreign producers from
shipping additional steel plate for factory floors and bridge decks,
for example, when U.S. producers could not meet demand.
   ``We've seen projects where they leave holes in the deck because
you can't get plate,'' said Griffin, who is also president of the
Houston steel trader Maurice Pincoffs Co.
   The U.S. quotas, negotiated by the Reagan administration starting
in 1984, were designed to limit foreign steel to roughly 20 percent
of the U.S. market.
   Domestic steel companies contend they still need protection as
the U.S. industry restructures, but steel users are urging the
quotas be dropped.
   Known as ``voluntary restraint agreements,'' the quotas ``ignore
the interests of consumers of steel-intensive produces (and) brought
about market shortages and price increases, reduced net
manufacturing employment in the United States and diminished the
potential for the export of steel-intenive products,'' the importers
association said in a statement.
   American steelmakers deny any connection between the quotas and
steel price increases, and they deny there have been any true
shortages. Only a renewal of the quotas will check predatory trade
practices and allow time to continue the turnaround that has brought
the domestic industry profits of $3.25 billion in the last seven
quarters after losses of $12 billion over the preceding five years,
they say.
   The importers said that barring a change of heart by Bush, they
prefer the quota plan to the unfair trade complaints that U.S.
producers say they will file if the current five-year program is
allowed to expire on schedule in September. Bush has said he favors
continuing the quota system.
   ``The alternative was to either have this type of organized,
orderly market or to have a series of harrassments such as the ones
that led to this quota, ... the counterveiling duty case or the
dumping case, and they are poison,'' said Fred Lamesch, a past
president of the importers association.
   Counterveiling duties can be levied against imports shown to have
damaged U.S. competitors as a result of unfair pricing. Dumping is
the practice of exporting goods at prices set artificially below the
cost of production.
   U.S. producers say both tactics aggravated their 1982-86
recession, during which they were forced to slash employment by
roughly half to today's 170,000 workers.
   Lamesch said none of the top steel-exporting nations have granted
any steel production subsidies for several years. The only subsidies
still available to European producers are those that help pay
employee benefits when plants close, he said.
   ``The French say America has the biggest subsidy by being able to
give pink slips to workers on Friday and say `Don't come back on
Monday,''' said Hans Mueller, an economist professor at Middle
Tennessee State University who is a cosultant for the importers
group.
   ``Most of the subsidies are optical illusions,'' Mueller said.
``We see subsidies in anything different than what we do.''
   With the Bush inauguration still six weeks away and with nine
months remaining before the quotas are scheduled to expire, American
steel users already are complaining that the domestic steel industry
seems too prosperous to be demanding further trade protection.
   ``Our guys would kill to be making the profit on sales that
they're making right now,'' Greg Estell, spokesman for the 1,000
member companies of the Precision Metal Forming Association, said
Friday.
   The Cleveland-based organization represents 80,000 of the
approximately 350,000 Americans who bend, stamp and cut steel into
parts for vehicles, appliances and other products. That
steel-consuming niche alone has more than twice as many employees as
basic steelmaking.
   Others demanding changes or abandonment of the quotas include the
Steel Service Center Institute, the Forging Industry Association and
the heavy equipment manufacturers Caterpillar Inc. and Deere & Co.
</TEXT>
