<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pepperell     12-05 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepperell,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepperell Sweetens Retirement Plan For Hundreds Of Employees,
Blasts Farley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile giant West Point-Pepperell Inc. is
offering more than 800 employees early retirement in an effort to
trim down the company, which has grown through the acquisition of
two competitors.
   The company says the program is not connected to its efforts to
thwart a $1.4 billion takeover attempt by Chicago-based Farley Inc.
   A company spokesman said the offer would affect between 800 and
900 salaried Pepperell employees, including those who came from
Cluett, Peabody & Co., acquired in 1986, and from J.P. Stevens & Co.
Inc., acquired this year.
   The spokesman said the plan, which offers enhanced retirement
benefits to employees aged 55 with 10 years service, is not
connected with the Farley bid.
   The offer is being made ``in the normal course of business,'' the
spokesman said. ``It's something that had been looked at for quite a
while when they were looking at the need to cut back staff.''
   Pepperell, based in West Point, Ga., has 41,000 employees and is
the nation's largest publicly held textile company.
   Farley, whose privately held conglomerate includes the maker of
Fruit of the Loom underwear, is engaged in a month-long battle with
Pepperell management to buy up the company for $48 per share tender
offer.
   The latest volley in the battle also came Monday as Farley took
out full-page advertisements in several newspapers including The
Atlanta Journal, The Atlanta Constitution and The New York Times
claiming ``management's most important objective is to entrench
management, not to do what's right for the owners of more than 99
percent of West Point-Pepperell shares not owned by management.''
   The advertisement attacked Pepperell's handling of Cluett and
Stevens, claiming both companies had deteriorated since their
acquisition by Pepperell.
   The ad was in reply to a similar effort two weeks ago by
Pepperell saying in part, ``Why turn a healthy, thriving, globally
competitive company like West Point-Pepperell into another
money-losing Farley enterprise?''
   Pepperell has failed in several court attempts to block the
Farley offer, claiming it violates federal regulations because it
involves too much debt and not enough equity.
   Farley owns 9.8 percent of Pepperell's outstanding shares, and
the company said last week it had been tendered enough stock to push
its stake to more than 49 percent of the company. The offer, which
is contingent on the overturning of Pepperell's shareholder rights
provisions, expires at midnight Wednesday.
   A federal appeals court has set a January hearing to decide on
the challenge to the shareholder rights.
   Farley also has asked for a special shareholder meeting to vote
on the offer.
</TEXT>
