<1ST_LINE>r f AM-StarWarsContract     12-05 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Star Wars Contract,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martin Marietta Group Wins Major Star Wars Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon awarded a contractor team led by
the Martin Marietta Corp. a $347 million contract on Monday in a key
step toward conducting ``Star Wars'' laser experiments in space.
   The 30-month contract represents a major installment in what is
to be a $1.5 billion program code-named ``Zenith Star.''
   Martin Marietta's Denver Aerospace Division and its two
subcontractors have been told to proceed with the final design and
development work on a small laser and associated equipment that
could be boosted into space for experimental firing in 1994, the
Pentagon said in a statement.
   Zenith Star involves research aimed at proving the feasibility of
firing laser beams at orbiting mirrors, which in turn direct the
beam to moving targets.
   The Martin Marietta team was selected over two competitors in
October 1987 to produce a plan for Star Wars experiments that would
prove space-based laser weapons are feasible. The two subcontractors
are the Lockheed Missile and Space Co. and TRW Inc.
   The Star Wars program, known formally as the Strategic Defense
Initiative, is a research effort aimed at developing various exotic
weapons that could be used to automatically shoot down nuclear
ballistic missiles fired at the United States or its allies.
</TEXT>
