<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   12-05 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0632</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices advanced broadly Monday as
investors, responding to the market's resilience in recent sessions,
temporarily put aside their worries about rising interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 31.48 to
2,123.76.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 12-to-7 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
929 issues up, 540 down and 518 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 144.66 million shares,
down from 124.61 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
185.93 million shares.
   Analysts said there was no specific news to spark Monday's rally,
but that the market's oversold condition and recent performance were
reason enough for many investors to go on a shopping spree.
   ``They're looking for an excuse to get back in,'' said Hugh
Johnson, a market analyst at First Albany Corp. ``When it seems
oversold, when it seems like pessimism is lopsided, those who have
been in the business instinctively want to get back in.''
   ``They're looking for events that will serve as a catalyst to
move the market on the upside,'' he said.
   The market was boosted by its own ability to rebound from
negative news, in particular, the Labor Department's announcement
Friday that 463,000 new jobs were created in November, analysts said.
   The government's figures indicated the economy continues to surge
and they heightened fears that the Federal Reserve would raise its
discount rate to control the economy and inflation.
   But prices on Wall Street fell only moderately on Friday, and
that encouraged traders to enter the market Monday, said Alfred
Goldman, a market analyst with A.G. Edwards Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
   Goldman said investors who were expecting a year-end stock rally
might be doing some early shopping, but the specter of rising
interest rates has not vanished from Wall Street _ even if it was
pushed into the background Monday.
   ``Meanwhile, the major sword of Damocles hanging over the market
is the fact that interest rates remain very high,'' Goldman said.
   Four major companies announced plans Monday to offer their
shareholders a chance to exchange more than $5 billion in stock for
a new type of security that can be traded whole or broken into three
parts.
   The announcement was a catalyst for some of Monday's buying,
Johnson said.
   The stocks of the four companies finished higher. American
Express was up | to 27{, Dow Chemical rose 2 to 86[, Pfizer picked
up 1~ to close at 58, and Sara Lee, which was up ~ to 45].
   Transportation issues were among the big winners, and lent
strength to the rest of the market, Goldman said. UAL was up 1} to
109{, and AMR rose 2[ to 54.
   Other gainers included IBM, up 1| to 120~, General Motors, up 2[
to 85}, and Dupont, which rose 1] to 82\.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE was Occidental
Petroleum, which slipped [ to 25~.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market rose by $23.172 billion, or 0.86
percent, in value.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.46 to 154.48.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 3.76 to 316.92, and S&P's
500-stock composite index picked up 3.12 to close at 274.93.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
1.50 to 375.41.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
1.48 to 296.75.
