<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-05 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar generally strengthened late Monday but
fell against the British pound, which surged on London press
speculation that Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
wanted a more expensive currency.
   Gold prices slipped in New York after rising in Europe. Republic
Bank of New York quoted bullion at $428.05 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m.
EST, down from $430.50 at the same time Friday.
   Foreign exchange brokers said the dollar's upward move came late
in the day after it fell in European dealings, staying in a narrow
range all day. They described trading as extremely light, thereby
exaggerating the influence of what few buyers and sellers were
participating.
   ``There's really been very little activity,'' said David Jacques,
senior trader on the corporate desk at the New York branch of
Britain's Barclay's Bank. ``There were a couple of orders pushing it
up.''
   Traders said action was more exciting in the pound, based on what
they called British press speculation that the government was
willing to see that currency rise by about 5 percent in value.
   A more expensive pound theoretically would pressure Britain's
exporters and make them less willing to grant what the government
considers inflationary wage demands from workers, the press accounts
suggested. Traders interpreted this as a signal to buy pounds
aggressively.
   In London it cost $1.8690 to buy one pound, up from $1.8597 late
Friday. In New York the pound fetched $1.8683, up from $1.8655, and
at times was trading above $1.87, the highest level in months. The
pound's strength raised the prospect of a $1.90 exchange rate soon,
traders said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 121.53 Japanese yen, down from
121.64. Later in London the dollar traded lower at 121.25 yen, but
strengthened in New York to 121.56 yen, vs. 121.20 yen late Friday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York vs. rates late Friday,
included: 1.7260 West German marks, up from 1.7220; 1.4442 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4415; 1.1867 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1857;
5.8875 French francs, up from 5.8850; and 1,275.45 Italian lire, up
from 1,274.25.
   Other late-dollar rates in Europe vs. rates late Friday,
included: 1.7225 West German marks, down from 1.7315; 1.4420 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4598; 5.8800 French francs, down from 5.9200;
1.9425 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9490; 1,273.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,279.50; and 1.1851 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1869.
   Gold traders said bullion prices fell in New York and rose in
Europe largely because of internal market influences and not outside
news.
   The New York Commodity Exchange quoted gold for current delivery
at $429.30 a troy ounce, down $2.40 from Friday. In London gold rose
$3.25 an ounce to $428.75; in Zurich it rose $4.70 to $429; and in
Hong Kong it fell 86 cents to $429.94.
   Silver for current delivery traded at $6.163 a troy ounce, off
2.7 cents. In London silver traded at $6.14, up one cent.
</TEXT>
