<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Eggs     12-05 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Eggs,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Endorses Eggs, Supports Subordinate in Salmonella Scare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke on Monday urged
shoppers to ``carry on buying eggs'' despite 46 recent outbreaks of
salmonella.
   Through October, there have been 46 outbreaks of salmonella,
affecting 1,000 people in England and Wales, traced to eggs,
according to Clarke.
   ``We accept there is a health hazard which we are all tackling,''
Clarke said during an appearance at the House of Commons. ``The
average member of the public is not at risk at all.''
   However, Clarke also defended statements by Edwina Currie, a
junior minister who said most of the nation's egg production was
affected by salmonella.
   ``She was right to stress the concern we feel about eggs and draw
attention to the advice we have issued,'' Clarke said.
   The Ministry of Agriculture announced that producers had agreed
to a voluntary code which included buying chickens only from
licensed hatcheries, inspecting flocks regularly for salmonella,
discarding cracked eggs and keeping eggs refrigerated throughout the
distribution chain.
   Food poisoning from all sources affects 1.5 million persons a
year, the health ministry said.
   Egg producers were still furious over Mrs. Currie's statement in
a television interview on Saturday, and John Coles, chairman of the
British Egg Information Service, said the group was considering a
lawsuit against her.
   ``We have got an industry with a retail value of something like
1.5 billion pounds ($2.8 billion) and if we lose 25-30 percent of
that market the losses will be astronomical,'' Coles said.
   However, the British Broadcasting Corp. said on its midday
television news that major grocery chains reported only slight dips
in egg sales.
   Clarke's chief medical adviser, Sir Donald Acheson, told the BBC
that pregnant women, infants, the elderly and the sick should only
eat eggs which had been cooked until solid.
   For healthy adults, however, ``I think it is an acceptable risk _
it's a very small one _ or us to continue to enjoy our boiled egg
with a runny inside,'' Acheson said.
   The British eat 30 million eggs a day produced by 39 million
laying hens on 5,000 commercial farms.
   Eggs were taken off the menu on Monday for 1,000 patients at
Queens Medical Center in Nottingham, and they will stay off until
the local health authority decides otherwise, said Rosalind Channon,
the hospital's assistant manager Rosalind Channon.
   Nonetheless, an egg-swallowing contest was held as scheduled
Monday in Gloucester. The winner, John Thornton, 25, swallowed 36
hard-boiled eggs in 15 minutes at the Golden Hart pub.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
