<DOCNO> AP881205-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 2208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-FordAntiques     12-05 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ford Antiques,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buyers Flock To Sale At Country Home of Henry Ford II</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Antique dealers and collectors crowded into a
marquee beside an English country mansion on Monday and paid $2
million for paintings, furniture, rugs, silver and ornaments owned
by the late Henry Ford II.
   The antiques had furnished Turville Grange near Henley, 35 miles
west of London, which was the country retreat of the American
automaker and philanthropist on his visits to Britain.
   The house, in the Queen Anne style of the 18th century, was not
being sold. It was used by the British royal family earlier in this
century and was owned by Prince Radziwill and his wife Lee, sister
of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, before Ford bought it in the 1970s.
   The sale total was double the estimate by Sotheby's, which sold
the house contents on instructions from his executors. Henry Ford II
died in September 1987. He was the grandson of Henry Ford, the
Detroit motor company's founder.
   ``The sale attracted a lot of commercial buyers, but also people
interested in Ford's life and the house. It was a cross-section of
buyers, many of them private collectors,'' said Beth McHattie, a
Sotheby's publicist.
   There were gasps when a simple silver cigarette box, made in
Birmingham in 1947 and expected to fetch about $1,500, sold for
$41,140.
   The interior was inset with a panel enclosing grass from the
first sod cut in 1929 by Edsel Ford, the founder's son, on the site
of the Ford car plant at Dagenham in east London. The box was
presented to Henry Ford II when he visited Dagenham in 1948.
   ``The bidding was very competitive because of the box's
connotations,'' said Ms. McHattie.
   There were more gasps when a Victorian brass and leather
upholstered fire fender, estimated at $1,870, was sold for $19,500
to a London dealer.
   Early American furniture that Ford bought from New York dealer
Israel Sack was expected to return across the Atlantic.
   The best piece was a 1740 walnut chest of drawers from
Philadelphia, which made $21,600, while an 18th century maple
armchair from Rhode Island went for $15,900.
   Carpets fetched the top prices. A Bessarabian carpet went for
$154,275 and a Ziegler carpet for nearly $60,000, both to anonymous
buyers.
   Sotheby's said to its knowledge there was no one from the Ford
family at the sale.
</TEXT>
