<DOCNO> AP881205-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 2232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankingIndustry     12-05 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banking Industry,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Banking Association President Warns of Industry Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commercial banking industry easily
could become obsolete without serious legislative reform, the
president of the American Bankers Association warned Monday.
   ``The future isn't all that bright,'' said Thomas P. Rideout,
also vice chairman of the First Union National Bank of North
Carolina in Charlotte, at the Oregon Bankers Association's annual
winter conference.
   From 1977 to 1987, he said, banking's share of financial assets
held by financial institutions dropped from 37 percent to 29 percent.
   In the same period, large banks' share of credit extended to
nonfinancial corporations fell from 62 percent to 44 percent, he
said. Credit-market debt held by banks for the same period also
dropped, from 41 percent to 35 percent.
   Deposit growth among competitors during the period far outpaced
the 117 percent growth experienced by commercial banks, with savings
and loan deposits up 139 percent, life insurance reserves up 191
percent, liabilities and capital of securities brokers and dealers
up 1,042 percent, and money market mutual funds up 6,450 percent,
Rideout said.
   Technology has permitted easy entry into the financial services
business by institutions outside the traditional banking industry,
he said, and their services are expanding.
   ``Competitors are being allowed to engage in banking without
meeting the supervisory standards imposed on banks, or our same
strict capital requirements, which in fact are getting stricter as
we head toward 1992,'' Rideout said. ``Lax standards, of course, are
one of the main causes behind the FSLIC (Federal Savings & Loan
Insurance Corp.) crisis today.''
   Bank failures have risen, he said, from 42 in 1982 to 184 in 1987
and 175 through October of this year. The number of institutions
identified as ``problem banks'' has risen from 300 in 1982 to 1,575
in 1987 and 1,495 through May of this year.
   Rideout said association members should target legislators to
push for reforming antiquated banking laws _ particularly those
covering deposit insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
