<FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 2140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CalifInsurance     12-05 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Calif Insurance,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislators Introduce Bills Backing Proposition 103</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several state lawmakers introduced
bills Monday to shore up the voter-approved measure to cut insurance
rates that has been temporarily stayed by the state Supreme Court.
   Senate Insurance Committee Chairman Alan Robbins unveiled a
measure which he said would prevent insurers in the state from
profiting as a result of any attempts to evade Proposition 103. The
bill, SB103, threatens hefty financial fines for pullbacks from the
market.
   ``If what's happened with these companies (withdrawing from the
California market) is allowed to snowball, and if more companies
then stop writing policies, that is something we cannot do and
something we're not going to do,'' Robbins said.
   ``In other states, penalties have not stopped companies from
leaving a market, but they have discouraged new companies from
coming in and picking up the business that's left behind,'' said
Edward Levy, representing the Association of California Insurance
Companies.
   Senate Leader David Roberti, a Los Angeles Democrat, said he was
introducing a bill that would create an office in the state Justice
Department to represent consumers with insurance problems during
legal or administrative proceedings.
   And Sen. Cecil Green, a Norwalk Democrat, said he will introduce
a measure that would give the consumer advocate's office the power
to investigate and intervene on behalf of consumers when insurance
companies are engaging in unfair methods of competition or deceptive
practices.
   Lawmakers said the rush to introduce bills, or sign on as
co-authors of other legislators' measures, stems from their
eagerness to implement the California electorate's will, expressed
with the recent passage of Proposition 103.
   ``I think the vote of the people passing Proposition 103, despite
tens of millions of dollars being spent by the insurance industry to
defeat it, has placed a focus of public attention on the issue,''
Robbins said.
   But the Legislature may face an uphill battle as it attempts to
pass significant insurance-related legislation, something it has
been unable to do in recent years.
   Even if lawmakers are able to steer bills between the powerful
lobbies of two perennial foes, insurers and trial lawyers, and gain
two-thirds votes, the measures will still have to go to Republican
Gov. George Deukmejian, who opposed Proposition 103.
   After voters approved rate-cutting Proposition 103, several
insurers announced they were limiting or ending their auto insurance
business in California.
   The state Supreme Court then stayed the initiative while
considering its constitutionality and most of the companies said
they would suspend plans while awaiting the outcome.
   Insurers are challenging several provisions of the measure,
including those that would roll back most rates to 20 percent below
November 1987 levels and a requirement that would force companies to
renew all policies unless the risk to the policyholder increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
