<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Sun-TimesTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0220 12-05 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sun-Times Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0220,0324</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: TOPS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with ratification. Picks up 6th
graf pvs bg'ng, The pay ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newsroom employees at the Chicago Sun-Times voted
overwhelmingly Monday night to approve a new 3-year labor contract
at the city's second-largest newspaper, a union leader said.
   The vote among reporters, photographers and other editorial
staffers was 132-26, said reporter Tom Gibbons, chairman of the
Chicago Newspaper Guild's Sun-Times unit.
   Earlier Monday, the guild's executive director said ratification
of the contract would be a step toward better relations between the
workers and management.
   ``During the course of negotiations, both sides said they would
like to have peace,'' Jerry Minkkinen said. ``If the membership
ratifies, we will try to make sure that happens.''
   The settlement, worked out last Friday moments after a strike was
set to begin, includes a $500 payment on Jan. 1 and raises of 3
percent in each of the following two years.
   The pay scale at the newspaper currently ranges from $625 a week
for starting reporters to $895 for reporters with five-years'
experience.
   Union and management initially agreed to a contract on Nov. 22,
but snags developed over pension formulas and the 250 guild members
sent their bargainers back to the table.
   The negotiators emerged with a second tentative contract shortly
after a noon strike deadline Friday. The agreement was nearly
identical to the first pact, but pension benefits were increased by
6 percent and other minor changes were made.
   The night city editor's slot will be exempt from union coverage
and the $500 payment will be made Jan. 1, instead of July 1.
   Newsroom employees have been working without a contract since
June 1.
   The Sun-Times has an estimated circulation of 605,000 daily and
614,000 on Sunday. Its competitor, Chicago Tribune, has an estimated
circulation of 765,000 daily and 1.11 million on Sunday.
</TEXT>
