<1ST_LINE>u f BC-IBM-Lowe     12-05 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-IBM-Lowe,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key IBM Manager Goes to Xerox, Paper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key executive of International Business
Machines Corp. has resigned to head product planning, development
and manufacturing at rival Xerox Corp., according to a published
report.
   The New York Times, in Tuesday's editions, said William C. Lowe,
47, had served as a lightning rod for criticism of IBM's personal
computer marketing strategy.
   Lowe, who resigned Monday as president of IBM's Entry Systems
Division, was the architect of the computer giant's 1981 entry into
the personal computer market, the Times said.
   In recent years, IBM's personal computer line has been battered
by competition from clone machines, the paper noted.
   IBM announced Monday that James A. Cannavino, a vice president,
has been named president of the Entry Systems Division to replace
Lowe. Cannavino will report to Richard T. Gerstner, a vice president
and the general manager of IBM's Personal Systems division.
   Cannavino had been president of the company's Data Systems
Division.
   In addition, a new Advanced Workstations Division will be headed
by Vice President Nicholas M. Donofrio, who also will report to
Gerstner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
